= Phillip |title= Quantifying immigrant diversity in Europe |journal= Ethnic and Racial Studies |volume= 37|issue=11 |pages= 2055\u20132070 |doi= 10.1080/01419870.2013.809131|year= 2014 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Nagayoshi |first=Kikuko |date= |title=Anti-immigration attitudes in different welfare states: Do types of labor market policies matter? |url= |journal=International Journal of Comparative Sociology |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Modood |first=Tariq |date=2014 |title=Understanding 'Death of Multiculturalism' discourse means understanding multiculturalism |url= |journal=Journal of Multicultural Discourses |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |date=2016 |title= Immigration, free movement and the EU referendum |url= |journal= National Institute Economic Review |volume=236 |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |last= Nagayoshi |first= Kikuko |last2= Hjerm |first2= Mikael |date=2015 |title= Anti-immigration attitudes in different welfare states: Do types of labor market policies matter? |url= |journal= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Andersson |first=Hans |date=2016 |title=Liberal Intergovernmentalism, spillover and supranational immigration policy |url= |journal=Cooperation and Conflict |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=38\u201354 |doi= 10.1177/0010836715597945|access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |last= Weber |first= Hannes |date=2015 |title=National and regional proportion of immigrants and perceived threat of immigration: A three-level analysis in Western Europe |url= |journal= International Journal of Comparative Sociology |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}\n* {{cite journal |last= Lozano |first=AA | display-authors=etal |title= Revisiting the European Union framework on immigrant integration: The European integration forum as a technology of agency |url= |journal= Ethnicities |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages= 556\u2013576 |doi=10.1177/1468796814528692 |access-date= |year=2014 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://frontex.europa.eu/trends-and-routes/migratory-routes-map/ Main migratory routes into the EU], updated by [[Frontex]]\n* [http://data.unhcr.org/mediterranean/regional.php Sea arrivals to Southern Europe], updated by [[UNHCR]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908133013/http://missingmigrants.iom.int/en/ Missing migrants project], data on arrivals by sea and fatalities by [[International Organization for Migration|IOM]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-34131911 BBC News, EU migration: Crisis in graphics], 18 February 2016\n* [http://graphics.thomsonreuters.com/15/migrants/index.html Europe's migration crisis], graphics by [[Reuters]]\n* [http://www.lucify.com/the-flow-towards-europe/ Interactive map and graphic showing the flow of asylum seekers to European countries over time]\n* [http://www.cfr.org/migration/europes-migration-crisis/p32874 Europe's Migration Crisis], backgrounder by the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]\n* [http://www.mapreport.com/countries/european_migrant_crisis.html European Migrant Crisis Timeline]\n* [https://www.business-of-migration.com/migration-today/europe-s-refugee-conundrums/ Europe's Refugee Conundrums]\n* [http://www.refugeeroads.com Refugee Roads \u2013 Documenting a bicycle tour along the Balkan route]\n* [https://www.thenation.com/article/europes-refugee-crisis-was-made-in-america/ Europe\u2019s Refugee Crisis Was Made in America]\n\n{{European migrant crisis}}\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:European migrant crisis| ]]\n[[Category:Migrant crises]]\n[[Category:2010s in Europe|Migrant crisis]]\n[[Category:2010s in Iraq]]\n[[Category:2010s in Libya]]\n[[Category:2010s in politics]]\n[[Category:2010s in Syria]]\n[[Category:2010s in the European Union]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of the Libyan Civil War (2011)]]\n[[Category:Arab diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Consequences of the Iraqi Civil War]]\n[[Category:Consequences of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to Europe]]\n[[Category:Refugees of the Arab Winter]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{About|the 2010s migrant crisis|the 1940s migration and refugees developments|World War II evacuation and expulsion}}\n{{See also|Timeline of the European migrant crisis}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Migration to Europe since 2014|2=Talk:European migrant crisis#Requested move 27 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues |\n{{Inadequate lead|date=March 2020}}\n{{Very long|rps=147|date=March 2020}}\n{{Copy edit |date=March 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize |date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{image frame|content={{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Map of the European Migrant Crisis 2015.png{{!}}Asylum applications in the European Union (EU) and European Free Trade Association (EFTA) states between 1 January and 30 June 2015 according to Eurostat data\n| photo2a= LE Eithne Operation Triton.jpg{{!}}Operation Triton: Irish Naval Service personnel from the L\u00c9 Eithne (P31) rescuing migrants, 15 June 2015\n| photo2b= 20151030 Syrians and Iraq refugees arrive at Skala Sykamias Lesvos Greece 2.jpg{{!}}Syrian and Iraqi immigrants getting off a boat from Turkey on the Greek island of Lesbos. A small boat in water, with land on the horizon behind. Many people are on its outside in orange life jackets, some carrying inner tubes as well. A few are in the water swimming toward the camera. In the foreground a man in a red and black wetsuit has his hand out to them.\n| photo3a= Manifestacio_barcelona_volem_acollir.jpg{{!}}Protest \"Volem acollir\" (\"We want to welcome\") took place in Barcelona on 18 February 2017 and became the biggest pro-refugee demonstration in Europe\n| photo3b= Flashmob_gegen_M\u00e4nnergewalt,_K\u00f6ln_2016_-4384.jpg{{!}}Protesters gather outside Cologne Cathedral after New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany, January 2016\n| size = 270\n| spacing = 1\n| color = #FFFFFF\n| border = 3\n| color_border = gray\n| text = Map of Crisis {{efn|Data for the rest of the year 2015 can be found in the Eurostat ''Asylum quarterly report''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Asylum_quarterly_report|title=Asylum quarterly report \u2013 Statistics Explained|website=ec.europa.eu}}</ref>}}, [[Operation Triton]], Refugees at Skala Sykamias Lesvos, Protesters at [[Protest \u00abVolem acollir\u00bb|\"Volem acollir\" (\"We want to welcome\")]], Protesters after [[New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany|assaults in Germany]]\n| text_background = #FFDEAD\n}}\n| width = 278\n}}\nThe '''European migrant crisis''',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32395181|title=Europe migrant crisis|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 November 2015|date=2015-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The battle over the words used to describe migrants |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-34061097|first=Camila|last=Ruz|work=BBC News|date=28 August 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Europe's Migration Crisis |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/migration|work=Financial Times|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Refugees or migrants \u2013 what's in a word? |url=http://blogs.ft.com/the-world/2015/09/refugees-or-migrants-whats-in-a-word/|first=Gideon|last=Rachman|work=Financial Times|date=3 September 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=European migrant crisis: A country-by-country glance |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/04/europe/migrant-crisis-country-by-country/|publisher=CNN|first=Laura|last=Smith-Spark|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> also known as the '''refugee crisis''',<ref>\"[http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/european-refugee-crisis-worsens-in-mediterranean-a-964304.html Europe's African Refugee Crisis: Is the Boat Really Full?]\". ''[[Der Spiegel]]''. 15 April 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UNHCR chief issues key guidelines for dealing with Europe's refugee crisis |url=http://www.unhcr.org/55e9793b6.html |publisher=UNHCR}}\"This is a primarily refugee crisis, not only a migration phenomenon\".</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=European Refugee Crisis 2015: Why So Many People Are Fleeing The Middle East And North Africa |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/european-refugee-crisis-2015-why-so-many-people-are-fleeing-middle-east-north-africa-2081454 |work=International Business Times |date=3 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What You Need to Know About Europe's Refugee Crisis: Q&A |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-08/what-you-need-to-know-about-europe-s-refugee-crisis-q-a |work=Bloomberg |date=8 September 2015}}</ref> was a period characterised by high numbers of people arriving in the [[European Union]] (EU) from across the [[Mediterranean Sea]] or overland through [[Southeast Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=EU migrant crisis: facts and figures {{!}} News {{!}} European Parliament |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/headlines/society/20170629STO78630/eu-migrant-crisis-facts-and-figures |website=europarl.europa.eu |accessdate=28 March 2019 |language=en |date=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34131911|title=Migrant crisis: Migration to Europe explained in seven charts|date=4 March 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=29 May 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[migrant crisis]] was part of a pattern of increased [[immigration to Europe]] from other continents which began in the mid-20th century.<ref name=SRI /> Between January 2015 and March 2016, according to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]], the top three nationalities among over one million [[Mediterranean Sea]] arrivals were [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|Syrian refugees]] (46.7%), [[Afghan refugees]] (20.9%) and [[Refugees of Iraq|Iraqi refugees]] (9.4%).<ref>{{Cite journal|date=31 March 2016|title=Monthly Arrivals by Nationality to Greece, Italy and Spain|url=http://data.unhcr.org/mediterranean/documents.php?page=1&view=grid&Type%5B%5D=3&Search=%23monthly%23|journal=Refugees/Migrants Emergency Response \u2013 Mediterranean|doi=|pmid=|access-date=14 May 2016}}</ref> [[Opposition to immigration#Europe|Opposition to immigration in many European countries]] appeared to result partly from the socio-economic threat they were perceived to represent.<ref name=SRI>{{cite journal|last1=Marozzi|first1=Marco|title=Construction, Robustness Assessment and Application of an Index of Perceived Level of Socio-economic Threat from Immigrants: A Study of 47 European Countries and Regions|journal=Social Indicators Research|volume=128|pages=413\u2013437|date=2015|doi=10.1007/s11205-015-1037-z}}</ref> \n\nThe majority of people arriving in Italy and Greece especially have been from countries mired in war ([[Syrian civil war|Syrian civil war (2011\u2013present)]], [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]], [[Iraqi conflict (2003\u2013present)]]) or which otherwise are considered to be '[[Refugee crisis#Modern and contemporary refugee crises|refugee-producing]]' and for whom [[Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees|international protection]] is needed. However, a smaller proportion is from elsewhere, and for many of these individuals, the term '[[migrant]]' would be correct. [[Immigrant]]s (a person from a non-EU country establishing his or her usual residence in the territory of an EU country for a period that is, or is expected to be, at least twelve months) include [[asylum seeker]]s and [[economic migrant]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNHCR viewpoint: 'Refugee' or 'migrant' \u2013 Which is right? |url=http://www.unhcr.org/55df0e556.html |publisher=UNHCR}}</ref> Some research suggested that record population growth in Africa and the Middle East was one of the drivers of the crisis,<ref>{{cite news|title=Population growth is part of migrant crisis|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/population-growth-is-part-of-migrant-crisis-1.2366757}}</ref> and it was also suggested that [[global warming]] could increase migratory pressures in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Devastating climate change could lead to 1m migrants a year entering EU by 2100|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/dec/21/devastating-climate-change-could-see-one-million-migrants-a-year-entering-eu-by-2100|accessdate=24 December 2018|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2017-12-21|last1=Correspondent|first1=Fiona Harvey Environment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Want To Reduce Migration? Spend Money On Climate Change, Not Border Security|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/freylindsay/2018/11/30/want-to-reduce-migration-spend-money-on-climate-change-not-border-security|accessdate=24 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A provocative new study says climate change will make Europe's migrant crisis even worse|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/21/climate-change-will-drive-more-migration-to-europe-study-asserts/|accessdate=24 December 2018}}</ref> In rare cases, immigration has been a cover for [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) [[Refugees_as_weapons#Migration Infiltration|militants disguised as refugees]] or migrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-germany-security-idUSKCN0VE0XL|title=German spy agency says ISIS sending fighters disguised as refugees|date=5 February 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=29 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/how-europes-migrant-crisis-became-an-opportunity-for-isis/2016/04/21/ec8a7231-062d-4185-bb27-cc7295d35415_story.html|title=Tracing the path of four terrorists sent to Europe by the Islamic State|date=22 April 2016|work=Washington Post|access-date=25 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nMost of the migrants came from regions south and east of Europe, including the [[Greater Middle East]] and [[Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34173252|title=Migrant crisis: Explaining the exodus from the Balkans|last=Delauney|first=Guy|date=8 September 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=29 May 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> Of the migrants arriving in Europe by sea in 2015, 58% were males over 18 years of age (77% of adults), 17% were females over 18 (22% of adults) and the remaining 25% were under 18.<ref name=\"bsUNHCR2015\"/> By religious affiliation, the majority of entrants were [[Muslim]], with a small component of non-Muslim minorities (including [[Yazidi]]s, [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] and [[Mandean]]s). The number of deaths at sea rose to record levels in April 2015, when five boats carrying almost 2,000 migrants to Europe [[List of migrant vessel incidents on the Mediterranean Sea|sank in the Mediterranean Sea]], with a combined death toll estimated at more than 1,200 people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mediterranean Crisis 2015 at six months: refugee and migrant numbers highest on record|url=http://www.unhcr.org/5592b9b36.html|work=UNHCR|date=1 July 2015}}</ref> The shipwrecks took place in a context of ongoing conflicts and refugee crises in several Asian and African countries, which increased the total number of forcibly [[displaced people]] worldwide at the end of 2014 to almost 60 million, the highest level since [[World War II]].<ref name=\"UNHCRtrends\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/world/europe/a-mass-migration-crisis-and-it-may-yet-get-worse.html|title=A Mass Migration Crisis, and It May Yet Get Worse|author=Rod Nordland|newspaper=The New York Times|date=31 October 2015|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Migrant arrivals versus \"illegal\" border crossings ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Table 1. New \"illegal\" migrants, versus total \"illegal\" border crossings\n! \n! Migrants&nbsp;from [[Asia]] or [[Africa]] newly arriving in the [[European Union|EU]], detected but not over an official [[Border checkpoint|border-crossing point]] (BCP)\n! Same&nbsp;from [[Kosovo]]\n! Total new migrants arrived to the EU, detected but not over an official BCP\n! \n! Seasonal, circular, workers \"illegally\" crossing from [[Albania]] to [[Greece]]\n! Detected \"illegal\" EU external border crossings by migrants from Greece/[[Bulgaria]] through&nbsp;western [[Balkans]]&nbsp;heading for [[European Union#Economy|northwestern]] EU member states\n! \n! Total detected \"illegal\" crossings of EU external borders\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2011\n| \n| \n| 131,000<ref name=Frontex2012,p4+14/>\n| \n| 5,000<ref name=Frontex2012,p4+14>{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2012.pdf#page=6 |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2012 |page=4, 14 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=April 2012}}</ref>\n| 5,000<ref name=Frontex2012,p4+14/>\n| \n| 141,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2012\n| \n| \n| 60,500<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| \n| 5,500<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| 6,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| \n| 72,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2013\n| \n| \n| 78,500<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| \n| 8,500<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| 20,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n| \n| 107,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2014\n| 231,000<ref name=Frontex2015,p.19,22,24\">{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2015.pdf#page=21 |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2015 |page=19, 22, 24 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n| circa 21,000<ref name=Frontex2015,p.19,22,24\"/>\n| circa 252,000<ref name=sum.col.1+2>The sum of the mentioned \"Migrants from Asia or Africa\u2026\" and \"[Migrants] from Kosovo\u2026\", left in this table</ref> \n| \n| 9,000<ref name=Frontex2015,p.19,22,24\"/>\n| circa 22,000<ref name=Frontex2015,p.19,22,24\"/>\n| \n| 283,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf#page=19 |page=5, 17 |title=Risk Analysis for 2016 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=March 2016}}</ref>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2015\n| 1,049,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.16,18,20>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf#page=18 |page=16, 18, 20 |title=Risk Analysis for 2016 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=March 2016}}</ref>\n| circa&nbsp;10,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.19/>\n| circa&nbsp;1,059,000<ref name=sum.col.1+2/>\n| \n| 9,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.16,18,20/>\n| circa&nbsp;754,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.19>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf#page=21 |page=19 |title=Risk Analysis for 2016 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=March 2016}}</ref>\n| \n| 1,822,000<ref name=Frontex2016,p.5,17/>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2016\n| 376,000<ref name=undetect>In addition to this number of 376,000 detected \"illegal\" migrants in 2016, [[European Border and Coast Guard Agency|Frontex]] presumed an increasing number of undetected migrants of this category. See: {{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2017.pdf#page=20 |title=Risk Analysis for 2017 |page=18-20 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=February 2017}}</ref>\n| --\n| 376,000<ref name=undetect/>\n| \n| 5,000<ref name=Frontex2017,p.18-20/>\n| 130,000<ref name=Frontex2017,p.18-20>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2017.pdf#page=20 |title=Risk Analysis for 2017 |page=18-20 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=February 2017}}</ref>\n| \n| 511,000<ref name=\"FrontexARA2017,p.6\">{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2017.pdf#page=8 |title=Risk Analysis for 2017 |page=6 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=February 2017}}</ref>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2017\n| 186,000<ref name=Frontex2018,p18>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Risk_Analysis/Risk_Analysis_for_2018.pdf#page=20 |title=Risk Analysis for 2018 |page=18, map |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=February 2018}}</ref>\n| --\n| 186,000<ref name=Frontex2018,p18/>\n| \n| 6,000<ref name=Frontex2018,p18/>\n| 12,000<ref name=Frontex2018,p18/>\n| \n| 204,000<ref name=Frontex2018,p18/> \n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2018\n| 139,700<ref name=Frontex2019,p16>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Risk_Analysis/Risk_Analysis_for_2019.pdf#page=18|title=Risk Analysis for 2019 | page=16 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=February 2019}}</ref>\n| \n| 139,700<ref name=Frontex2019,p16/>\n| \n| 4,500<ref name=Frontex2019,p16/>\n| 5,900<ref name=Frontex2019,p16/>\n| \n| 150,100<ref name=Frontex2019,p16/>\n|- align=\"right\"\n| 2019\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|} \n\nThe [[European Union|EU]] [[European Border and Coast Guard Agency|Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex)]] uses the terms \"illegal\" and \"irregular\" border crossings for crossings of an EU external border but not at an official [[Border checkpoint|border-crossing point]] (BCP).<ref name=Frontex2016,p.22>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf#page=24 |page=22 |title=Risk Analysis for 2016 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=March 2016}}</ref> These include the entrance into Europe of people rescued at sea and brought to land by EU citizens.<ref name=Frontex2016,p.20>{{cite web |url=https://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf#page=22 |page=20 |title=Risk Analysis for 2016 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=March 2016}}</ref> The total number of such illegal EU external border crossings can be higher than the number of migrants newly illegally arriving in the EU in a certain year, as becomes clear in Table 1, especially for the years 2015 and 2016. News media sometimes misrepresent these correct figures as given by Frontex.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n== Causes of increased migration in 2014 and 2015 ==\n=== 2014 ===\nAfter October 2013, when Italy started rescuing Africans from the Mediterranean Sea with a rescue program called 'Mare Nostrum' ('Our Sea'), the numbers of refugees arriving in Europe began to rise.<ref name=Spiegel>\"[http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/european-refugee-crisis-worsens-in-mediterranean-a-964304.html Europe's African Refugee Crisis: Is the Boat Really Full?]\". ''[[Der Spiegel]]''. 15 April 2014. Retrieved 17 March 2020.</ref>\n \n=== 2015 ===\nFactors cited as immediate triggers or causes of the sudden and massive increase in migrant numbers in the summer of 2015 along the Eastern Mediterranean and Western Balkan route (Turkey-Greece-North Macedonia-Serbia-Hungary) include:\n\n==== Cost of migration ====\nThe opening of the North Macedonia route enabled migrants from the Middle East to take very short, inexpensive voyages from the coast of Turkey to the Greek Islands, instead of the far longer, more perilous, and far more expensive voyage from Libya to Italy. According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', in addition to reducing danger, this lowered the cost from around $5\u20136,000 to $2\u20133,000.<ref name=EightSlyReasons/>\n\n==== Balkan route  ====\nOn 18 June 2015 the government of [[North Macedonia]] announced that it was changing its policy on migrants entering the country illegally. Previously, migrants were forbidden from transiting North Macedonia, causing those who chose to do so to take perilous, clandestine modes of transit, such as walking along railroad tracks at night. Beginning in June, migrants were given three-day, temporary asylum permits, enabling them to travel by train and road.<ref name=MacedoniaAllows>{{cite news|title=Macedonia Allows Migrants to Legitimately Transit Country|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/macedonia-migrants-asylum-law/2828577.html|accessdate=18 September 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=18 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119090246/http://www.voanews.com/content/macedonia-migrants-asylum-law/2828577.html|archive-date=19 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=EightSlyReasons>{{cite news |last=Sly |first=Liz |authorlink=Liz Sly |title=8 reasons Europe's refugee crisis is happening now|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2015/09/18/8-reasons-why-europes-refugee-crisis-is-happening-now/|accessdate=18 September 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=18 September 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the summer of 2015, several thousand people passed through North Macedonia and Serbia every day, and more than 100,000 had done so by July. <ref>[http://frontex.europa.eu/trends-and-routes/migratory-routes-map/ Frontex: Migratory Routes Map] (period data: choose \"eastern-borders-route\")</ref> Hungary started building the border fence with Serbia. Both states were overwhelmed organizationally and economically. In August 2015, a police crackdown on migrants crossing from Greece failed in North Macedonia, causing the police to instead turn their attention to diverting migrants north, into Serbia.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/>  On 18 October 2015, Slovenia began restricting admission to 2,500 migrants per day, stranding migrants in Croatia as well as Serbia and North Macedonia.<ref name=CroatiaSlovenia3/><ref name=CroatiaSlovenia4/> The humanitarian conditions were catastrophic; Refugees were waiting for illegal helpers at illegal assembly points without any infrastructure.<ref name=\"presse 20150209 report\">Thomas Roser: [http://diepresse.com/home/panorama/welt/4659013/Reportage_Der-Exodus-aus-dem-Kosovo ''Reportage: Der Exodus aus dem Kosovo.''] Die Presse, 9. Februar 2015</ref><ref name=\"profil 20150209 report\">Gregor Mayer: [http://www.profil.at/ausland/stacheldraht-ungarn-absperrung-grenze-serbien-5839226 ''Reportage: Unterwegs auf der Westbalkan-Route von Serbien nach Ungarn.''] Profil, 1. September 2015</ref>\n\n==== Syria ====\nSyrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]] blamed [[Europe]] and the [[United States]] for the migrant crisis, saying most of the refugees are fleeing the \"terrorism\" that he accuses the West of fomenting by supporting elements of the [[Syrian opposition]]. Meanwhile, the Syrian government announced increased military conscription, and simultaneously made it easier for Syrians to obtain passports, leading Middle East policy experts to speculate that he was implementing a policy to encourage opponents of his regime to \"leave the country\".<ref name=EightSlyReasons/>\n\nNATO's four-star General in the United States Air Force commander in Europe stated on the issue of indiscriminate weapons used by Bashar al-Assad, and the non-precision use of weapons by the Russian forces \u2013 are the reason which cause refugees to be on the move.<ref name=NATO>{{cite news |last1=Staff |title=NATO Commander: Russia uses Syrian refugees as 'weapon' against West |url=https://www.dw.com/en/nato-commander-russia-uses-syrian-refugees-as-weapon-against-west/a-19086285 |accessdate=20 August 2019 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=2 March 2016}}</ref> Gen. [[Philip Breedlove]] accused Russia and the Assad regime of \"deliberately weaponizing migration in an attempt to overwhelm European structures and break European resolve\".<ref name=NATO />\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Immigration to Europe}}\n[[File:Immigration in the EU.png|thumb|Immigration of non-EU nationals (green),<ref name=\"Immigration in the EU\"/> asylum applicants (orange)<ref>{{cite web |title=Asylum and first time asylum applicants by citizenship, age and sex Annual aggregated data (rounded) |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do |publisher=EUROSTAT}}</ref> and illegal border-crossings (blue)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2015.pdf#14 |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2015 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=27 April 2015}}</ref> in the European Union, 2010\u20132014]]\n[[File:Migranti sbarcati in Italia 1997-2016.png|thumb|Migrants arriving in Italy by sea, 1997\u20132015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ismu.org/irregolari-e-sbarchi-presenze/|title=Sbarchi e richieste di asilo 1997\u20132014|publisher=Fondazione Ismu}}</ref>]]\n\nBetween 2007 and 2011, large numbers of migrants from the Middle East and Africa crossed between Turkey and Greece, leading Greece and the European Border Protection agency Frontex to upgrade border controls.<ref name=\"bbcsep2014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-24521614 |title=Mapping Mediterranean migration |publisher=BBC |date=15 September 2014}}</ref> In 2012, immigrant influx into Greece by land decreased by 95 percent after the construction of a fence on that part of the Greek\u2013Turkish frontier which does not follow the course of the [[Maritsa]] River.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_17/12/2012_474782 |title=Greece completes anti-migrant fence at Turkish legends border |work=[[Kathimerini]] |date=17 December 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Bulgaria followed by upgrading a border fence to prevent migrant flows through Turkey.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/01/14/us-bulgaria-turkey-fence-idUSKBN0KN1JG20150114 |title=Bulgaria to extend fence at Turkish border to bar refugee influx |date=14 January 2015 |agency=[[Reuters]] |first=Angel |last=Krasimirov}}</ref><ref name=\"Minat\">*{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5f1e33449630459cb16e14c8f8c89263/search-under-way-700-migrants-lost-sea-south-italy |title=Survivor: Smugglers locked hundreds in hold of capsized boat |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite news |title=Analisi: Paolo Gentiloni |url=https://pagellapolitica.it/dichiarazioni/analisi/5221/paolo-gentiloni |language=Italian |newspaper=Pagella Politica |date=22 February 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/10/04/witness-boat-migrants-used-bottles-to-stay-afloat/2922215/ |title=Witness: Boat migrants used bottles to stay afloat |date=4 October 2013 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite news |title='Dozens feared dead' off Lampedusa as migrant boat capsizes |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-24499890 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=21 April 2015 |date=11 October 2013 }}\n* {{cite news |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE74D02Z20110514 |agency=Reuters |title=Hundreds more migrants reach Italy from Africa |date=14 May 2011 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite web |title=Sbarchi al 2 marzo 2015 |url=http://www.ismu.org/irregolari-presenze/ |website=ISMU |accessdate=21 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143337/http://www.ismu.org/irregolari-presenze/ |archivedate=27 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite news |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/654332/italian-navy-rescues-over-1000-migrants-from-countries-including-pakistan/ |agency=Reuters |title=Italian navy rescues Pakistani migrants from boats |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite web |title=Lampedusa and Immigration at the Mediterranean: Tragedies, Dilemmas and International Conflicts. A Crossroad for Europe. |url=http://www.festivaldeuropa.eu/lampedusa-and-immigration-at-the-mediterranean-tragedies-dilemmas-and-international-conflicts-a-crossroad-for-europe/ |publisher=Festival d'Europa |accessdate=21 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906212234/http://www.festivaldeuropa.eu/lampedusa-and-immigration-at-the-mediterranean-tragedies-dilemmas-and-international-conflicts-a-crossroad-for-europe/ |archive-date=6 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-24583286 |publisher=BBC |title=Why is EU struggling with migrants and asylum? |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite web |title=Updated: Italy rescues 1,500 migrants off Libyan coast, pregnant migrant brought to Malta |url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/51477/italy_rescues_300_migrants_pregnant_migrant_brought_to_malta |newspaper=[[Malta Today]] |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-12743356 |publisher=BBC |title=Italy blocks ferry of Moroccans fleeing Libya |date=15 March 2011 |accessdate=21 April 2015 }}</ref> \n\nBetween 2010 and 2013, around 1.4 million non-EU nationals, asylum seekers and refugees not included, immigrated in the EU each year, while around 750,000 of such non-EU nationals emigrated from the EU in those years, resulting in around 650,000 net immigration each year, but decreasing from 750,000 to 540,000 between 2010 and 2013.<ref name=\"Immigration in the EU\">{{cite web |title=Immigration in the EU |url=http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/home-affairs/e-library/docs/infographics/immigration/migration-in-eu-infographic_en.pdf |publisher=European Commission}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2014, the number of asylum applications in the EU peaked in 1992 (672,000), 2001 (424,000) and 2013 (431,000). In 2014 it reached 626,000.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |title=Asylum statistics |url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Asylum_statistics |publisher=EUROSTAT |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref> According to the [[UNHCR]], the EU countries with the biggest numbers of recognised refugees at the end of 2014 were France (252,264), Germany (216,973), Sweden (142,207) and the United Kingdom (117,161). No European state was among the top ten refugee-hosting countries in the world.<ref name=\"UNHCRtrends\"/>\n\nPrior to 2014, the number of [[Illegal entry|illegal border crossings]] detected by [[Frontex]] at the external borders of the EU peaked in 2011, with 141,051 total (sea and land combined).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2015.pdf |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2015 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Eurostat]], [[Member state of the European Union|EU member states]] received over 1.2 million first-time asylum applications in 2015, more than double that of the previous year. Four states (Germany, Hungary, Sweden and Austria) received around two-thirds of the EU's asylum applications in 2015, with Hungary, Sweden and Austria being the top recipients of asylum applications per capita.<ref name=\"asylum2015\" /> More than 1 million migrants crossed the [[Mediterranean Sea]] in 2015, considerably dropping to 364,000 in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/number-refugees-reaching-europe-plunged-2016-170106132732972.html|title=Number of refugees reaching Europe plunged in 2016|website=aljazeera.com}}</ref>  Numbers of arriving migrants fell again in 2017.<ref name=\"NebehayIOM\">{{cite news |last1=Nebehay |first1=Stephanie |title=Half as many migrants landed in Europe in 2017 as 2016: IOM |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-un/half-as-many-migrants-landed-in-europe-in-2017-as-2016-iom-idUSKBN1EU1KP |accessdate=16 July 2018 |work=Reuters |date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010 policy report ===\nIn 2010 the European Commission commissioned a study on the financial, political and legal implications of a relocation of migrants in Europe.<ref name=finalreport>{{cite web |title=Study on the Feasibility of Establishing a Mechanism for the Relocation of Beneficiaries of International Protection |url=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/e-library/docs/pdf/final_report_relocation_of_refugees_en.pdf |publisher=European Commission |accessdate=28 November 2018 |date=July 2010}}</ref> The report concluded that there were several options for dealing with the issues relating to migration within Europe, and that most member states favoured an \"ad hoc mechanism based on a pledging exercise among the Member States\".<ref name=finalreport/>\n\n=== Carriers' responsibility ===\nArticle 26 of the [[Schengen Convention]]<ref>[http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:42000A0922%2802%29:en:HTML Official Journal L 239, 22 September 2000]. ([[s:Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement|The Schengen acquis \u2013 Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement]])</ref> says that carriers which transport people into the Schengen area shall if they transport people who are refused entry into the Schengen Area, be responsible to pay for the return of the refused people, and pay penalties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carrieri sanctions |url=http://www.ecre.org/topics/areas-of-work/access-to-europe/7-carrier-sanctions.html |publisher=[[European Council on Refugees and Exiles]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310200237/http://www.ecre.org/topics/areas-of-work/access-to-europe/7-carrier-sanctions.html |archivedate=10 March 2016 }}</ref> Further clauses on this topic are found in EU directive 2001/51/EC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2001:187:0045:0046:EN:PDF|title=COUNCIL DIRECTIVE 2001/51/EC supplementing the provisions of Article 26 of the Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement}}</ref> This has had the effect that migrants without a visa are not allowed on aircraft, boats or trains going into the Schengen Area, so migrants without a visa have resorted to [[People smuggling|migrant smugglers]].<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/refugee-crisis-smugglers-offer-discount-refugees-willing-cross-bad-weather-1526441 Refugee crisis: Smugglers offer 'Bad weather discount' to migrants] (International Business Times, 25 October 2015)</ref> Humanitarian visas are in general not given to refugees who want to apply for asylum.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/report/2015/11/16/europes-refugee-crisis/agenda-action Europe\u2019s Refugee Crisis, An Agenda for Action] (Human Rights Watch, 16 November 2015)</ref>\n\nThe laws on [[migrant smuggling]] ban helping migrants to pass any national border if the migrants are without a visa or other permission to enter. This has caused many airlines to check for visas and refuse passage to migrants without visas, including through international flights inside the Schengen Area. After being refused air passage, many migrants then attempt to travel overland to their destination country. According to a study carried out for the European Parliament, \"penalties for carriers, who assume some of the control duties of the European police services, either block asylum-seekers far from Europe's borders or force them to pay more and take greater risks to travel illegally\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Analysis of the external dimension of the EU's asylum and immigration policies|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meetdocs/2004_2009/documents/dt/619/619330/619330en.pdf|publisher=European Parliament}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actnownews.com/refugee-crisis/|title=Way to Future of the Refugee crisis|work=Act Now News|accessdate=29 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114085750/http://actnownews.com/refugee-crisis/|archivedate=14 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== EU's management of the crisis ==\n=== Political positions ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote= Europe needs to fulfil its humanitarian duty, helping those fleeing for their lives, and as a Christian-Democrat, I want to reiterate that is not Christian rights, but human rights that Europe invented. But we also need to better secure our external borders and make sure that asylum rules are used properly and not abused. \n|source= \u2014  [[Manfred Weber]], leader of the [[European People's Party]] in the European Parliament.\n|align=centre\n|width=30%\n|quoted=1\n }}\n[[File:Praha, V\u00e1clavsk\u00e9 n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed, \u0159\u00edjnov\u00e1 demonstrace proti p\u0159ijet\u00ed uprchl\u00edk\u016f, Tomio Okamura.jpg|thumb|Czech politician [[Tomio Okamura]] speaks at the anti-immigration rally in [[Prague]], 17 October 2015]]\n[[File:Salvini Centinaio Giorgetti.jpg|thumb|right|[[Matteo Salvini]] with League's delegation at the [[Quirinal Palace]] in April 2018]]\n[[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]] identifies a \"double blackmail\" in the debate on the migrant crisis: those who argue Europe's borders should be entirely opened to refugees, and those who argue that the borders should be closed completely.<ref>{{cite book |last= \u017di\u017eek|first= Slavoj|date= 2016|title= Against the Double Blackmail|url= |location= London|publisher= Allen Lane|page= |isbn= |author-link= \u017di\u017eek}}</ref>{{page number needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[European Commission]]er for Migration, Home Affairs and Citizenship, [[Dimitris Avramopoulos]], said that the European Commission \"does not care about the political cost\" of its handling of the migration crisis, because it's there for five years to do its job \"with vision, responsibility and commitment\" and what drives it \"is not to be re-elected\", and invited European national leaders to do likewise and stop worrying about reelection.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/eu/11896827/Cost-of-migration-crisis-means-nothing-to-us-says-top-EU-official.html Cost of migration crisis means nothing to us, says top EU official]\". ''The Daily Telegraph''. 28 September 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=EU migration chief: Forget the 'political cost'|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/migration-news-political-europe-cost/|work=Politico|date=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2015, according to ''The New York Times'', [[Angela Merkel]], German [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] and leader of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]], in some of her strongest language theretofore on the immigrant crisis, warned that freedom of travel and open borders among the 28 member states of the EU could be jeopardised if they did not agree on a shared response to this crisis.<ref name=StrainedOpenBorders/>\n\n[[Nicolas Sarkozy]], President of [[The Republicans (France)|the Republicans]] and former French president, compared EU migrant plan to \"mending a burst pipe by spreading water round the house while leaving the leak untouched\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/nicolas-sarkozy/11686558/Nicolas-Sarkozy-compares-EU-migrant-plan-to-fixing-a-burst-water-pipe-with-water.html |title=Nicolas Sarkozy compares EU migrant plan to 'fixing a burst water pipe with water' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=18 October 2015|last1=Samuel |first1=Henry }}</ref> Following German Chancellor Angela Merkel's decision to allow tens of thousands of people to enter Germany, Sarkozy criticised her, saying that it would attract even greater numbers of people to Europe, where a significant part would \"inevitably\" end up in France due to the EU's free movement policies and the French welfare state. He also demanded that the Schengen agreement on borderless travel should be replaced with a new agreement providing border checks for non-EU citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2015/09/09/01002-20150909ARTFIG00427-crise-des-migrants-le-plan-de-sarkozy.php |title=Crise des migrants : le plan de Sarkozy |trans-title=Migrant crisis: Sarkozy's plan|work=Le Figaro|language=French|date=9 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[Italian Prime Minister]] and [[List of Secretaries of the Democratic Party (Italy)|Secretary]] of the Italian [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] [[Matteo Renzi]] said the EU should forge a single European policy on asylum.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34106343 |title=Migrant crisis: Austria holds suspected people smugglers |work=BBC News |date=31 August 2015}}</ref> [[French Prime Minister]] [[Manuel Valls]] of the French [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] stated, \"There must be close cooperation between the European Commission and member states as well as candidate members.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.euronews.com/en/312599/ |title=French PM Valls urges EU solidarity amid unprecedented migrant crisis |publisher=euronews.com |date=31 August 2015 |access-date=1 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901010323/http://m.euronews.com/en/312599/ |archive-date=1 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Sergei Stanishev]], President of the [[Party of European Socialists]], stated:\n\n{{Quote\n |quote= At this moment, more people in the world are displaced by conflict than at any time since the Second World War. ... Many die on the approach to Europe \u2013 in the Mediterranean \u2013 yet others perish on European soil. ... As social democrats the principle of solidarity is the glue that keeps our family together. ... We need a permanent European mechanism for fairly distributing asylum-seekers in European member states. ... War, poverty and the stark rise in inequality are global, not local problems. As long as we do not address these causes globally, we cannot deny people the right to look for a more hopeful future in a safer environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pes.eu/eu_response_to_direrefugee_crisis_urgently_needed|title=European response to dire refugee crisis urgently needed|work=Party of European Socialists|accessdate=19 September 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', the appeal of [[Eurosceptic]] politicians has increased.<ref name=Troianoski>{{cite news |last1=Troianovski |first1=Anton |title=Migration Crisis Pits EU's East Against West |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/migration-crisis-pits-eus-east-against-west-1439957453 |accessdate=19 August 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=19 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Nigel Farage]], leader of the British anti-EU [[United Kingdom Independence Party]] and co-leader of the eurosceptic [[Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy]] group, blamed the EU \"and Germany in particular\" for giving \"huge incentives for people to come to the European Union by whatever means\" and said that this would make deaths more likely. He claimed that the EU's Schengen agreement on open borders had failed and that Islamists could exploit the situation and enter Europe in large numbers, saying that \"one of the ISIL terrorist suspects who committed the first atrocity against holidaymakers in [[Tunisia]] has been seen getting off a boat onto Italian soil\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nigel-farage/11844290/Thousands-of-Isil-fighters-could-use-migrant-crisis-to-flood-into-Europe-Nigel-Farage-warns.html |title=Video: Thousands of Isis fighters could use migrant crisis to 'flood' into Europe, Nigel Farage warns \u2013 Telegraph |date=4 September 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nigel-farage/11836131/Nigel-Farage-EU-has-opened-doors-to-migration-exodus-of-biblical-proportions.html |title=Nigel Farage: EU has opened doors to migration exodus of biblical proportions |date=1 September 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph|last1=Wilkinson |first1=Michael }}</ref> In 2013, Farage had called on the UK government to accept more Syrian refugees,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/dec/29/nigel-farage-syrian-refugees-uk |title=Nigel Farage calls on government to let Syrian refugees into UK |newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 December 2013 }}</ref> before clarifying that those refugees should be Christian due to the existence of nearer places of refuge for Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|title=Nigel Farage rows back on call to grant asylum to Syrian refugees|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/dec/30/nigel-farage-asylum-syrian-refugees-christians|accessdate=20 September 2015|work=The Guardian|date=30 December 2013}}</ref>\n[[Marine Le Pen]], leader of the French far-right [[National Front (France)|National Front]] and co-president of the former [[Europe of Nations and Freedom]] (EMF) grouping, accused Germany of looking to hire \"slaves\" by opening its doors to large numbers of asylum seekers among a debate in Germany whether there should be exceptions to the recently introduced minimum wage law for refugees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.deregionales/baden-wuerttemberg/article145573021/BWIHK-Praesident-will-Mindestlohn-fuer-Fluechtlinge-aufweichen.html |title=BWIHK-Pr\u00e4sident will Mindestlohn f\u00fcr Fl\u00fcchtlinge aufweichen (BWIHK President wants to soften Minimum Wage Rules for Refugees) (in German) |work=Die Welt }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.n-tv.de/wirtschaft/Landkreise-wollen-Mindestlohn-senken-article15853956.html |title=Ausnahmen f\u00fcr Asylbewerber \u2013 Landkreise wollen Mindestlohn senken (Exceptions for Asylum Seekers \u2013 Organization of Districts wants to lower Minimum Wage) (in German) |work=N-TV.de}}</ref> Le Pen also accused Germany of imposing its immigration policy on the rest of the EU unilaterally.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/06/us-europe-migrants-france-farright-idUSKCN0R60TF20150906 |title=French far-right leader says Germany seeking 'slaves' in migrants |work=Reuters (US)|date=6 September 2015 }}</ref> Her comments were reported by the German<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/newsblog-zu-fluechtlingen-muenchen-stoesst-an-grenzen-seiner-aufnahmefaehigkeit/12282848.html |title=Newsblog zu Fl\u00fcchtlingen (in German) |work=Der Tagesspiegel}}</ref> and Austrian press,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://diepresse.com/home/politik/aussenpolitik/4814935/Le-Pen_Deutschland-sieht-in-Fluchtlingen-Sklaven- |title=Le Pen: Deutschland sieht in Fl\u00fcchtlingen \"Sklaven\" (in German) |work=Die Presse}}</ref> and were called \"abstruse claims\" by the online edition of ''[[Der Spiegel]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/front-national-unterstellt-deutschland-interesse-an-arbeitssklaven-a-1051675.html |title=Front National unterstellt Deutschland Interesse an Arbeitssklaven |work=Der Spiegel|date=6 September 2015 }}</ref> Centreright daily ''[[Die Welt]]'' wrote that she \"exploits the refugee crisis for anti-German propaganda\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article146112084/Berlin-will-mit-Fluechtlingen-Sklaven-rekrutieren.html |title=Berlin will mit Fl\u00fcchtlingen \"Sklaven rekrutieren\" (in German) |newspaper=Die Welt|date=7 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[Geert Wilders]], the leader of the Dutch [[Party for Freedom]] (a member of the former EMF grouping), who is known for his [[criticism of Islam]], called the influx of people an \"Islamic invasion\" during a debate in the Dutch parliament, speaking about \"masses of young men in their twenties with beards singing ''Allahu Akbar'' across Europe\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/10/us-europe-migrants-netherlands-idUSKCN0RA0WY20150910 |title=Wilders tells Dutch parliament refugee crisis is 'Islamic invasion' |work=Reuters (US)|date=10 September 2015 }}</ref> He also dismissed the idea that people arriving in Western Europe via the [[Balkans]] are genuine refugees, stating: \"Turkey, Greece, Macedonia, Serbia are safe countries. If you flee them then you are doing it for benefits and a house.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Wilders-tells-Dutch-parliament-refugee-crisis-is-Islamic-invasion-415828|title=Wilders tells Dutch parliament refugee crisis is 'Islamic invasion' |newspaper=Jerusalem Post}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial proposals ===\nAfter the migrant shipwreck on 19 April 2015, [[Italy's Premier]] [[Matteo Renzi]] spoke by telephone to French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] and to Maltese Prime Minister [[Joseph Muscat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasiciliaweb.it/articolo/128414/esteri/renzi-chiama-hollande-salvini-attacca-tragedia-annunciata |title=Renzi chiama Hollande Salvini: \"Tragedia annunciata\" |language=Italian |author=La Sicilia Multimedia |publisher=lasiciliaweb.it |accessdate=19 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907010136/http://www.lasiciliaweb.it/articolo/128414/esteri/renzi-chiama-hollande-salvini-attacca-tragedia-annunciata |archive-date=7 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.ilmattino.it/primopiano/cronaca/strage_migranti_renzi_vertice_ministri_ue/notizie/1305206.shtml |title=Renzi: \"Subito un vertice Ue, siamo pronti a bloccare la partenza dei barconi\" |language=Italian |work=Il Mattino |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> They agreed to call for an emergency meeting of European interior ministers to address the problem of migrant deaths. Renzi condemned human trafficking as a \"new slave trade\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32374027 |title=Italian PM Matteo Renzi condemns 'new slave trade' in Mediterranean |work=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> while Prime Minister Muscat said 19 April shipwreck was the \"biggest human tragedy of the last few years\". Hollande described people traffickers as \"terrorists\" who put migrant lives at risk. The [[German government]]'s representative for migration, refugees and integration, [[Aydan \u00d6zo\u011fuz]], said that with more migrants likely to arrive as the weather turned warmer, emergency rescue missions should be restored. \"It was an illusion to think that cutting off [[Operation Mare Nostrum|Mare Nostrum]] would prevent people from attempting this dangerous voyage across the Mediterranean\", she said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/migrants-ship-headed-for-italy-capsizes-north-of-libya-1.3039401 |title=Migrants' ship headed for Italy capsizes north of Libya |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=19 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BoatDisaster\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-32372351 |title=Med migrant boat disaster |date=18 April 2015 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref name=\"BoatDisaster\" /><ref name=\"EmergencyTalks\" /> [[Federica Mogherini]], [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|High Representative of the EU for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]], called for collective EU action ahead of a meeting in Luxembourg on Monday 20 April.<ref name=\"EmergencyTalks\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/eu-states-back-action-protect-migrants-mediterranean-mogherini-114546548.html |title=Europe should back action to protect migrants in Mediterranean: Mogherini |publisher=Reuters/Yahoo |date=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a press conference, Renzi confirmed that Italy had called an \"extraordinary European council\" meeting as soon as possible to discuss the tragedy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/prime-minister-matteo-renzi-defends-italys-response-migrants-drowning-mediterranean-1497254 |title=Prime Minister Matteo Renzi defends Italy's response to migrants drowning in the Mediterranean |newspaper=[[International Business Times UK]] |accessdate=19 April 2015|date=19 April 2015 }}</ref> various European leaders agreed with this idea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.antena3.com/noticias/mundo/naufraga-barco-700-inmigrantes-190-kilometros-lampedusa_2015041900016.html |title=Naufraga un pesquero con 700 inmigrantes a bordo cerca de la costa de Libia |publisher=Antena3.com |accessdate=19 April 2015|date=19 April 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/world/eu-s-tusk-considers/1794426.html |title=EU's Tusk considers special summit after migrants drown |publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |accessdate=19 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143419/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/mobile/world/eu-s-tusk-considers/1794426.html |archivedate=27 April 2015 }}</ref> Cameron tweeted on 20 April that he \"supported\" Renzi's \"call for an emergency meeting of EU leaders to find a comprehensive solution\" to the migrant crisis in the Mediterranean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/politics/2015/04/20/med-faces-humanitarian-crisis-renzi_f7f22df2-27a1-496e-8f96-481bbcff8a20.html |title=Med faces humanitarian crisis, not just wreck, says Renzi |publisher=ANSA.it |accessdate=20 April 2015|date=20 April 2015 }}</ref> He later confirmed that he would attend an emergency summit of European leaders on Thursday.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32382962 |title=Mediterranean migrant deaths: PM calls for action after boat disaster |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 April 2015 |date=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2015, the European Commission proposed a 10-point plan to tackle the crisis:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-4813_en.htm |title=European Commission \u2013 PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Joint Foreign and Home Affairs Council: Ten point action plan on migration |publisher=Europa (web portal) |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Reinforce the Joint Operations in the Mediterranean, namely [[Operation Triton|Triton]] and Poseidon, by increasing the financial resources and the number of assets. We will also extend their operational area, allowing us to intervene further, within the mandate of Frontex;\n* A systematic effort to capture and destroy vessels used by the smugglers. The positive results obtained with the Atalanta operation should inspire us to similar operations against smugglers in the Mediterranean;\n* [[Europol]], [[Frontex]], [[European Asylum Support Office|EASO]] and [[Eurojust]] will meet regularly and work closely to gather information on smugglers' modus operandi, to trace their funds and to assist in their investigation;\n* EASO to deploy teams in Italy and Greece for joint processing of asylum applications;\n* Member States to ensure fingerprinting of all migrants;\n* Consider options for an emergency relocation mechanism;\n* A EU wide voluntary pilot project on resettlement, offering a number of places to persons in need of protection;\n* Establish a new return programme for rapid return of irregular migrants coordinated by Frontex from frontline Member States;\n* Engagement with countries surrounding Libya through a joined effort between the Commission and the EEAS; Initiatives in Niger have to be stepped up.\n* Deploy Immigration Liaison Officers (ILO) in key third countries, to gather intelligence on migratory flows and strengthen the role of the EU Delegations.\nA year after the 10-point plan was introduced{{When|date=March 2019}}, the European Commission also began the process for reforming the Common European Asylum system.\n\nStarted in 1999, the European Commission began devising a plan to create a unified asylum system for those seeking refuge and asylum. Named the Common European Asylum System (CEAS), the system sought to address three key problems which consisted of asylum shopping, differing outcomes in different EU Member States for those seeking asylum, and differing social benefits in different EU Member States for those seeking asylum.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mjilonline.org/the-common-european-asylum-system-its-history-content-and-shortcomings/|title=The Common European Asylum System: Its History, Content, and Shortcomings \u2013 The Michigan Journal of International Law|last=Raithel|first=Silvia|date=2016-02-09|work=The Michigan Journal of International Law|access-date=2017-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn an attempt to address these issues, the European Commission created five components that sought to fulfill minimum standards for asylum:<ref name=\":03\" />\n* The Asylum Procedures Directive\n* The Receptions Conditions Directive\n* The Qualification Directive\n* The Dublin regulation\n* The Eurodac Regulation\nCompleted in 2005, the Common European Asylum System sought to protect the rights those seeking asylum. The system proved to create differing implementation across EU states, building an uneven system of twenty-eight asylum systems across individual states. Due to this divided asylum system and problems with the Dublin system, the European Commission proposed a reform of the Common European Asylum System in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/explainers/understanding-migration-and-asylum-european-union|title=The EU Has a Solidarity Crisis. Not a Refugee Crisis.|website=Open Society Foundations|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nStarting on 6 April 2016, the European Commission began the process of reforming the Common European Asylum System and creating measures for safe and managed paths for legal migration to Europe. First Vice-President Frans Timmermans stated that, \"we need a sustainable system for the future, based on common rules, a fairer sharing of responsibility, and safe legal channels for those who need protection to get it in the EU.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-16-1246_en.htm|title=European Commission \u2013 PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Commission presents options for reforming the Common European Asylum System and developing safe and legal pathways to Europe|website=europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nThe European Commission identified five areas that needed improvement in order to successfully reform the Common European Asylum System:<ref name=\":12\" />\n* Establishing a sustainable and fair system for determining the Member State responsible for asylum seekers.\n* Achieving greater convergence and reducing asylum shopping.\n* Preventing secondary movements within the EU.\n* A new mandate for the EU's asylum agency (to allow the Asylum Support Office to have a role in implementing policy and have an operational position).\n* Reinforcing the Eurodac system (to support the implementation of a reformed Dublin System).\n\nTo create safer and more efficient legal migration routes, the European Commission sought to meet the following five goals:<ref name=\":12\" />\n* A structured resettlement system.\n* A reform of the EU Blue Card Directive (to enhance the admission process and increase rights).\n* Measures to attract and support innovative entrepreneurs (to increase economic growth and create jobs).\n* A REFIT evaluation of the existing legal migration rules (to simplify the current rules for living, working, or studying in the EU).\n* Pursuing close cooperation with third countries (to create a more successful management of migrants).\n\nOn 13 July 2016, the European Commission introduced the proposals to complete the reform of the Common European Asylum System. The reform sought to create a just policy for asylum seekers, while providing a new system that was simple and shortened. Ultimately, the reform proposal attempted to create a system that could handle normal and impacted times of migratory pressure.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-16-2433_en.htm|title=European Commission \u2013 PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Completing the reform of the Common European Asylum System: towards an efficient, fair and humane asylum policy|website=europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nThe European Commission's outline for reform proposed the following:<ref name=\":22\" />\n* Replace the Asylum Procedures Directive with a Regulation, which sought to create a fair and efficient common EU procedure:\n** Simplify, clarify, and shorten asylum procedures.\n** Ensure common guarantees for asylum seekers.\n** Ensure stricter rules to combat abuse.\n** Harmonize rules on safe countries.\n* Replace the existing Qualification Directive with a new Regulation, which sought to unify protection standards and rights:\n** Create greater convergence of recognition rates and forms or protection.\n** Implement firmer rules sanctioning secondary movements.\n** Provide protection only for as long as needed.\n** Strengthen integration incentives.\n* Reform the Reception Conditions Directive, which would allow for common reception standards for asylum seekers:\n** Administer standards and indicators on reception conditions developed by the European Asylum Support Office and update contingency plans.\n** Ensure asylum seekers remain available and discourage them from absconding.\n** Clarify that reception conditions will only be provided in the Member State responsible.\n** Grant earlier access to the labour market.\n** Implement common reinforced guarantees.\n\n=== Securing borders ===\n{{Further|Operation Triton|EU Navfor Med}}\n{{See also|Operation Mare Nostrum|Operation Triton}}\n[[File:Migrants in Hungary 2015 Aug 018.jpg|thumb|Migrants crossing illegally into Hungary underneath the unfinished [[Hungary\u2013Serbia border fence]], 25 August 2015]]\n[[File:RIMG0257.JPG|thumb|In June 2015, [[Royal Navy]] ship {{HMS|Enterprise|H88|6}} replaced {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}} in the [[EU Navfor Med|mission]] to rescue migrants crossing the Mediterranean from Libya to Italy<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/11962766/HMS-Richmond-and-HMS-Enterprise-rescue-541-migrants-from-the-Med.html HMS Richmond and HMS Enterprise rescue 541 migrants from the Med]\". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. 29 October 2015.</ref>]]\n[[File:Hungarian-Serbian_border_barrier_1.jpg|thumb|[[Hungarian border barrier]] ]]\nThe [[2013 Lampedusa migrant shipwreck]] involved \"more than 360\" deaths, leading the Italian government to establish [[Operation Mare Nostrum]], a large-scale naval operation that involved [[search and rescue]], with some migrants brought aboard a naval [[amphibious assault ship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marina.difesa.it/EN/operations/Pagine/MareNostrum.aspx |title=Mare Nostrum Operation |publisher=Marina Militare}}</ref> In 2014, the Italian government ended the operation, calling the costs too large for one EU state alone to manage; Frontex assumed the main responsibility for search and rescue operations. The Frontex operation is called [[Operation Triton]].<ref name=\"European Commission\">{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-566_en.htm |title=EC MEMO, Brussels, 7 October 2014, Frontex Joint Operation 'Triton' \u2013 Concerted efforts to manage migration in the Central Mediterranean |publisher=European Union, European Commission |accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref> The Italian government had requested additional funds from the EU to continue the operation but member states did not offer the requested support.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.vice.com/article/italy-is-about-to-shut-down-the-sea-rescue-operation-that-saved-more-than-90000-migrants-this-year |title=Italy Is About to Shut Down the Sea Rescue Operation That Saved More Than 90,000 Migrants This Year |work=[[Vice News]] |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> The UK government cited fears that the operation was acting as \"an unintended 'pull factor', encouraging more migrants to attempt the dangerous sea crossing and thereby leading to more tragic and unnecessary deaths\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/oct/27/uk-mediterranean-migrant-rescue-plan |title=UK axes support for Mediterranean migrant rescue operation |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> The operation consisted of two surveillance aircraft and three ships, with seven teams of staff who gathered intelligence and conducted screening/identification processing. Its monthly budget was estimated at \u20ac2.9&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"European Commission\" /> Amid an upsurge in the number of sea arrivals in Italy from Libya in 2014, several \nEuropean Union governments refused to fund the Italian-run rescue option [[Operation Mare Nostrum]], which was replaced by [[Frontex]]'s [[Operation Triton]] in November 2014. In the first six months of 2015, Greece overtook Italy in the number of arrivals, becoming in the summer of 2015 the starting point of a flow of refugees and migrants moving through [[Balkan]] countries to [[Northern Europe]]an countries, mainly Germany and Sweden.\n\n''The Guardian'' and [[Reuters]] noted that doubling the size of [[Operation Triton]] would still leave the mission with fewer resources than the previous Italian-run rescue option ([[Operation Mare Nostrum]]) whose budget was more than 3 times as large, had 4 times the number of aircraft<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/20/two-more-mediterranean-migrant-boats-issue-distress-calls-as-eu-ministers-meet |title=Two more migrant boats issue distress calls in Mediterranean |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=21 April 2015|date=20 April 2015 |last1=Kirchgaessner |first1=Stephanie |last2=Traynor |first2=Ian |last3=Kingsley |first3=Patrick }}</ref> and had a wider mandate to conduct search and rescue operations across the Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/04/20/us-europe-migrants-idUSKBN0NA07020150420 |title=Migrants' bodies brought ashore as EU proposes doubling rescue effort |agency=Reuters |accessdate=21 April 2015 |date=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2015, a five-hour emergency summit was held and EU heads of state agreed to triple the budget of Operation Triton to \u20ac120&nbsp;million for 2015\u20132016.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/eu-triple-funding-operation-triton-tackle-mediterranean-migrant-crisis-1498100 |title=EU to triple funding for 'Operation Triton' to tackle Mediterranean migrant crisis |work=IBT |accessdate=24 April 2015|date=24 April 2015 }}</ref> EU leaders claimed that this would allow for the same operational capabilities as Operation Mare Nostrum had had in 2013\u20132014. As part of the agreement the United Kingdom agreed to send {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}}, two naval patrol boats and three helicopters to join the Operation.<ref name=\"auto4\" /> On 5 May 2015 it was announced by the Irish Minister of Defence [[Simon Coveney]] that the [[L\u00c9 Eithne (P31)|L\u00c9 Eithne]] would also take part in the response to the crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pollak |first1=Sorcha |title=L\u00c9 Eithne to be dispatched in migrant search on May 8th |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/l\u00e9-eithne-to-be-dispatched-in-migrant-search-on-may-8th-1.2200382 |work=The Irish Times |date=5 May 2015}}</ref> Amnesty International immediately criticised the EU response as \"a face-saving not a life-saving operation\" and said that \"failure to extend Triton's operational area will fatally undermine today's commitment\".<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2015/04/face-saving-not-a-lifesaving-operation/ |title=Europe's response: \"Face-saving not a life-saving operation\" |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2015, the European Union decided to launch a new operation based in Rome, called [[EU Navfor Med]], under the command of the Italian Admiral [[Enrico Credendino]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eeas.europa.eu/csdp/missions-and-operations/eunavfor-med/pdf/cv_credendino_en.pdf|title=Operation SOPHIA IT Navy Biography (pdf)}}</ref> to undertake systematic efforts to identify, capture and dispose of vessels used by migrant smugglers.<ref name=\"Kanter 2015\">{{cite news | last=Kanter | first=James | title=E.U. Agrees to Naval Intervention on Migrant Smugglers | website=The New York Times | date=18 May 2015 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/19/world/europe/european-union-human-trafficking-military.html | accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> The first phase of the operation, launched on 22 June, involved naval surveillance to detect smugglers' boats and monitor smuggling patterns from Libya towards Italy and Malta. The second phase, called \"Operation Sophia\", started in October, and was aimed at disrupting the smugglers' journeys by boarding, searching, seizing and diverting migrant vessels in international waters. The operation uses six EU warships.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: EU to begin seizing smugglers' boats|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34461503|work=BBC News|date=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Europe gears up to seize smugglers|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-eu-34454392|work=BBC News|date=7 October 2015}}</ref> As of April 2016, more than 13,000 migrants were rescued from the sea and 68 alleged smugglers were arrested in the course of the operation.<ref name=\"auto11\"/>\n\nThe EU seeks to increase the scope of EU Navfor Med so that a third phase of the operation would include patrols inside Libyan waters in order to capture and dispose of vessels used by smugglers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/eu-approves-military-action-against-mediterranean-people-smugglers-083904759.html|title=EU backs military action against Med people smugglers|date=14 September 2015|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/justice/130258|title=EU to expand Mediterranean anti-smuggler force|work=EUobserver|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rt.com/news/315238-mediterranean-smugglers-eu-military/|title=EU approves military action against people smugglers in Mediterranean \u2013 reports|work=RT English|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Land operations on Libya to destroy vessels used by smugglers had been proposed, but commentators note that such an operation would need a UN or Libyan permit.\n\nThe Greek islands (Kos, Leros, Chios, for example) serve as main entry points into Europe for Syrian refugees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muep.mau.se/bitstream/handle/2043/21323/EMR%20DP2016%20-%20v2.pdf?sequence=2|title=Host Communities and the Refugee Crisis A Case Study of Kos Island, Greece|last=Rozali|first=Eleni|date=2016|website=|access-date=February 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe entry routes through the Western Balkan have experienced the greatest intensity of border restrictions in the 2015 EU migrant crisis, according to ''The New York Times''<ref name=BorderCrackdowns>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/09/15/world/europe/migrant-borders-europe.html|title=Closing the Back Door to Europe|author1=Sarah Almukhtar |author2=Josh Keller |author3=Derek Watkins |newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> and other sources, as follows:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! From || To || Barrier || class=\"unsortable\"|Situation\n|-\n| {{flag|Turkey}} || {{flag|Greece}} || [[Border barrier#Greece|Greece]]\n| Greece built a razor-wire fence in 2012 along its short land border with Turkey.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/> In September 2015, Turkish provincial authorities gave approximately 1,700 migrants three days to leave the border zone.<ref name=TurkeyGreece>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/09/16/world/europe/ap-eu-europe-migrants-the-latest.html|title=The Latest: Hundreds Seek to Cross Turkey-Greece Border|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Turkey}} || {{flag|Bulgaria}} || [[Border barrier#Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]\n| As a result of Greece's diversion of migrants to Bulgaria from Turkey, Bulgaria built its own fence to block migrants crossing from Turkey.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Greece}} ||{{flag|North Macedonia}} || [[Macedonian border barrier|Macedonian]]\n| In November 2015, North Macedonia began erecting a fence along its southern border with Greece, with the intention of channeling the flow of migrants through an official checkpoint as opposed to limiting the inflow of migrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/migrants-clash-with-macedonian-police-on-greek-border-1.1464198|title=Migrants clash with Macedonian police on Greek border|author1=Costas Kantouris |author2=Konstantin Testorides |date=28 November 2015|accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> Beginning in November 2015, Greek police permitted only Syrians, Iraqis, and Afghans to cross into North Macedonia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/world/europe/greece-macedonia-migrants-refugees.html|title=Thousands of Migrants Stranded in Greece as Route North Is Narrowed|author=Suzanne Daley|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 December 2015|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref> In February, Macedonian soldiers began erecting a second fence meters away from the previous one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2016/02/07/more-problems-at-fyrom-greek-border-slows-refugees-journey-north/|title=More problems at FYROM-Greek border slows refugees' journey north|date=7 February 2016|author=Euronews}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Serbia}} || {{flag|Hungary}} || [[Hungarian border barrier|Hungaria]]\n| Hungary built a 175-km (109-mi) razor-wire fence along its border with Serbia in 2015.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Croatia}} || {{flag|Hungary}} || [[Hungarian border barrier|Hungary]]\n| Hungary built a 40-km (25-mi) razor-wire fence along its border with Croatia in 2015.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/> On 16 October 2015, Hungary announced that it would close off its border with Croatia to migrants.<ref name=HungaryCroatia2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/17/world/europe/hungary-croatia-refugees-migrants.html|title=Hungary to Close Its Border With Croatia in Migrant Crackdown|author=Rick Lyman|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Croatia}} || {{flag|Slovenia}} || [[Slovenian border barrier|Slovenia]]\n| Slovenia blocked transit from Croatia in September 2015,<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/> pepper spraying migrants trying to cross.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/latest-un-agency-calls-joint-european-response-113758508.html#]. Retrieved 19 September 2015.</ref> Although re-opening the border, by 18 October 2015, Slovenia restricted crossing to 2,500 migrants per day.<ref name=CroatiaSlovenia4/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Hungary}} || {{flag|Austria}} || \n| Austria planned to put border controls into effect along its border with Hungary in September 2015, and officials said the controls could stay in effect under European Union rules for up to six months.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Slovenia}} || {{flag|Austria}} || [[Austrian border barrier|Austrian]]\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Russia}} || {{flag|Norway}}  || \n|On 25 January 2016, it was reported that Russia closed its northern border checkpoint with Norway for asylum seekers to return to Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/russia-shuts-arctic-border-to-norway-over-security-reasons/a-19001593|title=Russia shuts arctic border to Norway over \u2032security reasons\u2032 \u2013 News \u2013 DW.COM \u2013 24.01.2016|work=DW.COM}}</ref> While the announcement was noted as closure of the border, it apparently was considering only returning asylum seekers, thus only partial closure of the border.\n|-\n| {{flag|Russia}} || {{flag|Finland}} || \n| On 4 December 2015, Finland temporarily closed one of its land border crossings by lowering the border gate and blocking the road with a car. The closure was reported to only apply for asylum seekers and lasted only a couple of hours.<ref name=\"tass.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://tass.ru/en/world/841803|title=TASS: World \u2013 Finnish border guards block 15 Mideast, African immigrants in Russia's Murmansk region|work=TASS}}</ref> On 27 December 2015, Finland closed its Russian border for people riding on bicycles, reportedly enforcing the rule only on {{Interlanguage link multi|Raja-Jooseppi|fi|3=Raja-Jooseppi (ylikulkupaikka)}} and [[Salla]] checkpoints. Earlier, more and more asylum seekers had crossed the border on bikes.<ref name=\"http://tass.ru/en/world/847182\">{{cite web|author=<%= item.timeFlag %> |url=http://tass.ru/en/world/847182 |title=TASS: World \u2013 Finland prohibits crossing border with Russia on bikes \u2013 media |publisher=Tass.ru |date= |accessdate=2018-06-28}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Austria}} || {{flag|Germany}} || \n| Germany placed temporary travel restrictions from Austria by rail in 2015<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/> but has imposed the least onerous restrictions for migrants entering by the Western Balkans route in 2015, in the context that Chancellor Angela Merkel had insisted that Germany will not limit the number of refugees it accepts.<ref name=BorderCrackdowns/>\n|}\n\n=== Migration policies ===\n==== Migration Partnership Framework ====\n[[File:FAMILY PHOTO 2016-09-20 (29519477920).jpg|thumb|3rd Prague Process Ministerial Conference]]\n\nBeginning in 1999, the Tampere Agenda outlines the EU\u2019s policy on migration, presenting a certain openness towards freedom, security, and justice.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite journal|last=European Parliament|date=2018|title=Migration and Asylum: A Challenge for Europe|url=|journal=Asylum Policy|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> This agenda focuses on two central issues, including the development of a common asylum system and the enhancement of external border controls.<ref name=\":25\" /> The externalization of borders with Turkey is essentially the transferring of border controls and management to foreign countries, which are in close proximity to EU countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://privacyinternational.org/news-analysis/3224/new-report-underlines-eus-strategy-war-migration-border-externalisation|title=New Report Underlines the EU's Strategy in the War on Migration: Border Externalisation|website=Privacy International|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> The EU\u2019s decision to externalize its borders puts significant pressure on non-EU countries to cooperate with EU political forces.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Bennett|first=M.B|date=2018|title=The Refugee Crisis and the EU's Externalisation of Integrated Border Management to Libya and Turkey|url=|journal=EU Diplomacy Papers|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>  \n\n[[Prague Process (co-operation in migration management)|Communication on Global Approach to Migration and Mobility]]\" (GAMM). The Migration Partnership Framework introduced in 2016 implements greater resettlement of migrants and alternative legal routes for migration.<ref name=\":25\" /> The Migration Partnership Framework's goals aligns with the EU\u2019s efforts throughout the refugee crisis to deflect responsibility and legal obligations away from EU member states and onto transit and origin countries.<ref name=\":25\" /> <ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Bennett|first=M.B|date=2018|title=The Refugee Crisis and the EU's Externalisation of Integrated Border Management to Libya and Turkey|url=|journal=EU Diplomacy Papers|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> By directing migrant flows to third countries,{{what?|date=December 2019}} policies place responsibilities on third countries{{what?|date=December 2019}}.<ref name=\":19\" /> States with insufficient resources are forced (by law) to ensure the protection of migrants\u2019 rights, including the right to asylum.<ref name=\":19\" /> Destination states under border externalization strategies are responsible for rights violated outside their own territory.<ref name=\":19\" /> Fundamental rights of migrants can be impacted during the process of externalizing borders.<ref name=\":19\" /> For example, child migrants are recognized to have special status under international law, yet during transit, they are vulnerable to trafficking and other crimes.\n\n==== Africa Agreement: Emergency Trust Fund ====\nBetween 11 and 12 November 2015, [[Valletta Summit on Migration]] between European and African leaders was held in [[Valletta]], [[Malta]], to discuss the migrant crisis. The summit resulted in the EU setting up an Emergency Trust Fund to promote development in Africa, in return for African countries to help out in the crisis.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migration summit: \"We are in a race against time to save Schengen\" \u2013 Tusk|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151112/local/watch-valletta-summit-concluding-press-conference.591885|accessdate=12 November 2015|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Angela Merkel  ====\nAccording to the ''Washington Post'', German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]]'s public pledges (at a time of diplomatic standoff with the [[Third Orb\u00e1n Government|government of Hungary]] at the beginning of September, when tens of thousands of refugees were attempting to cross Hungarian territory without getting processed for asylum application in the country) that Germany would offer temporary residency to refugees, combined with television footage of cheering Germans welcoming refugees and migrants arriving in Munich,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/05/refugee-crisis-warm-welcome-for-people-bussed-from-budapest|title=Cheering German crowds greet refugees after long trek from Budapest to Munich|author=Emma Graham-Harrison|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=5 September 2015}}</ref> persuaded large numbers of people to move from Turkey up the Western Balkan route.<ref name=EightSlyReasons/>  \n\nOn 25 August 2015 \u2013 according to ''The Guardian'' \u2013 'Germany's federal agency for migration and refugees' made it public, that \"The #Dublin procedure for Syrian citizens is at this point in time effectively no longer being adhered to\". During a press conference, \"Germany's interior minister, Thomas de Maizi\u00e8re, confirmed that the suspension of the Dublin agreement was \"not as such a legally binding act\", but more of a \"guideline for management practice\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/25/it-took-on-a-life-of-its-own-how-rogue-tweet-led-syrians-to-germany|title='It took on a life of its own': how one rogue tweet led Syrians to Germany|author1=Philip Oltermann  |author2=Patrick Kingsley|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=25 August 2016|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> Around 24 August 2015, while thousands of migrants tried to reach Western Europe through the Balkans, a considerable proportion of them fleeing the [[Syrian Civil War]], and noticing that most of the burden of migrants crossing the [[Mediterranean Sea]] fell on the peripheral southern EU member states [[Greece]] and [[Italy]], the German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], according to news media, decided to no longer follow the rule under the [[Dublin Regulation|'Dublin' EU regulations for asylum seekers]] holding that migrants \"can apply for asylum only in the first EU member state they enter\"<ref name=\"DropsRules\"/> (The [[Dublin Regulation|'Dublin' regulation]] actually holds that the migrant should apply for asylum in the first EU country where he was ''formally registered''.){{fact|date=March 2020}} Germany ordered its officers to also process asylum applications from Syrians if they had come through other EU countries.<ref name=\"DropsRules\">{{cite news|last1=Holehouse|first1=Matthew|last2=Huggler|first2=Justin|last3=Vogt|first3=Andrea|date=24 August 2015|title=Germany drops EU rules to allow in Syrian refugees|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11821822/Germany-drops-EU-rules-to-allow-in-Syrian-refugees.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> In the night of 4 September 2015, Merkel decided that Germany would admit the thousands of refugees who were stranded in [[Hungary]],<ref name=NRC6Sep2015>{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2015/09/06/1061000-a1413393 'Wenen verwacht vandaag weer 10.000 migranten \u2013 paus doet oproep' (Vienna today expects another 10,000 migrants \u2013 Pope issues an appeal)]. ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 6 September 2015. Retrieved 15 July 2019.</ref> in sweltering conditions,<ref name=politico15Sep>[https://www.politico.eu/article/merkel-changed-her-mind-migration-crisis-eu-schengen-border-control/ 'Why Merkel changed her mind']. ''Politico'', 15 September 2015. Retrieved 18 July 2019.</ref> and whom the Hungarian prime minister Orban had sent to the [[Austria]]n border.<ref name=Trouw3Sep16>{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.trouw.nl/nieuws/duitse-wilkommenskultur-is-ver-in-het-geheugen-weggezakt~bd698aa1/ 'Duitse 'Wilkommenskultur' is ver in het geheugen weggezakt' (German welcoming culture has sunk deep in our memory)]. ''[[Trouw]]'', 3 September 2016. Retrieved 15 July 2019.</ref> With that decision, she reportedly aimed to prevent disturbances at the German borders.<ref name=Trouw3Sep16/>  The days following that 4 September, tens of thousands of refugees traveled from Hungary via [[Vienna]] into Germany.<ref name=NRC6Sep2015/><ref name=politico15Sep/>\n\nAnalyst Will Hutton for the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' on 30 August 2015 praised Merkel's decisions on migration policies: \"Angela Merkel's humane stance on migration is a lesson to us all\u2026 The German leader has stood up to be counted. Europe should rally to her side\u2026 She wants to keep Germany and Europe open, to welcome legitimate asylum seekers in common humanity, while doing her very best to stop abuse and keep the movement to manageable proportions. Which demands a European-wide response (\u2026)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/30/immigration-asylumseekers-refugees-migrants-angela-merkel|title=Angela Merkel's humane stance on immigration is a lesson to us all|author=Will Hutton|work=The Guardian|accessdate=19 September 2015|date=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Turkey Agreement: Locating migrants to safe country ====\n[[File:Sea arrivals to Greece and Italy, 2015.png|thumb|upright=2|Mediterranean sea arrivals to Greece and Italy from January 2015 to September 2016, according to UNHCR data<ref name=\"UNHCR2015\">{{cite web|title=Arrivals to Greece, Italy and Spain. January\u2013December 2015|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/MonthlyTrendsofNationalities-ArrivalstoGreeceItalyandSpain-31December2015.pdf|publisher=UNHCR}}</ref>]]\n\nThe EU proposed to the Turkish government a plan in which Turkey would take back every refugee who entered Greece (and thereby the EU) illegally. In return, the EU would accept one person into the EU who is registered as a Syrian refugee in Turkey for every Syrian sent back from Greece.<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.psca.eu/uploads/MleCMS/Issue%20VII_complete.pdf|title=The EU's response to the so-called refugee \"crisis\"|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref>  12 EU countries have national lists of so-called [[Safe country of origin|safe countries of origin]]. The [[European Commission]] is proposing one, common EU list designating as 'safe' all [[Future enlargement of the European Union#Recognised candidates|EU candidate countries]] ([[Albania]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Serbia]] and [[Turkey]]), plus [[Future enlargement of the European Union#Potential candidates that have not yet applied for EU membership|potential EU candidates]] [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and [[Kosovo]].<ref name=\"safe\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/home-affairs/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/background-information/docs/2_eu_safe_countries_of_origin_en.pdf |title=An Eu 'Safe Countries of Origin' List |accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> The list would allow for faster returns to those countries, even though asylum applications from nationals of those countries would continue to be assessed on an individual, case-by-case basis.<ref name=\"safe\"/> International Law generated during the Geneva Convention states that a country is considered \"safe\" when there is a democratic system in a country and generally there is: no persecution, no torture, no threat of violence, and no armed conflict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/background-information/docs/2_eu_safe_countries_of_origin_en.pdf|title=AN EU 'SAFE COUNTRIES OF ORIGIN' LIST.|last=|first=|date=|website=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009225639/https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/background-information/docs/2_eu_safe_countries_of_origin_en.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-09|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nIn November, Turkish president [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] reportedly threatened to send the millions of refugees in Turkey to EU member states if it was left to shoulder the burden alone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/12/turkish-president-threatens-to-send-millions-of-syrian-refugees-to-eu|title=Turkish president threatens to send millions of Syrian refugees to EU|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 February 2016|author=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> On 12 November 2015, at the end of the two-day summit in Malta, EU officials announced an agreement to offer Turkey \u20ac3 billion over two years to manage more than 2 million refugees from Syria who had sought refuge there, in return for curbing migration through Turkey into the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/13/world/europe/european-union-refugees-migrants-sweden.html?ribbon-ad-idx=5&rref=world/europe&module=Ribbon&version=origin&region=Header&action=click&contentCollection=Europe&pgtype=article|title=Europe Nears Accord With Turkey to Stem Tide of Refugees|author=James Kanter|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> The \u20ac3 billion fund for Turkey was approved by the EU in February 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: EU approves 3 bn-euro fund for Turkey|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35486655|work=BBC News|date=3 February 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2016, the Netherlands proposed that the EU take in 250,000 refugees a year from Turkey in return for Turkey closing the Aegean sea route to Greece, but Turkey rejected the plan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey dismisses EU plan to resettle refugees in return for sealing sea route|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/10/turkey-dismisses-eu-plan-to-resettle-refugees-in-return-for-sealing-sea-route|work=The Guardian|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> Starting on 7 March 2016, the EU met with Turkey for another summit in [[Brussels]] to negotiate further solutions of the crisis. An original plan saw for the closing statement to declare the Western Balkan route closed. However, this was met with criticism from German chancellor Angela Merkel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Feilschen um Formulierungen|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/eu-gipfel-fluechtlinge-113.html|publisher=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]]|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210627/http://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/eu-gipfel-fluechtlinge-113.html|archivedate=7 March 2016|language=German|date=7 March 2016}}</ref> Turkey countered the offer by demanding a further \u20ac3 billion in order to help them in supplying the 2.7 million refugees in Turkey. In addition, the Turkish government asked for their citizens to be allowed to travel freely into the Schengen area starting at the end of June 2016, as well as an increased speed in talks of a possible [[accession of Turkey to the European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Harte Verhandlungen \u00fcber t\u00fcrkische Vorschl\u00e4ge|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/eu-gipfel-fluechtlinge-121.html|publisher=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]]|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307211020/http://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/eu-gipfel-fluechtlinge-121.html|archivedate=7 March 2016|language=German|date=7 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rankin|first1=Jennifer|title=Resettling Syrians, aid and visa changes on table at EU-Turkey migration summit|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/07/eu-offers-another-3bn-to-turkey-at-emergency-migration-summit|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210858/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/07/eu-offers-another-3bn-to-turkey-at-emergency-migration-summit|archivedate=7 March 2016|date=7 March 2016}}</ref> The plan to send migrants back to Turkey was criticized on 8 March 2016 by the United Nations, which warned that it could be illegal to send the migrants back to Turkey in exchange of financial and political rewards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-idUSKCN0WA1D4|title=U.N., rights groups say EU-Turkey migrant deal may be illegal|author1=Stephanie Nebehay |author2=Gabriela Baczynska |date=8 March 2016|work=Reuters|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2016, an agreement between the [[European Union]] and [[Turkey]], aiming to discourage migrants from making the dangerous sea journey from Turkey to [[Greece]], came into effect. Under its terms, migrants arriving in Greece would be sent back to Turkey if they did not apply for asylum or their claim was rejected, whilst the EU would send around 2,300 experts, including security and migration officials and translators, to Greece in order to help implement the deal.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35854413|title=Migrant crisis: EU-Turkey deal comes into effect|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=21 March 2016|date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was also agreed that any irregular migrants who crossed into Greece from Turkey after 20 March 2016 would be sent back to Turkey, based on an individual case-by-case evaluation. Any Syrian returned to Turkey would be replaced by a Syrian resettled from Turkey to the EU, preferably the individuals who did not try to enter the EU illegally in the past and not exceeding a maximum of 72,000 people.<ref name=\"a\" /> Turkish nationals would have access to the Schengen passport-free zone by June 2016 but this would not include non-Schengen countries such as the UK. The talks aiming at Turkey's accession to the EU as a member began in July 2016, and $3.3 billion in aid was to be delivered to Turkey.<ref name=\"bbc.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=EU-Turkey Agreement: Questions and Answers|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-16-963_en.htm|publisher=European Commission}}</ref> The talks were suspended in November 2016, following the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-eu-idUSKCN1QA0MJ|title=Turkey condemns European parliament committee call to suspend...|date=21 February 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=21 February 2019}}</ref>  A similar threat was raised as the [[European Parliament]] voted to suspend EU membership talks with Turkey in November 2016: \"if you go any further,\" [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]] declared, \"these border gates will be opened. Neither me nor my people will be affected by these dry threats.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Adamson|first=Fiona B|last2=Tsourapas|first2=Gerasimos|date=2019-05-01|title=Migration Diplomacy in World Politics|journal=International Studies Perspectives|language=en|volume=20|issue=2|pages=113\u2013128|doi=10.1093/isp/eky015|issn=1528-3577|url=http://pure-oai.bham.ac.uk/ws/files/57727314/Adamson_Tsourapas_2018_Migration_diplomacy_in_world_politics_International_Studies_Perspectives.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/president-erdogan-turkey-eu-membership-migrants-refugees-europe-warning-a7438316.html|title=Turkey warns Europe it will open the floodgates to more migrants|date=2016-11-25|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref>\n\nMigrants from Greece to Turkey were to be given medical checks, registered and fingerprinted, then bused to \"reception and removal\" centres.<ref name=\"BBC April 8\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35993767 Migrant crisis: Deportations resume from Greece to Turkey] [[BBC News]]. Published on 8 April 2016,</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publictenders.net/tender/374386|title=TR-Ankara: IPA \u2013 construction of reception and removal centres|work=publictenders.net|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> and later deported to their home countries.<ref name=\"BBC April 8\"/> The [[UNHCR]]'s director [[Vincent Cochetel]] claimed in August 2016 that parts of the deal were already de facto suspended because of the post-coup absence of Turkish police at the Greek detention centres to oversee deportations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greece on edge, as Turkish coup prompts surge in new arrivals |url=https://euobserver.com/beyond-brussels/134868|publisher=euobserver|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish police withdrawal from Greece stalls EU migration pact|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/31/turkish-police-withdrawal-greece-stalls-eu-migration-pact-unhcr|publisher=theguardian|language=en|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe UNHCR said it was not a party to the EU-Turkey deal and it would not be involved in returns or detention.<ref>{{cite news|title=UNHCR redefines role in Greece as EU-Turkey deal comes into effect|url=http://www.unhcr.org/56f10d049.html|work=UNHCR|date=22 March 2016}}</ref> Like the UNHCR, four aid agencies ([[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]], the [[International Rescue Committee]], the [[Norwegian Refugee Council]] and [[Save the Children]]) said they would not help implementing the EU-Turkey deal because blanket expulsion of refugees contravened international law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Refugee crisis: key aid agencies refuse any role in 'mass expulsion'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/23/refugee-crisis-aid-agencies-unhcr-refuse-role-mass-expulsion-greece-turkey|work=The Guardian|date=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Amnesty International]] said that the agreement between EU and Turkey was \"madness\", and that 18 March 2016 was \"a dark day for Refugee Convention, Europe and humanity\". Turkish prime minister [[Ahmet Davutoglu]] said that Turkey and EU had the same challenges, the same future and the same destiny. Donald Tusk said that the migrants in Greece would not be sent back to dangerous areas.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/turkey/12197969/Refugee-crisis-Turkey-and-EU-agree-deal-to-send-migrants-back-to-Turkey-from-Greece.html Migrants given 24-hour deadline to reach Europe after Turkey and EU agree 'historic' deal] M. Holehouse, R. Akkoc and N. Squires, The Daily Telegraph, 18 March 2016</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2017, Turkish [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|interior minister]] [[S\u00fcleyman Soylu]] threatened to send 15,000 refugees to the [[European Union]] every month, while Turkish foreign minister [[Mevlut Cavusoglu]] also threatened to [[EU-Turkey deal|cancel the deal]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nu.nl/buitenland/4549128/turkije-dreigt-met-sturen-migranten-europese-unie.html |title= Turkije dreigt met sturen migranten naar Europese Unie |language= nl |work= [[NU.nl]] |year= 2017 |access-date= 17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/turkey-threatens-to-send-europe-15000-refugees-a-month/28375772.html|title=Turkey Threatens To Send Europe 15,000 Refugees A Month|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Refugees waiting at Greek-Turkish Border.jpg|thumb|Refugees protesting at the Pazarkule border gate, the Greek-Turkish border]]\n\nOn 9 October 2019, the [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]] began. Within the first week and a half 130,000 people were displaced. On 10 October it was reported that President Erdo\u011fan had threatened to send \"millions\" of Syrian refugees to Europe in response to criticism of his military offensive into Kurdish-controlled northern Syria. <ref>{{Cite web|title=Turkey's Erdogan threatens to send 'millions' of refugees to Europe if EU calls Syria offensive 'invasion' |date=2019-10-10|website=The Telegraph|language=en|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/10/turkeys-erdogan-threatens-send-millions-refugees-europe-eu-calls/}}</ref> On 27 February 2020, a senior Turkish official said Turkish police, coast guard and border security officials had received orders to no longer stop refugees\u2019 land and sea crossings to Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security/turkey-with-more-dead-troops-wont-stop-syrian-refugees-reaching-europe-official-idUSKCN20L0GQ|title=Turkey, with more dead troops, won't stop Syrian refugees reaching Europe: official|work=Reuters|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Changes in Schengen & Dublin ====\n{{Main|Dublin Regulation|Schengen Area}}\n[[File:Map of the Schengen Area.svg|thumb|{{legend|#003399|The [[Schengen Area]]}}{{legend|#ffa500|European Union members legally obliged to join Schengen at a future date}}{{legend|#27a4bb|Countries with open borders}}]]\nIn the [[Schengen Agreement]] of 14 June 1985, 26 European countries (22 of the 28 [[European Union]] member states, plus four [[European Free Trade Association]] states) joined together to form an area where border checks on internal Schengen borders (i.e. between member states) are abolished and instead checks are restricted to the [[Schengen Area#Regulation of external borders|external Schengen borders]] and countries with external borders are obligated to enforce border control regulations. Countries may reinstate internal border controls for a maximum of two months for \"public policy or national security\" reasons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Schengen: Controversial EU free movement deal explained|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-13194723|work=BBC News|date=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dublin regulation]] determines the EU member state responsible to examine an [[right of asylum|asylum]] application to prevent asylum applicants in the EU from \"[[asylum shopping]]\", where applicants send their applications for asylum to numerous EU member states to get the best \"deal\" instead of just having \"safety countries\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/07/13/eu-floats-new-asylum-system-seeks-to-stop-asylum-shopping.html|title=EU floats new asylum system, seeks to stop 'asylum shopping'|date=13 July 2016}}</ref> or \"asylum orbiting\", where no member state takes responsibility for an asylum seeker. By default (when no family reasons or humanitarian grounds are present), the first member state that an asylum seeker entered and in which they have been fingerprinted is responsible. If the asylum seeker then moves to another member state, they can be transferred back to the member state they first entered. This has led many to criticise the Dublin rules for placing too much responsibility for asylum seekers on member states on the EU's external borders (like Italy, Greece, Croatia and Hungary), instead of devising a burden-sharing system among EU states.<ref>{{cite web|title=EU legal framework on asylum and irregular immigration 'on arrival'|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/551333/EPRS_BRI%282015%29551333_EN.pdf|publisher=European Parliamentary Research Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Asylum in the EU: Facts and Figures|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2015/551332/EPRS_BRI%282015%29551332_EN.pdf|publisher=European Parliamentary Research Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dublin regulation leaves asylum seekers with their fingers burnt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/oct/07/dublin-regulation-european-asylum-seekers|work=The Guardian|date=7 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the Commission to the European Parliament and Council addressed \"inherent weaknesses\" in the Common European Asylum System and proposed reforms for the Dublin Regulation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/proposal-implementation-package/docs/20160406/towards_a_reform_of_the_common_european_asylum_system_and_enhancing_legal_avenues_to_europe_-_20160406_en.pdf|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament and the Council|last=|first=|date=4 June 2016|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Under the initial Dublin Regulation, responsibility was concentrated on border states that received a large influx of asylum seekers. A briefing by the European Parliament explained that the Dublin Agreement was only designed to assign responsibility, not effectively share responsibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/586639/EPRS_BRI(2016)586639_EN.pdf|title=EU Legislation in Process: Reform of the Dublin System|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The reforms would attempt to create a burden-sharing system through several mechanisms. The proposal would introduce a \"centralized automated system\" to record the number of asylum applications across the EU, with \"national interfaces\" within each of the Member States.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statewatch.org/news/2017/feb/eprs-mgration-compendium.pdf|title=Addressing Migration in the European Union: Selected publications by the European Parliamentary Research Service|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It would also present a \"reference key\" based on a Member State's GDP and population size to determine its absorption capacity.<ref name=\":02\" /> When absorption capacity in a Member State exceeds 150 percent of its reference share, a \"fairness mechanism\" would distribute the excess number of asylum seekers across less congested Member States.<ref name=\":02\" />  If a Member State chooses not to accept the asylum seekers, it would contribute \u20ac250,000 per application as a  \"solidarity contribution\".<ref name=\":02\" /> The reforms have been discussed in European Parliament since its proposal in 2016, and was included in a meeting on \"The Third Reform of the Common European Asylum System \u2013 Up for the Challenge\" in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/legislative-train/theme-towards-a-new-policy-on-migration/file-revision-of-the-dublin-regulation|title=Legislative train schedule {{!}} European Parliament|website=European Parliament|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Dublin Regulation]], an asylum seeker has to apply for asylum in the first EU country they entered, and, if they cross borders to another country after being fingerprinted, they can be returned to the former. As most asylum seekers try to reach Germany or Sweden through the other EU countries in order to apply for asylum there, and as 22 EU countries form the borderless [[Schengen area]] where internal border controls are abolished, enforcement of the Dublin Regulation became increasingly difficult during late summer 2015, with some countries allowing asylum seekers to transit through their territories and other countries renouncing the right to return them back or reinstating border controls within the Schengen Area to prevent them from entering. In July 2017, the [[European Court of Justice]] upheld the Dublin Regulation, despite the high influx of 2015, giving EU member states the right to deport migrants to the first country of entry to the EU.<ref name=\"telegraph26July2017\">{{cite news|title=EU court rejects 'open-door' policy and upholds right of member states to deport refugees|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/07/26/eu-court-rejects-open-door-policy-upholds-right-member-states/|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nCountries responded in different ways:\n*Hungary became overburdened by asylum applications and on 23 June 2015 it stopped receiving back applicants who had crossed the borders to other EU countries and been detained there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/06/23/uk-europe-migrants-austria-hungary-idUKKBN0P31ZB20150623 |title=Defying EU, Hungary suspends rules on asylum seekers |agency=Reuters |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> Later in the year, migrants in southern Hungary started a hunger strike in protest against the closure of the green border with Serbia.<ref>[http://www.rt.com/news/315389-hungary-refugees-hunger-strike Refugees start sit-down hunger strike in southern Hungary \u2013 media reports], RT</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/sep/15/refugee-crisis-hungary-launches-border-crackdown-live-updates Refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency at Serbian border \u2013 live updates], ''The Guardian''</ref> Hungarian police used tear gas and a water cannon on the protesters after they threw stones and concrete at the riot police.<ref>{{cite news|first=Krisztina|last=Than |title=Hungarian police fire water cannon and tear gas at migrants|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/16/us-europe-migrants-hungary-protests-idUSKCN0RG1TA20150916 |agency=Reuters |date=16 September 2015|access-date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n* On 24 August 2015, in accordance with article 17 of the Dublin III Regulations, Germany suspended the general procedure as regards Syrian refugees and to process their asylum applications directly itself.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/germany-opens-its-gates-berlin-says-all-syrian-asylumseekers-are-welcome-to-remain-as-britain-is-urged-to-make-a-similar-statement-10470062.html |title=Germany opens its gates: Berlin says all Syrian asylum-seekers are welcome to remain, as Britain is urged to make a 'similar statement' |work=The Independent |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> The change in Germany asylum policy incited large numbers of migrants to move towards Germany, especially after German chancellor Merkel stated that \"there is no legal limit to refugee numbers\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11861966/Germany-to-reinstate-border-controls-as-country-struggles-with-influx-of-refugees-live.html |title=Germany 'to reinstate border controls' as country struggles with influx of refugees \u2013 live |work=The Independent |accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kvoa.com/story/29997280/the-latest-merkel-says-no-legal-limit-to-refugee-numbers |title=The Latest: Merkel says no legal limit to refugee numberse |publisher=KVOA |accessdate=12 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923182953/http://www.kvoa.com/story/29997280/the-latest-merkel-says-no-legal-limit-to-refugee-numbers |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref> Austria was meanwhile allowing unimpeded travel of migrants from Hungary to Germany through its own territory.  Germany then established temporary border controls along its border with Austria, in order to \"limit the current inflows\" and \"return to orderly procedures when people enter the country\" according to German Interior Minister [[Thomas de Maizi\u00e8re]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34239674 Migrant crisis: Germany to start temporary border controls]. BBC News</ref> The Czech Republic reacted by increasing police presence along its border with Austria in anticipation of the mass of migrants in Austria trying to reach Germany through the Czech Republic. Czech police  conducted random searches of vehicles and trains within Czech territory, with cars and helicopters patrolling alongside the green border. Some Czech police officers were stationed also within Austria in order to give advance warning if large numbers of migrants moved towards the Austrian\u2013Czech borders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novinky.cz/domaci/380564-policiste-chystaji-zalohy-pro-dohled-na-hranici.html |title=Policist\u00e9 chystaj\u00ed z\u00e1lohy pro dohled na hranici |publisher=novinky.cz |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> Between 9 and 10 September, Denmark closed rail lines with Germany, after hundreds of migrants refused to be registered in the country as asylum seekers and insisted on continuing their travel to Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-denmark-shuts-rail-link-as-europe-wrangles-over-refugees-2015-9 |title=Denmark has shut down its rail link as refugees surge into Scandinavia |work=Business Insider |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n* On 2 September 2015, the Czech Republic also decided to defy the Dublin Regulation and to offer Syrian refugees the option to have their application processed in the Czech Republic or to continue their journey elsewhere. Immigrants of other nationalities  would normally face detention and return under the Dublin Regulation if trying to reach Germany through the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.praguepost.com/eu-news/49584-change-in-czech-refugee-policy |title=Change in Czech refugee policy |work=The Prague Post |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> On 7 September, Austria began phasing out special measures that had allowed tens of thousands of migrants to cross its territory and decided to reinstate the Dublin Regulation.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34169726 Migrant crisis: Austria 'to end emergency migrant measures']. [[BBC News]]. 7 September 2015.</ref>\n* On 14 September, Austria established border controls alongside its border with Hungary. Austria deployed police officersand the army along its border.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34242123 Migrant crisis: Austria to deploy troops]. [[BBC News]].</ref> Hungary also deployed army personnel along its border with Serbia<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34205849|title=Migrant crisis: Hungarian army stages border protection exercise|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> and announced that in future those who illegally enter the Hungarian territory of Schengen will be arrested and face imprisonment.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34229335 Europe migrant crisis: Hungary PM calls for \u20ac3bn Syria aid package]. [[BBC News]]. 12 September 2015.</ref> They later closed the border.<ref name=\"Holehouse 2015\">{{cite web | last=Holehouse | first=Matthew | title=Refugee crisis: Croatia seals border crossings with Serbia | website=The Daily Telegraph | date=18 September 2015 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/hungary/11873012/Refugee-crisis-Hungary-declares-victory-in-border-strategy-as-migrants-head-to-Croatia-instead.html | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Following Austrian chancellor Werner Faymann's remarks likening Hungary's treatment of refugees to Nazi policies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-13/austria-likens-hungary-asylum-seeker-policy-to-nazi-era/6771418 |title=European migrant crisis: Hungary hits back at Austria's criticism of 'Nazi-like' asylum seeker policies |publisher=ABC.au |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> Hungary started transporting refugees by bus directly to the border with Austria, where they were offloaded and tried to cross to Austria on foot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bbj.hu/politics/report-refugees-bused-from-roszke-to-austrian-border_103990 |title=Report: Refugees bused from R\u00f6szke to Austrian border |work=Budapest Business Journal |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Management of immigration ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable toptextcells zebra\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+Expenditure on refugees (caseload) 2015\u20132016 (2016 summary)<ref name=\"cost2016\">[https://euagenda.eu/upload/publications/untitled-67413-ea.pdf John Cosgrave, Karen Hargrave, Marta Foresti und Isabella Massa: \u201eEurope\u2019s refugees and migrants Hidden flows, tightened borders and spiralling costs\u201c] Overseas Development Institute 09/2016, page 43\u201346.</ref>\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Country !! Refugees<br> (Case) !! Costs<br> in  \u20ac Mil.!! Share<br> (GDP) !! \u00f8 Costs<br> in \u20ac per<br> citizen/year\n|-\n|Sweden ||179,017 || 2,403 ||0.54%|| 245.27\n|-\n|Austria||136,208 || 1,566 ||0.46%|| 181.91\n|-\n|Germany || 1,301,068 || 13,309 ||0.44%|| 163.48\n|-\n|Switzerland ||65,164 || 1,156 ||0.19%|| 139.45\n|-\n|Norway ||33,613 || 645 ||0.18%|| 124.19\n|-\n|Luxembourg || 4,263 ||69 ||0.13%|| 120.82\n|-\n|Finland ||37,739 ||447 ||0.21%|| 81.53\n|-\n|Denmark ||27,970 ||393 ||0.15%|| 69.31\n|-\n|Malta || 3,398 || 24 ||0.28%|| 56.36\n|-\n|Belgium ||52,700 || 543 ||0.13%|| 48.08\n|-\n|Netherlands || 58,517 || 680 ||0.10%|| 40.15\n|-\n|Italy || 197,739 || 2,359 ||0.14%|| 38.80\n|-\n|Cyprus || 4,550 || 36 ||0.21%|| 30.79\n|-\n|Hungary || 114,365 || 293 ||0.27%|| 29.80\n|-\n|Iceland || 850 ||10 || 0.06%|| 29.02\n|-\n|Greece || 57,521 || 313 ||0.18%|| 28.91\n|-\n|France || 149,332 || 1,490 ||0.07%|| 22.30\n|-\n|UK || 81,751 ||1,081 ||0.04%|| 16.59\n|-\n|Bulgaria || 36,194 || 95 || 0.22% || 13.23\n|-\n!EU+[[EFTA]] ||2,614,306||27,296||0.17%||52.14\n|-\n|}\nThe table \"Expenditure on refugees (caseload) 2015\u20132016 (2016 summary)\" summarizes the 1.7 million asylum applicants in 2015 will cost \u20ac18 billion in maintenance costs in 2016. The total 2015 and 2016 asylum caseload will cost \u20ac27.3 billion (27.296 in \u20ac Mil.) in 2016. In the \"Expenditure on refugees (caseload) 2015\u20132016 (2016 summary),\"  Sweden will bear the heaviest cost. <ref name=\"cost2016\" />\n==== Quota system (relocation) ====\nThe escalation in April 2015 of [[List of migrant vessel incidents on the Mediterranean Sea|shipwrecks of migrant boats in the Mediterranean]] led European Union leaders to reconsider their policies on border control and processing of migrants.<ref name=\"EmergencyTalks\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/04/19/us-europe-migrants-idUSKBN0NA07020150419|title=EU leaders call for emergency talks after 700 migrants drown off Libya|agency=Reuters|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> On 20 April the European Commission proposed a 10-point plan that included the [[European Asylum Support Office]] deploying teams in Italy and Greece for joint processing of asylum applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-4813_en.htm|title=European Commission \u2013 PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Joint Foreign and Home Affairs Council: Ten point action plan on migration|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Also in April 2015 German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] proposed a new system of quotas to distribute non-EU asylum seekers around the EU member states.<ref>Justin Huggler, Andrew Marszal, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11561430/Angela-Merkel-calls-for-new-rules-for-distributing-asylum-seekers-in-Europe.html Angela Merkel calls for new rules for distributing asylum seekers in Europe], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' dated 24 April 2015</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, as thousands of migrants started to move from [[Budapest]] to [[Vienna]], Germany, Italy and France demanded asylum-seekers be shared more evenly between EU states. Commission President [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] proposed to distribute 160,000 asylum seekers among EU states under a new migrant quota system to be set out. [[Jean Asselborn]], the Luxembourg foreign minister, called for the establishment of a European Refugee Agency, which would have the power to investigate whether every EU member state is applying the same standards for granting asylum to migrants. Viktor Orb\u00e1n, the prime minister of Hungary, criticised the European Commission warning that \"tens of millions\" of migrants could come to Europe. Asselborn declared to be \"ashamed\" of Orb\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nicola-sturgeon/11841808/David-Cameron-insists-he-cares-about-refugees-amid-criticism-from-Tories.html |title=David Cameron insists he 'cares' about refugees amid criticism from Tories |date=4 September 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wort.lu/en/politics/zdf-german-tv-interview-jean-asselborn-ashamed-of-hungary-pm-orban-55e968910c88b46a8ce5f66a |work=Luxemburger Wort |title=Jean Asselborn 'ashamed' of Hungary PM Orban}}</ref> German Foreign Minister [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] said that EU members reluctant to accept compulsory migrant quotas may have to be outvoted: \"if there is no other way, then we should seriously consider to use the instrument of a qualified majority\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11873936/Eastern-European-countries-may-be-forced-accept-quotas-for-migrants.html |title=Eastern European countries may be forced accept quotas for migrants |date=18 September 2015 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2015-09-22 EU JHA Council majority vote to relocate 120,000 refugees.svg|thumb|right|National governments' position in the European Union Justice and Home Affairs Council majority vote to relocate 120,000 refugees:\n{{legend|#8cd19d|Yes}}\n{{legend|#ff9000|[[Opt-outs in the European Union|Opt-out]]}}\n{{legend|#5cacc4|Abstention}}\n{{legend|#fa3d3f|No}}\n{{legend|#D6D6D6|Non-EU state}}]]\nLeaders of the [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] (Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia) declared in a September meeting in Prague that they will not accept any compulsory long-term quota on redistribution of immigrants.<ref>Ian Traynor. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/05/migration-crisis-europe-leaders-blame-brussels-hungary-germany Refugee crisis: east and west split as leaders resent Germany for waiving rules]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 5 September 2015.</ref> Czech Government's Secretary for European Affairs [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Prouza]] commented that \"if two or three thousand people who do not want to be here are forced into the Czech Republic, it is fair to assume that they will leave anyway. The quotas are unfair to the refugees, we can't just move them here and there like a cattle.\" According to the Czech interior minister [[Milan Chovanec]], from 2 September 2015, Czech Republic was offering asylum to every Syrian caught by the police notwithstanding the Dublin Regulation: out of about 1,300 apprehended until 9 September, only 60 decided to apply for asylum in the Czech Republic, with the rest of them continuing to Germany or elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novinky.cz/domaci/380081-nemuzeme-s-uprchliky-soupat-jako-s-dobytkem-odmitla-vlada-znovu-kvoty.html |title=Nem\u016f\u017eeme s uprchl\u00edky \u0161oupat jako s dobytkem, odm\u00edtla vl\u00e1da znovu kv\u00f3ty |date=9 September 2015 |publisher=Novinky.cz}}</ref>\n\nCzech President [[Milo\u0161 Zeman]] said that [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] refugees fleeing [[War in Donbass]] should be also included in migrant quotas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukrainian refugees should be among voluntarily accepted \u2013 Zeman |url=http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/ukrainian-refugees-should-be-among-voluntarily-accepted-zeman/1259473 |publisher=[[Czech News Agency|\u010cTK]] |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, the Czech Republic started a program of medical evacuations of selected Syrian refugees from Jordan (400 in total). Under the program, severely sick children were selected for treatment in the best Czech medical facilities, with their families getting asylum, airlift and a paid flats in the Czech Republic after stating clear intent to stay in the country. However, from the initial 3 families that had been transported to Prague, one immediately fled to Germany. Czech Prime Minister [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] stated that this signals that quota system will not work either.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/syrsti-azylanti-odesli-z-ceska-do-nemecka-f16-/domaci.aspx?c=A151106_160518_domaci_jj |title= Mal\u00ed Sy\u0159an\u00e9 se m\u011bli l\u00e9\u010dit v Motole, rodina obratem odjela do N\u011bmecka [Little Syrians were supposed to get treatment in Motol Hospital, a family immediately left to Germany] |date=9 November 2015 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 2015, France announced that it would accept 24,000 asylum-seekers over two years; Britain announced that it would take in up to 20,000 refugees, primarily vulnerable children and orphans from camps in Jordan, Lebanon and Turkey; and Germany pledged US$6.7 billion to deal with the migrant crisis.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/08/world/europe/europe-migrant-crisis.html|title=A Steady Flow Staggers into Europe, Outpacing Pledges of Shelter |author1=Rick Lyman |author2=Steven Erlange |author3=Aurelien Breeden |newspaper=The New York Times |date=7 September 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UK to accept 20,000 refugees from Syria by 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34171148 |accessdate=8 September 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=7 September 2007}}</ref> However, also on 7 September 2015, both Austria and Germany warned that they would not be able to keep up with the current pace of the influx and that it would need to slow down first.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/07/europe/europe-migrant-crisis/index.html |title=Migrant crisis: More troubles in Hungary as Austria, Germany near tipping point |author1=Holly Yan |author2=Arwa Damon |publisher=CNN |date=7 September 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2015, European Union interior ministers meeting in the [[Justice and Home Affairs Council]] approved a plan to relocate 120,000 asylum seekers over two years from the frontline states [[Italy]], [[Greece]] and [[Hungary]] to all other EU countries (except Denmark, Ireland and the United Kingdom which have [[Opt-outs in the European Union|opt-outs]]). The relocation plan applies to asylum seekers \"in clear need of international protection\" (those with a recognition rate higher than 75 percent, i.e. [[Syria]]ns, [[Eritrea]]ns and [[Iraq]]is) \u2013 15,600 from Italy, 50,400 from Greece and 54,000 from Hungary \u2013 who will be distributed among EU states on the basis of quotas taking into account the size of economy and population of each state, as well as the average number of asylum applications. The decision was taken by majority vote, with the [[Czech Republic]], [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] and [[Slovakia]] voting against and [[Finland]] abstaining. Since Hungary voted against the relocation plan, its 54,000 asylum seekers would not be relocated for now, and could be relocated from Italy and Greece instead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Why EU deal on refugees is difficult|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34324096|work=BBC News|date=25 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: EU ministers approve disputed quota plan|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34329825|work=BBC News|date=22 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Justice and Home Affairs Council, 22/09/2015|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/meetings/jha/2015/09/22/|publisher=Council of the European Union}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/23/world/europe/european-union-ministers-migrants-refugees.html|title=European Union Ministers Approve Plan to Distribute Refugees|author=James Kanter|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 September 2015|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref> Czech Interior Minister tweeted after the vote: \"Common sense lost today.\"<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/11883024/Europe-ministers-agree-relocation-of-120000-refugees-by-large-majority.html EU quota plan forced through against eastern European states' wishes]\". ''The Daily Telegraph''. 23 September 2015.</ref> Slovak Prime Minister [[Robert Fico]] is threatening legal action over EU's mandatory migrant quotas at [[European Court of Justice]] in Luxembourg.<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/23/eu-summit-brussels-divisive-deal-refugee-quotas EU braces for turbulent summit after divisive deal on refugee quotas]\". ''The Guardian''. 23 September 2015.</ref> On 9 October, the first 20 Eritrean asylum seekers were relocated by plane from Italy to Sweden,<ref>{{cite news|title=Eritrean refugees flown from Italy to Sweden in first EU quota relocation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/09/eritrean-refugees-italy-sweden-eu-quota-relocation|work=The Guardian|date=9 October 2015}}</ref> following the EU prerequisite [[fingerprinting]] in Italy as the first member country of asylum registration.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/10/world/europe/italy-sends-eritreans-to-sweden-as-eu-migrant-relocations-begin.html?ribbon-ad-idx=8&rref=world&module=Ribbon&version=origin&region=Header&action=click&contentCollection=World&pgtype=article|title=Italy Sends Eritreans to Sweden as E.U. Migrant Relocations Begin|author=Elisabetta Povoledo|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 October 2015|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2015, the leaders of Greece and other states along Western Balkan routes to wealthier nations of Europe, including Germany, agreed to set up holding camps for 100,000 asylum seekers, a move which German Chancellor Merkel supported.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/26/world/europe/merkel-and-east-european-leaders-discuss-migrant-crisis-in-brussels.html?ref=world|title=European Leaders Look Again for a Unified Response to Migrant Crisis|author=Andrew Higgins|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November it was reported that [[Frontex]] had been maintaining combined asylum seeker and deportation hotspots in Lesbos, Greece since October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deutsche-wirtschafts-nachrichten.de/2015/12/12/hotspots-fuer-fluechtlinge-das-haessliche-gesicht-deutschlands-und-der-eu/|title=Hotspots f\u00fcr Fl\u00fcchtlinge: Das h\u00e4ssliche Gesicht Deutschlands und der EU|date=12 December 2015|work=\u2013 DEUTSCHE WIRTSCHAFTS NACHRICHTEN}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 December 2015, the EU proposed taking over the border and coastal security operations at major migrant entry pressure points, via its Frontex operation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/16/world/europe/eu-borders-migrant-crisis.html|title=E.U. Pushes to Take Over Border Security at Migrant Pressure Points|author=James Kanter|newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 December 2015|accessdate=15 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy September 2016 the quota system proposed by EU has been abandoned for the time being, after staunch resistance by [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/migration/135576|title=EU buries migration dispute for now|website=EUobserver}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/schulz-admits-mandatory-relocation-of-refugees-has-failed/|title=Schulz admits mandatory relocation of refugees has failed|first=Georgi|last=Gotev|date=16 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 9 June 2017, 22,504 people have been resettled through the quota system, with over 2000 of them being resettled in May alone.<ref>{{cite web |title=RELOCATION AND RESETTLEMENT 13 JUNE 2017|date=13 June 2017|url=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/20170613_factsheet_relocation_and_resettlement_en.pdf |accessdate=26 August 2017|publisher=Euriopean Commission}}</ref> All relevant countries participate in the relocation scheme with exception of Austria, Denmark, Czech Republic, Poland, and Hungary,<ref>{{cite web|title=Relocation and Resettlement \u2013 State of Play |publisher=European Commission|date=8 February 2017|url=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/what-we-do/policies/european-agenda-migration/20170208_factsheet_on_relocation_and_resettlement_en.pdf|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref> against whom the European commission has consequentially launched sanctions procedure only to the Czech Republic, Poland, and Hungary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/eu-opens-sanctions-procedure-against-hungary-poland-and-czech-republic-over-refugees/|title=EU opens sanctions procedure against Hungary, Poland and Czech Republic over refugees|website=EURACTIV.com|date=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Crime by immigrants ====\n[[File:Aussetzen einer Belohnung Verbrechen in der Silvesternacht 2015-2016 K\u00f6ln -4597.jpg|thumb|During [[2015\u201316 New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany]], a poster showing the title \"Offering a Reward\" in both German and Arabic in Cologne.]]\nHistorically, migrants have often been portrayed as a \"security threat,\" and there has been much focus on the narrative that terrorists maintain networks amongst transnational, refugee, and migrant populations. This fear has been exaggerated into a modern-day Islamist terrorism Trojan Horse in which terrorists hide among refugees and penetrate host countries.<ref name=\"LinkstoCrime\">{{Cite journal|last=Schmid|first=Alex|year=2016|title=Links Between Terrorism and Migration: An Exploration|url=https://www.icct.nl/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Alex-P.-Schmid-Links-between-Terrorism-and-Migration-1.pdf|journal= Terrorism and Counter-Terrorism Studies|volume=|pages=|via=|doi=10.19165/2016.1.04}}</ref> In the wake of [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], Poland's European affairs minister-designate [[Konrad Szyma\u0144ski]] stated that he sees no possibility of enacting the EU refugee relocation scheme,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/poland-plans-to-backtrack-on-migrant-commitment-following-attacks-in-paris-a6734521.html |title=Poland says it cannot accept migrants under EU quotas, following attacks in Paris |newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> saying, \"We'll accept [refugees only] if we have security guarantees.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/11/14/uk-france-shooting-poland-reaction-idUKKCN0T30P920151114|title=Poland says cannot take migrants under EU quotas without guarantees after Paris attacks|agency=Reuters|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe attacks prompted European officials\u2014particularly German officials\u2014to re-evaluate their stance on EU policy toward migrants, especially in light of the ongoing European migrant crisis.<ref name=ParisAttacksMigrants1>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/16/world/europe/paris-attacks-shift-europes-migrant-focus-to-security.html?rref=collection%2Fnewseventcollection%2Fattacks-in-paris&action=click&contentCollection=europe&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=1&pgtype=collection|title=Paris Attacks Shift Europe's Migrant Focus to Security|author1=Rick Lyman |author2=Alison Smale |newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=ParisAttacksMigrants2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/11/14/world/europe/ap-eu-germany-migrants-rising-tensions.html|title=Paris Attacks Provoke Fresh Migrant Fears in Europe|author=Eldar Emric, Demetri Nellas, and the Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> Many German officials believed a higher level of scrutiny was needed, and criticised the position of German Chancellor Angela Merkel, but the German Vice-Chancellor [[Sigmar Gabriel]] defended her stance, and pointed out that a lot of migrants were fleeing terrorism.<ref name=ParisAttacksMigrants2/>\n\nIn January 2016, 18 of 31 men suspected of [[New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany|violent assaults on women]] in [[Cologne]] on [[New Year's Eve]] were identified as asylum seekers, prompting calls by German officials to deport convicted criminals who may be seeking asylum;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/09/world/europe/cologne-new-years-eve-attacks.html|title=18 Asylum Seekers Are Tied to Attacks on Women in Germany|author=Alison Smale|newspaper=The New York Times|date=8 January 2016|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> these sexual attacks brought about a fresh wave of anti-immigrant protests across Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/14/world/europe/a-climate-of-fear-widens-divisions-in-europes-migrant-crisis.html|title=Sexual Attacks Widen Divisions in European Migrant Crisis|author=Jim Yardley|newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 January 2016|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Merkel used [[Wir schaffen das]] during the violence and crime by the immigrants in Germany, including the [[2016 Munich shooting]], the [[2016 Ansbach bombing]], and the [[W\u00fcrzburg train attack]].<ref>{{cite news|title=After rampages, Merkel says again: Wir schaffen das|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20160728/merkel-says-again-wir-schaffen-das|agency=AFP|publisher=The Local|date=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, according to the Italian [[Daily newspaper|daily]] newspaper ''[[La Stampa]]'', officials from [[Europol]] conducted an investigation into the trafficking of fake documents for [[ISIL]]. They identified fake [[Syrian]] passports in the [[refugee camp]]s in [[Greece]] that were destined to supposed members of ISIL, in order to avoid Greek government controls and make their way to other parts of Europe. Also, the chief of Europol said that a new task force of 200 counter-terrorism officers would be deployed to the Greek islands alongside Greek border guards in order to help Greece stop a \"strategic\" level campaign by ISIL to infiltrate terrorists into Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2016/08/21/italia/in-europa-la-fabbrica-della-cittadinanza-cos-funziona-il-business-dei-passaporti-comprati-e0dWQ28J4sGXYEcJ0jWLOI/pagina.html|title=In Europa la fabbrica della cittadinanza: cos\u00ec funziona il business dei passaporti comprati|last=Scarcella|first=Roberto|date=2016-08-21|website=LaStampa.it|language=IT|access-date=2019-06-29}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016 Danish immigration minister [[Inger St\u00f8jberg]] authorities reported 50 cases of suspected radicalised asylum seekers at asylum centres. The reports encompassed everything from adult [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] sympathisers celebrating terror attacks to violent children who dress up as IS fighters decapitating teddy bears. St\u00f8jberg expressed her consternation at asylum seekers ostensibly fleeing war yet simultaneously supporting violence. Asylum centres having detected radicalisation routinely report their findings to police. The 50 incidents were reported between 17 November 2015 and 14 September 2016.<ref name=\"tv2_dk_22okt2016a\">{{cite news|title=IS-videoer, terrorjubel og halshugget bamse: 50 mistanker om radikalisering p\u00e5 asylcentre sendt til Udl\u00e6ndingestyrelsen|url=http://nyheder.tv2.dk/politik/2016-10-22-stoejberg-om-radikalisering-paa-asylcentre-der-er-alvorlige-sager-iblandt|accessdate=23 October 2016|publisher=[[TV 2 (Denmark)]]|date=22 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tv2_dk_22okt2016b\">{{cite news|title=St\u00f8jberg om radikalisering p\u00e5 asylcentre: Der er alvorlige sager iblandt|url=http://nyheder.tv2.dk/politik/2016-10-22-stoejberg-om-radikalisering-paa-asylcentre-der-er-alvorlige-sager-iblandt|accessdate=23 October 2016|publisher=[[TV2 (Denmark)]]|date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that ISIL was paying the smugglers fees of up to $2,000 [[USD]] to recruit people from refugee camps in Jordan and Lebanon child migrants in a desperate attempt to radicalize children for the group. The reports by counter-extremism thinktank [[Quilliam (think tank)|Quilliam]] indicate that an estimated 88,300 unaccompanied children\u2014who are reported as missing\u2014were at risk of radicalization by ISIL.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/05/isis-recruitment-drive-child-refugees|title=Isis paying smugglers' fees in recruitment drive among child refugees|last=Townsend|first=Mark|date=2017-02-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-07|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Hungary challenged EU plans to share asylum seekers across EU states at the European Court of Justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35158769 |title=Migrant crisis: One million enter Europe in 2015 |author=no by-line. |date=22 December 2015 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |access-date=22 December 2015}}</ref> The border has been closed since 15 September 2015, with razor wire fence along its southern borders, particularly Croatia, and by blocking train travel.<ref name=\"Noack\">{{cite news |last=Noack |first=Rick |date=22 December 2015|title=Over a million refugees and migrants arrived in Europe this year. Here is what you need to know. |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-million-refugees-migrants-europe-20151222-story.html |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |location=Chicago, USA |access-date=24 December 2015}}</ref> The government believes that \"illegal migrants\" are job-seekers, threats to security and likely to \"threaten our culture\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35162515 |title=Migrant crisis: Hungary denies fuelling intolerance in media |last=Thorpe |first=Nick |date=22 December 2015 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |access-date=24 December 2015}}</ref> There have been cases of immigrants and ethnic minorities being attacked. In addition, Hungary has conducted wholesale deportations of refugees, who are generally considered to be allied with [[ISIL]].<ref name=\"matthewweaver1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/sep/15/refugee-crisis-hungary-launches-border-crackdown-live-updates|title=Refugee crisis: Hungary rejects all asylum requests made at border \u2013 as it happened|author=Matthew Weaver|newspaper=the Guardian|date=15 September 2015}}</ref> Refugees are outlawed and almost all are ejected.<ref name=\"matthewweaver1\" />\n\n==== Crime on immigrants ====\n{{see also|Opposition to immigration}}\nThere can be instances of exploitation at the hands of enforcement officials, citizens of the host country, instances of human rights violations, child labor, mental and physical trauma/torture, violence-related trauma, and [[Sexual exploitation and abuse in humanitarian response|sexual exploitation]], especially of children, have been documented. <ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Aggrawal |first=A. |title=Refugee Medicine |year=2005 |veditors=Payne-James JJ, Byard RW, Corey TS, Henderson C |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Forensic and Legal Medicine |publisher=Elsevier Academic Press |location=London |volume=3|pp=514\u2013525}}</ref>\n\nOn October, [[2015 German refugee attack plot]] was foiled by German police which was a plot by [[neo-Nazis]] to attack a refugee center with explosives, knives, a baseball bat and a gun. Nazi magazines and memorabilia from the Third Reich, flags emblazoned with banned swastikas were found. According to prosecutor goal was \"to establish fear and terror among asylum-seekers\". The accused claimed to be either the members of Die Rechte, or anti-Islam group Pegida (N\u00fcgida). <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/germany-police-foil-neo-nazi-073146377.html#ioeGHQv|title=Germany: Police foil Neo-Nazi terror attack on refugee shelter}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the [[Euro-Med HRM|Euro-Mediterranean Human Rights Monitor]] issued a report regarding the humanitarian situation of migrants into [[Greece]]. It hosts 16.209 migrants on its island and 33.650 migrants on the mainland, most of whom are women and children. Because of lack of water, medical care and security protection witnessed by the Euro- Med monitor team- especially with the arrival of winter, they are at risk of serious deterioration in health, mostly children and pregnant women. 1,500 refugees were, accordingly, moved into other places since their camps were deluged with snow, but relocation of the refugees always came too late after they lived without electricity and heating devices for too long. It also showed that there is a lack of access to legal services and security protection to the refugees and migrants in the camps; there is no trust between the resident and the protection offices, paving a path for some people to report crimes and illegal acts in the camps. In addition, the migrants are subject to regular xenophobic attacks, fascist violence, forced strip searches at the hands of residents and police and detention. The women living in the Athens settlements and the [[Vasilika refugee camp|Vasilika]], [[Softex]] and [[Diavata]] camps feel worried about their children as they may be subjected to sexual abuse, trafficking and drug use. As a result, some of the refugees and migrants commit suicide, burn property and protest. Finally, it clarified the difficulties the refugees face when entering into Greece; more than 16,000 people are trapped while waiting for deportation on the Greek islands of [[Lesbos|Lesvos]], [[Chios]], [[Samos]], [[Leros]] and [[Kos]], and the number of residents is double the capacity of the five islands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://euromedmonitor.org/en/article/1703/Asylum-seekers-attempt-suicide-daily-as-they-face-desperate-circumstances-in-Greece|title=Asylum seekers attempt suicide daily as they face desperate circumstances in Greece|last=Monitor|first=Euro-Med|newspaper=Euro-Mediterranean|language=en|access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 dozens of Afghani asylum seekers made a demonstration in a square in Stockholm against their pending deportations. They were attacked by a group of 15\u201316 men who threw fireworks at them. Three protesters were injured and one was taken to hospital. None were arrested.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gp.se/nyheter/sverige/strejkande-ensamkommande-attackerade-1.4515731|title=Strejkande ensamkommande attackerade|work=G\u00f6teborgs-Posten|access-date=10 August 2017|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Profile of migrants==\n{{image frame|content={{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Map of the European Migrant Crisis 2015 - Asylum applicants' countries of origin.png{{!}}Countries of origin of asylum applicants in the EU and EFTA states between 1 January and 30 June 2015\n| photo2a= Hosted and departing refugees 2015.svg{{!}}This map shows the distribution of refugees and asylum seekers at the end of 2015 in the regions of Middle East, Africa and Europe while also showing the top 8 (data in millions) worldwide countries of origin of refugees (note that Turkey is out of scale, hosting 2.7 millions refugees while Palestinian refugees are not included; UNHCR data)\n| photo3a = Sea arrivals to Greece and Italy in 2015 by nationality.png{{!}}Nationalities of the Mediterranean sea arrivals to Greece and Italy in 2015, according to UNHCR data\n| photo3b= Carte des routes d'immigration africaine vers l'Europe.svg{{!}}Map of migrants' routes to North Africa and Europe from West Africa\n| photo3c= Syrian refugees in the Middle East map en.svg{{!}}Syrian refugees hosted in some Middle East countries (Turkey, Lebanon, Jordan, Iraq, and Egypt); only a small fraction of all Syrian refugees have been resettled anywhere in the world (data as of August 2015)\n| size = 270\n| spacing = 1\n| color = #FFFFFF\n| border = 3\n| color_border = gray\n| text = Countries of origin of asylum applicants (1 January \u2013 30 June 2015), Distribution of refugees and asylum seekers at 2015<ref name=\"UNHCR persons of concern\">{{cite web|url=http://popstats.unhcr.org/en/persons_of_concern|title=UNHCR persons of concern|date=10 November 2016}}</ref> Nationalities of the Mediterranean sea arrivals in 2015 <ref name=\"UNHCR2015\" />, Map of migrants' routes, Syrian refugees as of August 2015<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2015/09/syrias-refugee-crisis-in-numbers/ Syria's refugee crisis in numbers], Amnesty International, 4 September 2015</ref> \n| text_background = #FFDEAD\n}}\n| width = 278\n}}\n{{See also|Refugee crisis|List of countries by refugee population|Arab Winter|Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|Emigration from Africa}}\n\nAccording to the [[UNHCR]], the number of [[Displaced person|forcibly displaced people]] worldwide reached 59,500,000 at the end of 2014, the highest level since World War II,<ref>{{cite news |title=The Global Refugee Crisis, Region by Region |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/06/09/world/migrants-global-refugee-crisis-mediterranean-ukraine-syria-rohingya-malaysia-iraq.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 August 2015}}</ref> with a 40 percent increase taking place since 2011.  Of these 59.5&nbsp;million, 19.5&nbsp;million were [[refugees]] (14.4&nbsp;million under UNHCR's mandate, plus 5.1&nbsp;million [[Palestinian refugees]] under [[UNRWA]]'s mandate), and 1.8&nbsp;million were [[asylum-seekers]]. The rest were persons displaced within their own countries ([[internally displaced persons]]). The 14.4&nbsp;million refugees under UNHCR's mandate were around 2.7&nbsp;million more than at the end of 2013 (a 23 percent increase), the highest level since 1995. Among them, [[Syrian refugees]] became the largest refugee group in 2014 (3.9&nbsp;million, 1.55&nbsp;million more than the previous year), overtaking [[Afghan refugees]] (2.6&nbsp;million), who had been the largest refugee group for three decades. Six of the ten largest countries of origin of refugees were African: [[Somalia]], [[Sudanese refugees|Sudan]], [[South Sudan]], the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]], the [[Central African Republic]] and [[Eritrea]].<ref name=\"UNHCRtrends\">{{cite web |url=http://unhcr.org/556725e69.html |title=UNHCR Global Trends \u2013Forced Displacement in 2014 |publisher=UNHCR |date=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The dispossessed|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2015/06/daily-chart-15|work=The Economist|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the [[UNHCR]], the number of [[Displaced person|forcibly displaced people]] worldwide reached 65,600,000 at the end of 2016; the highest level since World War II. Of these 65,600,000, 22.5 million were [[refugees]] (17.2 million under UNHCR's mandate, plus 5.3 million [[Palestinian refugees]] under [[UNRWA]]'s mandate). 2.8 million of the refugees were asylum seekers. The rest were persons displaced within their own countries ([[internally displaced persons]]). The 17.2 million refugees under UNHCR's mandate were around 2.9 million more than at the end of 2014, the highest level since 1992.\n\nAs of 2017, 55 percent of refugees worldwide came from three nations: South Sudan, Afghanistan, and Syria. Of all displaced peoples, 17 percent of them are being hosted in Europe. As of April 2018, 15,481 refugees have successfully arrived to the shores of Europe via sea within the first few months of the year alone. There was an estimated 500 that have died in this year alone. In 2015, there was a total of 1.02 million arrivals by sea. Since then, the influx has steadily decreased but is ongoing nonetheless.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data2.unhcr.org/en/situations/mediterranean#_ga=2.97327127.949908654.1523126683-1807715582.1519328261|title=Situation Mediterranean Situation|website=data2.unhcr.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAccording to UNHCR data, 58 percent of the refugees and migrants arriving in Europe by sea in 2015 were men, 17 percent were women and 25 percent were children.<ref name=\"bsUNHCR2015\" /><ref name=\"abcUNHCR2015\" /> Of the asylum applications received in Sweden in 2015, 70 percent were by men (including minors).<ref name=sma2015/> Men search for a safe place to live and work before attempting to reunite later with their families.<ref name=\"UNHCRMed\"/> In war-torn countries, men are also at greater risk of being forced to fight or of being killed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/europes-man-problem/|title=Europe's man problem|publisher=Politico Europe|date=6 January 2016}}</ref> Among people arriving in Europe there were also large numbers of women and unaccompanied children.<ref name=\"UNHCRMed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/5592bd059.html#7 |title=The sea route to Europe: The Mediterranean passage in the age of refugees |page=7 |publisher=[[UNHCR]]}}</ref> Europe has received a record number of asylum applications from unaccompanied child refugees in 2015, as they became separated from their families in war, or their family could not afford to send more than one member abroad. Younger refugees also have better chances of receiving asylum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/young-and-alone-europe-sees-record-surge-of-child-refugees-1.1430278|title=Young and alone: Europe sees record surge of child refugees|author=Sylvia Hui, Associated Press|date=11 October 2015|accessdate=11 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020000722/http://www.northjersey.com/news/young-and-alone-europe-sees-record-surge-of-child-refugees-1.1430278|archivedate=20 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to UNHCR, the top ten nationalities of Mediterranean Sea arrivals in 2015 were [[Syria]] (49 percent), [[Afghanistan]] (21 percent), [[Iraq]] (8 percent), [[Eritrea]] (4 percent), [[Pakistan]] (2 percent), [[Nigeria]] (2 percent), [[Somalia]] (2 percent), [[Sudan]] (1 percent), [[the Gambia]] (1 percent) and [[Mali]] (1 percent).<ref name=\"bsUNHCR2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/over-1-million-arrivals-in-europe-by-sea-unhcr-115123000668_1.html|title=Over 1 million arrivals in Europe by sea: UNHCR|date=30 December 2015|work=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref><ref name=\"abcUNHCR2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-30/more-than-1-million-asylum-seekers-reached-europe-by-sea-in-2015/7060012|title=More than 1 million asylum seekers reached Europe by sea this year: UNHCR|date=30 December 2015|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> Asylum seekers of seven nationalities had an asylum recognition rate of over 50 percent in EU States in the first quarter of 2015, meaning that they obtained protection over half the time they applied: Syrians (94 percent recognition rate), Eritreans (90 percent), [[Iraq]]is (88 percent), Afghans (66 percent), [[Iran]]ians (65 percent), [[Somalia|Somalis]] (60 percent) and [[Sudan]]ese (53 percent). Migrants of these nationalities accounted for 90 percent of the arrivals in Greece and 47 percent of the arrivals in Italy between January and August 2015, according to UNHCR data.<ref name=\"Asylum quarterly report\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=How many migrants to Europe are refugees? |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2015/09/economist-explains-4 |work=The Economist |date=7 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n[[Developing countries]] hosted the largest share of refugees (86 percent by the end of 2014, the highest figure in more than two decades); the [[least developed countries]] alone provided asylum to 25 percent of refugees worldwide.<ref name=\"UNHCRtrends\"/> Even though most Syrian refugees were hosted by neighbouring countries such as [[Turkey]], [[Lebanon]] and [[Jordan]], the number of asylum applications lodged by Syrian refugees in Europe steadily increased between 2011 and 2015, totaling 813,599 in 37 European countries (including both EU members and non-members) as of November 2015; 57 percent of them applied for [[asylum in Germany]] or [[Serbia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria Regional Refugee Response|url=http://data.unhcr.org/syrianrefugees/asylum.php|publisher=UNHCR}}</ref> \n\n=== Origins, routes, motivations ===\n[[File:Aegean Sea with island groups labeled.gif|thumb|Island groups of the [[Aegean Sea]] ]]\n[[File:Greece\u2013Turkey land border.svg|thumb|Greek, Turkish and Bulgarian borders and the course of the [[Maritsa|Evros River]] (also known as Maritsa River)]]\n\nThe \"European Migrant Crisis\" refers to an enormous and  unprecedented wave of both war refugees from the [[Syrian Civil War]] and economic migrants from the Near East and Africa.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite book|title=The Politics of Migration and Immigration in Europe|date=2016|last=Geddes, Andrew|isbn=978-1-4739-8757-9|edition= 2nd|location=London|oclc=961205880}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAs of May 2017, [[Frontex]] (the European border and coast guard agency) identifies the following eight main routes on sea and on land used by irregular migrants to enter the EU:<ref>{{cite web |title=Migratory routes map |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/trends-and-routes/migratory-routes-map/ |accessdate=29 August 2015 |publisher=[[Frontex]]}}</ref>\n* ''Western African route'' (Sea passage from [[West Africa]]n countries, into the [[Canary Islands]], i.e. territory of [[Spain]])\n* ''Western Mediterranean route'' (Sea passage from [[North Africa]] to southern coast of Spain, also including the land route through the borders of [[Ceuta]] and [[Melilla]].)\n* ''Central Mediterranean route'' (Sea passage from North Africa (particularly [[Egypt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://regionalmms.org/index.php/research-publications/feature-articles/item/51|title=Migration through Egypt: The Safe Alternative to Libya?|access-date=28 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229032112/http://regionalmms.org/index.php/research-publications/feature-articles/item/51|archive-date=29 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Libya]]) towards [[Italy]] and [[Malta]] across the [[Mediterranean Sea]].) Most migrants taking to sea on this route do so on vessels operated by [[People smuggling|people smugglers]]. NGOs such as [[Save the Children]], [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|MSF]] and German organisation Sea Eye operate search-and-rescue ships in this area bringing migrants to Europe.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*''[[Apulia]] and [[Calabria]] route'' (Sea passage of migrants from Turkey and Egypt who enter Greece and then cross the [[Ionian Sea]] towards southern Italy. Since October 2014 this has been classified by Frontex as a subset of the Central Mediterranean route.)\n* ''Albania\u2013Greece circular route'' (Large number of illegal land border crossings whereby economic migrants from [[Albania]] cross into [[Greece]] for seasonal jobs and then return home.)\n* ''Western Balkan route'' (Land and sea route from the Greek-Turkish border, through [[North Macedonia]] and [[Serbia]] into [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] or [[Croatia]].<ref name=\"aljazeera.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/09/refugees-seeking-routes-border-closures-150916045558970.html|title=Refugees cross Croatia border in search of new route|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Mostly used by Asian immigrants (from [[Syria]], [[Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq]]) but also used by large numbers of migrants from [[Western Balkans|Western Balkan]] countries themselves, primarily [[Kosovo]]).\n* ''Eastern Mediterranean route'' (Passage used by migrants, mostly Asian, crossing from Turkey into EU via [[Greece]], [[Bulgaria]] or [[Cyprus]]. Large portions of these migrants continue along the Western Balkan route towards Hungary or Romania.)\n* ''Eastern Borders route'' (The 6,000&nbsp;km long land border between EU's eastern member countries and [[Russia]], [[Belarus]], [[Ukraine]] and [[Moldova]].)\nIn addition:\n* ''An Arctic route'' (from Russia via to [[S\u00f8r-Varanger]] in [[Norway]]) had emerged by September 2015<ref name=ArcticRoute/> and was becoming one of the fastest-growing routes to enter [[Western Europe]] by November 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2015/11/11/world/asia/11reuters-europe-migrants-arctic.html?ref=world&_r=0|title=Growing Number of Asylum Seekers Opt for Arctic Route to Enter Europe|author=Catherine Evans|newspaper=The New York Times|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> This route was closed for a while in 2016, after Russia and Norway decided to curb movement through Salla and Lotta for migrants, allowing only Russian, Norwegian and Belarusian citizens to access it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/657646/Russia-SHUTS-DOWN-border-Europe-fears-new-migrant-route-ARCTIC|title=Russia SHUTS DOWN border with Europe amid fears over new migrant route through the ARCTIC|first=Oli|last=Smith|date=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic migrants ====\nMigrants from the [[Western Balkans]] ([[Kosovo]], [[Albania]], [[Serbia]]) and parts of [[West Africa]] ([[The Gambia]], [[Nigeria]]) are more likely to be [[economic migrants]], fleeing poverty and lack of jobs, many of them hoping for a better lifestyle and job offers, without valid claims to [[Convention relating to the Status of Refugees|refugee status]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mass Migration: What Is Driving the Balkan Exodus? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/western-balkan-exodus-puts-pressure-on-germany-and-eu-a-1049274.html |work=Der Spiegel |date=26 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=NossiterNiger>{{cite news |last1=Nossiter |first1=Adam |title=Migrant Smuggling Business Is Booming in Niger, Despite Crackdown |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/world/africa/migrant-smuggling-business-is-booming-in-niger-despite-crackdown.html?ref=world&_r=0 |accessdate=20 August 2015 |work=The New York Times |date=20 August 2015}}</ref> The majority of asylum applicants from [[Serbia]], [[North Macedonia]] and [[Montenegro]] are [[Romani people|Roma]] people who feel discriminated against in their countries of origin.<ref name=\"BalkanExodus\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34173252|title=Migrant crisis: Explaining the exodus from the Balkans|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> \n\nSome argue that migrants have been seeking to settle preferentially in those national destinations offering more generous [[social welfare]] benefits and hosting more established Middle Eastern and African immigrant communities. Others argue that migrants are attracted to more tolerant societies with stronger economies, and that the chief motivation for leaving Turkey is that they are not permitted to leave camps or work.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/13/world/europe/eastern-europe-migrant-refugee-crisis.html|title=Eastern Bloc's Resistance to Refugees Highlights Europe's Cultural and Political Divisions|author=Rick Lyman|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> A large number of refugees in Turkey have been faced with rather difficult living circumstances.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Villasana |first1=Danielle |title=Picturing health: challenges for Syrian refugees in Turkey |journal=The Lancet |date=October 2016 |volume=388 |issue=10056 |pages=2096\u2013103 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31647-6 |pmid=27642017 }}</ref> Thus, many refugees arriving in southern Europe continue their journey in attempts to reach northern European countries such as Germany, which are observed as having more prominent outcomes of security.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unhcr.org/en-us/protection/operations/5592bd059/sea-route-europe-mediterranean-passage-age-refugees.html|title=The sea route to Europe: The Mediterranean passage in the age of refugees|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|newspaper=UNHCR|access-date=16 November 2016}}</ref> In contrast to Germany, historically a popular final destination for the EU migrants, France saw its popularity erode in 2015 among migrants seeking asylum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/18/world/europe/a-belated-welcome-in-france-is-drawing-few-migrants.html|title=A Belated Welcome in France Is Drawing Few Migrants|author=Adam Nossiter|newspaper=The New York Times|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=17 September 2015|quote=Migrants crowding onto the trains in Hungary shout, \"Germany, Germany!\" But they do not shout, \"France, France.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/09/10/world/europe/scale-of-migrant-crisis-in-europe.html|title=The Scale of the Migrant Crisis, From 160 to Millions|author1=Gregor Aisch |author2=Sarah Almukhtar |author3=Josh Keller |author4=Wilson Andrews |newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 September 2015|accessdate=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe influx from states like [[Nigeria]] and [[Pakistan]] is a mix of economic migrants and refugees fleeing from violence and war such as [[Boko Haram insurgency]] in north-east Nigeria and the [[War in North-West Pakistan]].<ref name=\"origins\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Who does the EU send back?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34190359|work=BBC News|date=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Europe's forgotten migrants \u2013 the ones who aren't from Syria|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-europe-forgotten-migrants-20150916-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Escaping from conflicts \u2013 persecution ====\n[[Refugee]]s are people forced to flee their country of origin because of persecution, war, or violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unrefugees.org/refugee-facts/what-is-a-refugee/|title=What is a Refugee? Definition and Meaning |publisher=USA for UNHCR|access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAscertaining motivation is complex, but, according to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]], most of the people arriving in Europe in 2015 were [[refugees]], fleeing war and [[persecution]]<ref name=\"UNHCRarrivals\"/> in countries such as [[Syria]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Iraq]] and [[Eritrea]]: according to [[UNHCR]] data, 84 percent of Mediterranean Sea arrivals in 2015 came from the world's top ten refugee-producing countries.<ref name=\"UNHCRarrivals1\">{{cite news|title=Over one million sea arrivals reach Europe in 2015|url=http://www.unhcr.org/5683d0b56.html|work=UNHCR|date=30 December 2015 |accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Wars fueling the crisis are the [[Syrian Civil War]] and the [[Iraq conflict (2003\u2013present)|Iraq War]], the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]], the [[Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)|War in Somalia]] and the [[War in Darfur]]. Refugees from [[Eritrea]], one of the [[Human rights in Eritrea|most repressive]] states in the world, flee from indefinite military [[conscription]] and [[forced labour]].<ref name=\"origins\">{{cite news|title=Refugee crisis: apart from Syrians, who is travelling to Europe?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/10/refugee-crisis-apart-from-syrians-who-else-is-travelling-to-europe|work=The Guardian|date=10 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=It's not at war, but up to 3% of its people have fled. What is going on in Eritrea?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/22/eritrea-migrants-child-soldier-fled-what-is-going|work=The Guardian|date=22 July 2015}}</ref> Some ethnicities or religions from an originating country are more represented among the migrants than others, for instance Kurds make up 80 to 90 percent of all Turkish refugees in Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/asyl-in-deutschland-auffallend-viele-kurdische-fluechtlinge/14446010.html|title=Auffallend viele kurdische Fl\u00fcchtlinge|website=tagesspiegel.de}}</ref>\n\nRefugees coming specifically from the Middle East have been attempting to seek asylum in Europe rather than in countries surrounding their own neighboring regions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/your-guide-to-europes-migrant-crisis/|title=A region-by-region guide to the Middle East's migrant crisis|newspaper=PBS NewsHour|language=en-US|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref> In 2015, over 80 percent of the refugees who arrived in Europe by sea, came from Syria, Iraq, and Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-24583286|title=Why is EU struggling with migrants and asylum?|date=3 March 2016|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref> Routes in which these refugees face while attempting to arrive in Europe, are most often extremely dangerous.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daynes|first=Leigh|date=1 October 2016|title=The health impacts of the refugee crisis: a medical charity perspective|journal=Clinical Medicine|language=en|volume=16|issue=5|pages=437\u2013440|doi=10.7861/clinmedicine.16-5-437|pmid=27697805|pmc=6297302|issn=1470-2118}}</ref> The jeopardy to endure such routes also supports the arguments behind certain refugees' preferential motivations of seeking asylum within European nations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unhcr.org/en-us/protection/operations/5592bd059/sea-route-europe-mediterranean-passage-age-refugees.html|title=The sea route to Europe: The Mediterranean passage in the age of refugees|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|newspaper=UNHCR|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Major groups ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable toptextcells zebra\" style=\"text-align:right; float: right;\"\n|+Asylum seekers in percent / year<ref name=\"Eurostat2015-2017\">[http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/7203832/3-04032016-AP-EN.pdf/790eba01-381c-4163-bcd2-a54959b99ed6 ''Record number of over 1.2 million first time asylum seekers registered in 2015.''] (44/2016) 4. March 2016; [http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/7921609/3-16032017-BP-EN.pdf/e5fa98bb-5d9d-4297-9168-d07c67d1c9e1 ''1.2 million first time asylum seekers registered in 2016''] (46/2017) 16. March 2017; [http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/8754388/3-20032018-AP-EN.pdf/50c2b5a5-3e6a-4732-82d0-1caf244549e3 ''Asylum in the EU Member States: 650 000 first-time asylum seekers registered in 2017''] (47/2018) 20. March 2018</ref>\n! Sort !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017\n|-\n|[[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|Syrian]]             ||style=\"background: yellow;|29%     ||style=\"background: yellow;|28%     ||16%\n|-\n|Undeclared             ||26%     ||28%     ||style=\"background: yellow;|40%\n|-\n|[[Afghan refugees|Afghanistan]]        ||14%     || 15%    ||{{0}}7%\n|-\n|[[Refugees of Iraq|Iraq]]               ||10%     ||11%     ||{{0}}7%\n|-\n|Albanian       ||{{0}}5% ||{{0}}2% ||{{0}}3%\n|-\n|Bangladesh    || \u2013     || \u2013     ||{{0}}3%\n|-\n|Ivory Coast || \u2013     || \u2013     ||{{0}}2%\n|-\n|Eritrea        ||{{0}}3% ||{{0}}3% ||{{0}}4%\n|-\n|Guinea         || \u2013     || \u2013     ||{{0}}3%\n|-\n|Iran               ||{{0}}2% ||{{0}}3% ||{{0}}3%\n|-\n|Kosovo         ||{{0}}5% || \u2013     || \u2013\n|-\n|Nigeria            ||{{0}}2% ||{{0}}4% ||{{0}}6%\n|-\n|Pakistan           ||{{0}}4% ||{{0}}4% ||{{0}}5%\n|-\n|Russia       || \u2013     ||{{0}}2% ||\n|-\n|Turkey             || \u2013     || \u2013     ||{{0}}2%\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Syria ====\nThe greatest number of refugees fleeing to Europe [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|originate from Syria]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} Their migration stems from severe socio-political oppression under [[Bashar al-Assad|President Bashar al-Assad]]. Civil war ensued with clashes between pro and anti-government groups. Anti-government forces were supported by external governments (including the US, UK and France<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.enca.com/hollande-confirms-french-delivery-arms-syrian-rebels|title=Hollande confirms French delivery of arms to Syrian rebels|date=21 August 2014|work=AFP|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>) in an effort to topple the Syrian government via classified programs such as [[Timber Sycamore]] that effectively delivered thousands of tons of weaponry to rebel groups.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/world/middleeast/cia-arms-for-syrian-rebels-supplied-black-market-officials-say.html|title=C.I.A. Arms for Syrian Rebels Supplied Black Market, Officials Say|access-date=2018-10-04|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/59374/us-arms-shipment-to-syrian-rebels-detailed|title=US arms shipment to Syrian rebels detailed {{!}} IHS Jane's 360|date=2016-12-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205081205/http://www.janes.com/article/59374/us-arms-shipment-to-syrian-rebels-detailed|archive-date=2016-12-05|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-ends-covert-cia-program-to-arm-anti-assad-rebels-in-syria-a-move-sought-by-moscow/2017/07/19/b6821a62-6beb-11e7-96ab-5f38140b38cc_story.html|title=Trump ends covert CIA program to arm anti-Assad rebels in Syria, a move sought by Moscow|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/what-the-demise-of-the-cias-anti-assad-program-means/2017/07/20/f6467240-6d87-11e7-b9e2-2056e768a7e5_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} What the demise of the CIA's anti-Assad program means|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/21/tony-thomas-syria-secret-program-cia-240818|title=Top general confirms end to secret U.S. program in Syria|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-10-04|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/02/world/middleeast/cia-syria-rebel-arm-train-trump.html|title=Behind the Sudden Death of a $1 Billion Secret C.I.A. War in Syria|access-date=2018-10-04|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/plans-to-send-heavier-weapons-to-cia-backed-rebels-in-syria-stall-amid-white-house-skepticism/2016/10/23/f166ddac-96ee-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Plans to send heavier weapons to CIA-backed rebels in Syria stall amid White House skepticism|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/creeping-incrementalism-us-forces-and-strategy-iraq-and-syria-2011-2016-update|title=Creeping Incrementalism: U.S. Forces and Strategy in Iraq and Syria from 2011 to 2016: An Update|website=csis.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref> In 2011, a group of Syrians displayed pro-democracy protests in the city of [[Daraa]]. [[President of Syria|Syrian President]] [[Bashar al-Assad]] responded with force and consequently, more protests were triggered nationwide against the Assad regime. By July 2011, hundreds of thousands of people were protesting against President Assad. An early violent crackdown was implemented to try to mitigate these uprisings\u2014however, these measures were met with more unrest. By [[Arab Spring|May 2011]], thousands of people had already fled the country and the first refugee camps opened in Turkey. In March 2012, the UNHCR decided to appoint a Regional Refugee Coordinator for Syrian Refugees\u2014recognising the growing concerns surrounding the crisis. Just a year later, in March 2013, the number of Syrian refugees reached 1,000,000. By December 2017, [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]] counted 1,000,000 asylum applications for Syrian refugees in the European Union. As of March 2018, UNHCR has counted nearly 5.6 million registered Syrian refugees worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data2.unhcr.org/en/situations/syria|title=Situation Syria Regional Refugee Response|website=data2.unhcr.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==== Afghanistan ====\n[[Afghan refugees]] comprise the second-largest refugee population in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unhcr.org/en-us/afghanistan.html|title=Afghanistan|publisher=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en}}</ref> According to the UNHCR, there are almost 2.5 million registered refugees from Afghanistan. Most of these refugees have fled the region due to war and persecution. The majority have resettled in Pakistan and Iran, but it is becoming increasingly common to migrate further west to the European Union. Afghanistan has faced nearly 40 years of conflict dating back to the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|Soviet invasion in 1979]]. Since then, the nation has faced fluctuating levels of [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|civil war]] amidst unending unrest. The increase in refugee numbers has been credited primarily to the [[Taliban]] presence within Afghanistan. Their retreat in 2001, led to nearly 6 million Afghan refugees returning to their homeland. However, after [[Taliban insurgency|civil unrest and fighting alongside the Taliban's return]], nearly 2.5 million refugees have fled Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rescue.org/article/afghanistan-what-you-need-know-about-one-worlds-longest-refugee-crises|title=Afghanistan: What you need to know about one of the world's longest refugee crises|date=2016-09-08|work=International Rescue Committee (IRC)|access-date=2018-04-07|language=en}}</ref> Most Afghan refugees, however, seek refuge in the neighboring nation of Pakistan. Increasing numbers, though, have committed to the strenuous migration to Turkey and the European Union.\n\n== Developments ==\n[[File:Wien - Demo Mensch sein in \u00d6sterreich - 8.jpg|thumb|\"Syrian Refugees Welcome\" rally in [[Vienna]], 31 August 2015]]\n===Austria===\n{{flagu|Austria}} \u2013 On 6 August 2015, [[Amnesty International]] Secretary General [[Heinz Patzelt]] inspected the refugee camp ''Bundesbetreuungsstelle'' in [[Traiskirchen]] where more than 4,800 migrants/refugees are housed. Medical expert [[Siroos Mirzaei]] from Amnesty International noted that the people had to wait for days in order to get medical help, this due to the vast number of people received over a short period of time. The report also stated that four doctors were present at the refugee camp and that showers and some hygienic facilities were in disrepair. Patzelt claimed, \"Austria is currently violating human rights and should focus on unattended children and minors\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.at/de/traiskirchen-pa2/ |title=Traiskirchen Symptom systematischer M\u00e4ngel im Umgang mit Asylwerbern |publisher=Amnesty International \u00d6sterreich |accessdate=28 August 2015 |language=de |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814130015/https://www.amnesty.at/de/traiskirchen-pa2/ |archivedate=14 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Immigranten beim Grenz\u00fcbergang Wegscheid (23128928661).jpg|thumb|Migrants in Austria, November 2015]]\nOn 27 August 2015, 71 migrants were found dead in an unventilated food truck near [[Vienna]].<ref>see also [[:de:Fl\u00fcchtlingstrag\u00f6die bei Parndorf|German Wikipedia]]{{Better source|date=June 2016|reason=[[WP:CIRCULAR]]}}</ref> As an official response to this event, on 31 August 2015, Austria began inspections of vehicles for smuggled immigrants entering from across the border with Hungary, leading to vehicular backups of 19&nbsp;km (12&nbsp;mi) and trains stalled for hours.<ref name=StrainedOpenBorders>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/01/world/europe/austria-migrant-crisis-truck.html|title=Migrant Crisis Tests Core European Value: Open Borders |author1=Alison Smale |author2=Melissa Eddy |newspaper=The New York Times |date=31 August 2015 |accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nLate on 4 September 2015, Chancellor [[Werner Faymann]] of Austria, in conjunction with Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] of Germany, announced that migrants would be allowed to cross the border from Hungary into Austria and onward to Germany, and early on 5 September 2015, buses with migrants began crossing the Austro-Hungarian border.<ref name=AllowedToCross1>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/05/world/europe/migrant-crisis-hungary.html|title=Migrants Cross Austria Border From Hungary |author1=Rick Lyman |author2=Anemona Hartocollis |author3=Alison Smale |newspaper=The New York Times |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=AllowedToCross2>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/the-latest-austria-germany-to-accept-bused-migrants/ar-AAdWjak?li=BBgzzfc&ocid=iehp |title=The Latest: Austria, Germany to accept bused migrants |publisher=MSN |access-date=5 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015140038/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/the-latest-austria-germany-to-accept-bused-migrants/ar-AAdWjak?li=BBgzzfc&ocid=iehp |archive-date=15 October 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Austria noted that 6,500 migrants had crossed the border by the afternoon of 5 September 2015, with 2,200 already on their way to Germany.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/06/world/europe/migrant-crisis-austria-hungary-germany.html|title=Thousands of Migrants Reach Austria as New Groups Set Off |author1=Alison Smale |author2=Steven Erlanger |newspaper=The New York Times |date=5 September 2015 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euronews.com/2015/09/05/relieved-migrants-cross-hungary-austria-border/ |title=Relieved migrants cross Hungary-Austria border |publisher=euronews |date=5 September 2015 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015, Austria followed Germany's suit and instituted border controls of its own at the border with Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/15/world/europe/europe-migrants-germany.html|title=Austria, Slovakia and the Netherlands Introduce Border Controls|newspaper=The New York Times|author1=Melissa Eddy |author2=Dan Bilefsky |date=14 September 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> Austrian authorities also deployed the [[Austrian Army]] to the border with Hungary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rt.com/news/315239-austria-army-border-checks/|title=Austria deploys army to boost refugee checks, Slovakia brings back border controls|work=RT English|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/09/14/uk-europe-migrants-austria-idUKKCN0RE0SZ20150914|title=Austria says army will help impose tougher border checks|agency=Reuters UK|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 2015, Austria permitted entry to approximately 10,000 migrants from Slovenia and Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/20/world/europe/thousands-flood-into-austria-as-refugees-are-bounced-around-europe.html|title=Thousands of Migrants Flood into Austria|author1=Sewell Chan |author2=Palko Karasz |newspaper=The New York Times|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> Austria has taken on the role of regulator of the flow of migrants destined for Germany by feeding, housing and providing them health care in transit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/22/world/europe/austria-takes-on-role-of-distribution-center-for-migrants.html|title=Austria Takes Role of Distribution Center for Germany-Bound Migrants|author1=Palko Karasz |author2=Barbara Surk |newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 September 2015|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 October 2015, Austria decided to build a fence along its border with Slovenia (that has a total length of 91&nbsp;km<ref name=\"ld\">{{cite web|url=http://www.laenderdaten.de/geographie/grenzen.aspx|title=Staatsgrenzen \u2013 Grenzl\u00e4nge, K\u00fcstenl\u00e4nge und Grenzl\u00e4nder aller Staaten der Welt|work=laenderdaten.de|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>) to \"be able to control the migrants in an orderly manner\", said Minister of the Interior [[Johanna Mikl-Leitner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/austria-build-slovenia-border-fence-control-migrant-flow-081818360.html|title=Austria to build Slovenia border fence to 'control' migrant flow|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2016, Austria announced it would limit the number of asylum applicants to 37,500 in each of the next four years, compared to the 90,000 applications in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Austria to slash asylum claims|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-35364768|work=BBC News|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> On 19 February 2016, Austria started putting a daily cap of 80 asylum seekers allowed to enter the country to apply for Austrian asylum, and a maximum of 3,200 allowed daily to transit towards other countries (de facto most of them to Germany). The EU's migration commissioner said the cap was incompatible with Austria's obligations under EU and international law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Austria asylum cap begins despite EU anger|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35609823|work=BBC News|date=19 February 2016}}</ref> The EU Council of Ministers' legal team however concluded that Austria's moves are not illegal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/asylum-seekers-limit-not-illegal-council-legal-opinion-commission-migration/|title=Council lawyers: Austria's refugee cap not illegal|date=4 March 2016|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Austrian authorities planned to stop providing food and accommodation to rejected asylum applicants. The proposed legislation introduces penalties between \u20ac5000 to \u20ac15000 for those who remain in Austria with those refusing to leave to be detained. The applicant [[Identity fraud|lying about his identity]] would face a \u20ac5000 fine.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/austria-plans-tougher-measures-against-refused-asylum-seekers/a-37750857|title=Austria plans tougher measures against refused asylum seekers {{!}} DW {{!}} 28.02.2017|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> According to the interior ministry, application from Afghans, Nigerians and Pakistanis had mainly been rejected.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nFrom April 2018, Austrian authorities would confiscate mobile phones of migrants in order to use its geographical data to verify how the migrant arrived to the country. If migrants are found to have entered via a country covered by the Dublin regulation, they will be sent there. To cover the cost of handling the application, 840 euro is demanded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180418-austria-seize-refugees-mobiles-demand-cash|title=Austria to seize refugees' mobiles and demand cash|date=2018-04-18|work=France 24|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Bulgaria===\n{{flagu|Bulgaria}} \u2013 Bulgaria built a fence along its border with Turkey to prevent migrants from crossing through its territory in order to reach other EU countries. The fence is equipped with infrared cameras, motion sensors and wire, and is monitored by the army.<ref name=\"Lyman 2015\">{{cite news | last=Lyman | first=Rick | title=Bulgaria Puts Up a New Wall, but This One Keeps People Out | website=The New York Times | date=5 April 2015 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/06/world/europe/bulgaria-puts-up-a-new-wall-but-this-one-keeps-people-out.html | accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3183352/How-Bulgaria-keeps-migrants-50-miles-razor-wire-Fence-Turkish-border-15ft-tall-5ft-wide-said-kept-500-people-month.html |title=Bulgaria keeps migrants out with 50 miles of razor wire along Turkish border |work=Daily Mail}}</ref>\n\n===Croatia===\n{{flagu|Croatia}} \u2013 Croatia will receive 1,064<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24sata.hr/svijet/juncker-predstavlja-svoj-plan-u-hrvatsku-ce-1064-izbjeglice-436389|title=Potvr\u0111ene najave: Hrvatska \u0107e morati primiti 1064 izbjeglice|work=24sata.hr|accessdate=19 September 2015|language=hr}}</ref> migrants in the next two years from 2015 according to the EU plan. Croatia was originally supposed to receive 505 migrants, but decided to accept more\u2014which makes it the only country in the EU, along with Estonia, which has done so.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hr.n1info.com/a62086/Svijet/Svijet/Spanjolska-nece-primiti-3000-izbjeglica-dio-ide-u-Hrvatsku.html |title=\u0160panjolska ne\u0107e primiti 3000 izbjeglica, dio ide u Hrvatsku |work=N1 HR}}</ref> On 29 August 2015 a Croatian daily newspaper ''[[Jutarnji list]]'' published an interview with a \"senior government official\" who said that the Croatian Government formed an interdepartmental working group that is working on a plan on how to accept these migrants. Croatia will in October 2015 send its delegation to the migrants' camps in Italy and Greece, which will choose immigrants from Syria and Eritrea that Croatia will accept. Criteria for the selection will be: 1. any kind of connection to Croatia, such as family in Croatia or a diploma from one of the Croatian Universities (while Croatia was member of [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], many foreigners from [[Non-Aligned Movement]] countries, especially Syrians, were coming to Croatia to study), 2. education in occupations that are in demand in Croatia, and 3. families with small children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/je-li-hrvatska-spremna-za-izbjeglicki-val--zelimo-skolovane-izbjeglice--najbolje-s-djecom/1406645/|title=JE LI HRVATSKA SPREMNA ZA IZBJEGLI\u010cKI VAL? \u017delimo \u0161kolovane izbjeglice, najbolje s djecom |work=jutarnji.hr}}</ref> In addition, Croatia shares a land border with Serbia. Therefore, there is a risk of a strong inflow of migrants from Serbia considering that Hungary erected a fence on its border with Serbia. Nearly 80 percent of the border consists of the Danube river, but the problem is the 70 kilometers long so-called \"Green Border\" near [[Tovarnik]]. According to the Croatian Minister of Interior [[Ranko Ostoji\u0107]] \"police in the area has enough people and equipment to protect Croatian border against illegal immigrants\".<ref name=\"auto8\" /> Croatian President [[Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107]] and First Deputy Prime Minister [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]] rejected the option of building a fence on Croatian border with Serbia.<ref name=\"auto9\" /><ref name=\"auto10\" /> Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107 has accused German Chancellor Angela Merkel of causing \"chaos\".<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/angela-merkel/11883426/Croatia-president-blames-Angela-Merkel-for-refugee-crisis.html Croatia president blames Angela Merkel for refugee crisis]\". ''The Daily Telegraph''. 22 September.</ref> In expectancy of possible new migrant wave that might activate in winter of 2016, President Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107 stated on 21 September 2016 before the UN General Assembly that \"if a new migrant wave reaches Croatian borders, Croatia would not let migrants pass through its territory\" because Croatia needed to protect its territory, adding that it turned out that over 85 percent of them were economic migrants and not genuine refugees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.index.hr/clanak.aspx?id=920755|title=Kolinda ka\u017ee da Hrvatska ne\u0107e propu\u0161tati izbjeglice i da su to ionako ve\u0107inom ekonomski migranti|website=index.hr}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Anti-imigration-rally-Prague-Aug2015.jpg|thumbnail|Anti-immigration rally called \"For our culture and safe country\" in Prague, [[Czech Republic]], 12 September 2015]]\n[[File:Prorefugee protest Prague.jpg|thumbnail|Pro-migration rally in [[Prague]], Czech Republic, 12 September 2015]]\nCroatia, an EU member state [[2013 enlargement of the European Union|since 2013]], shares a land border (527&nbsp;km) with Serbia and therefore experienced a strong inflow of migrants from Serbia after [[Hungary\u2013Serbia barrier|Hungary erected a fence on its border with Serbia]]. Nearly 80 percent of the border consists of the [[Danube River]], but there is a 70 kilometer-long segment of land border in [[Syrmia]], in the forests and fields near [[Tovarnik]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} Also, parts of the Croatia-Serbia border are known [[minefields in Croatia|minefields]], which represent a considerable threat. According to the Croatian Minister of Interior [[Ranko Ostoji\u0107]], \"police in the area have enough people and equipment to protect the Croatian border against illegal immigrants\".<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/hrvatska/bajakovo-i-tovarnik-kriticne-tocke-na-zelenoj-granici-sa-srbijom-kroz-koju-bi-emigranti-mogli-ilegalno-uci-u-hrvatsku-1019618 |title=Hrvatska na udaru imigranata, krizne to\u010dke Bajakovo i Tovarnik |work=Ve\u010dernji list}}</ref> Croatian President [[Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107]] and First Deputy Prime Minister [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]] have so far rejected the option of building a fence along the Croatian border with Serbia.<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web |url=http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/svijet/grabar-kitarovic-hrvatska-nece-graditi-zidove-prema-srbiji-kao-madjarska---390052.html |title=Grabar Kitarovi\u0106: Hrvatska ne\u0107e graditi zidove prema Srbiji kao Ma\u0111arska |author=T.V. |work=Dnevnik.hr}}</ref><ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/-hrvatska-nece-graditi-zidove-ako-val-izbjeglica-krene-prema-nama--vesna-pusic-iskazala-prezir-prema-madarskom-rjesenju/1405895/ |title='HRVATSKA NE\u0106E GRADITI ZIDOVE AKO VAL IZBJEGLICA KRENE PREMA NAMA' Vesna Pusi\u0107 iskazala prezir prema ma\u0111arskom rje\u0161enju |work=Jutarnji.hr}}</ref> Croatian Prime Minister [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] said his country is ready to help refugees coming to Europe, insisting that people fleeing conflict should be given the right to remain in the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/croatian-pm-offers-help-for-refugees-08-31-2015|title=Croatian PM Pledges Help for Refugees|publisher=balkaninsight.com|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 September 2015, Croatia started to experience the first major waves of refugees, who carved out a new route through Europe after Hungary sealed its borders.<ref name=\"aljazeera.com\"/> On 15 September 2015, Hungary announced it would start arresting people crossing the border illegally, and as of early 16 September, Hungary had detained 519 people and pressed criminal charges against 46 for trespassing.<ref name=AlternateCroatia/> Thousands of migrants were subsequently led to pursue alternative routes through Croatia from Serbia.<ref name=AlternateCroatia>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/17/world/europe/europe-refugee-migrant-crisis.html|title=Migrants Clash With Police in Hungary, as Others Enter Croatia|author1=Rick Lyman |author2=Dan Bilefsky |newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 September 2015|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> After Hungary closed its border with Serbia on 15 September, migrants headed towards the Serbian town of [[\u0160id]], less than 10 kilometers from the Croatian border. Several buses filled with migrants arrived on the Croatian border crossing of [[Tovarnik]], where the Croatian [[Vukovar-Srijem County]] Care and Rescue teams as well as the [[Croatian Red Cross]] were on standby awaiting migrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/pogledajte-video-i-fotografije-iz-tovarnika/842208.aspx|title=Ovako je danas bilo u Tovarniku: Preko polja se do Hrvatske probijala i djevojka u kolicima|work=index.hr|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> On 17 September, as of 3:30&nbsp;am, more than 5,000 migrants had arrived in Tovarnik.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/foto--izbjeglicka-drama-u-hr-u-hrvatsku-uslo-5650-izbjeglica--u-tovarniku-situacija-izmakla-kontroli/1419579/|title=FOTO, VIDEO: SITUACIJA SVE TE\u017dA Drama u Slavoniji: Vlaka jo\u0161 uvijek nema, a izbjeglice nemaju ni kapi vode! U Dugavama azilant ga\u0111ao ciglom fotoreportera, s balkona hotela vi\u010du: 'Sloboda' |work=jutarnji.hr}}</ref> Interior Minister [[Ranko Ostoji\u0107]] said Croatia was \"absolutely full\" by the evening of 17 September 2015, and Croatia decided to close its border with Serbia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34286432|title=Migrant crisis: Croatia closes border crossings with Serbia|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Train lines from Serbia via Croatia to Slovenia were closed until further notice.\n\nAs of 6 October 2015, 125,000 had entered Croatia in the space of three weeks.<ref>{{cite news | title=If Germany Stops Receiving Refugees, Croatia Could Close Its Borders|url=http://www.total-croatia-news.com/news/1097-if-germany-stops-receiving-refugees-croatia-could-close-its-borders}}</ref> Between mid-September and mid-October 2015, about 200,000 migrants had passed through Croatia, most moving on to Hungary.<ref name=HungaryCroatia2/> On 17 October 2015, Hungary closed its border with Croatia to migrants, forcing diversion of migrants to Slovenia instead.<ref name=HungaryCroatia2/> However, Slovenia, with a population of only two million, stated that it would only be able to admit 2,500 people per day, stranding thousands of migrants in Croatia as well as Serbia and North Macedonia, while new migrants continued to add to this backlog.<ref name=CroatiaSlovenia3>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/10/17/world/europe/ap-eu-europe-migrants.html|title=Thousands of Migrants Surge into Slovenia in New Route|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 October 2015|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=CroatiaSlovenia4>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/thousands-stranded-on-new-migrant-route-through-europe/ar-AAfAX74?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout |title=Thousands stranded on new migrant route through Europe |author=Radul Radovanovic |publisher=The Associated Press, MSN |date=18 October 2015 |accessdate=18 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117031158/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/thousands-stranded-on-new-migrant-route-through-europe/ar-AAfAX74?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout |archivedate=17 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn late December 2015, Slovenia put up a razor-wire fence on the border with western Croatian regions of [[Istria]] and [[Gorski kotar]], of which the latter is a habitat of the [[Eurasian lynx|lynx]] and the [[Eurasian brown bear|brown bear]], which are both endangered and protected by law in Croatia. Local hunters have found deer killed by the fence. The [[World Wildlife Fund|WWF]] and the inhabitants of the regions from both sides of the border have protested against the decision to put up the razor-wire fence.<ref name=CroatiaSlovenia5>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/slovenias-fence-croatia-border-threatening-wildlife-wwf-203307042.html|title=Slovenia's fence on Croatia border threatening wildlife: WWF|author=Yahoo News|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=18 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=CroatiaSlovenia6>{{cite web|url=http://about.hr/news/croatia/istrians-protest-against-razor-wire-fence-croatia-slovenia-border-3925|title=Istrians protest against razor wire fence on Croatia-Slovenia border|author=Croatia|publisher=Hina|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202060746/https://about.hr/news/croatia/istrians-protest-against-razor-wire-fence-croatia-slovenia-border-3925|archivedate=2 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=CroatiaSlovenia7>{{cite web|url=http://about.hr/news/europe/protest-rally-against-razor-fence-slovenian-croatian-border-crossing-5450|title=Protest rally against razor fence at Slovenian-Croatian border crossing|author=Croatia|publisher=Hina|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202045306/https://about.hr/news/europe/protest-rally-against-razor-fence-slovenian-croatian-border-crossing-5450|archivedate=2 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2016, Croatia started implementing border restrictions on the border with Serbia, aiming to reinstate the Schengen rules.<ref name=CroatiaSlovenia8>{{cite web|url=http://www.newkerala.com/news/2016/fullnews-32348.html|title=Slovenia, Croatia, Serbia begin closure of Balkan route|author=New Kerala|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n{{flagu|Czech Republic}} \u2013 Czech Republic will receive 4,306 refugees according to quotas accepted by the [[European Commission]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MAPPED: How many refugees each European country will take under EU plans |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/607349/Migrant-crisis-map-EU-refugee-quota |accessdate=23 September 2015 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=22 September 2015}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]] [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] said the [[European Commission]] had failed in solving the crisis and expressed disagreement with proposed quotas saying: \"We reject the system of quotas. I do not consider it effective, I do not think it would help bring any solution. It makes no sense to discuss any numbers for now\". He said Europe needs to complete what the [[European Council]] has agreed in the past and not to create new plans and proposals. He supports the idea of creating hotspots in Italy or Greece.<ref>{{cite news |title=EC failed in solving migration, quotas make no sense \u2013 Czech PM |url=http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/ec-failed-in-solving-migration-quotas-make-no-sense-czech-pm/1255977 |accessdate=13 September 2015 |publisher=[[\u010cTK]] |date=8 September 2015}}</ref> Czech President [[Milo\u0161 Zeman]] has expressed his dissatisfaction with the mass inflow of migrants to Europe on several occasions. In late August 2015 in an interview for radio \"Frekvence 1\" he said: \"The reception of migrants from the Middle East and Northern Africa to the territory of Czech Republic brings with it three major risks \u2013 spread of infectious diseases, terrorism of the Islamic state and the creation of new ghettos.\" According to his opinion the majority of refugees are actually economic migrants that are not fleeing war. The President also thinks that migrants that are crossing Czech territory in order to go to Germany will stay in Czech Republic when Germany eventually stops accepting them, \"which would then make Czech Republic to defend its boundaries with the police and army\".<ref>{{cite web |title=President cites disease, terrorist sleeper cells as causes for concern |url=http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/49528-zeman-refugees-should-be-promptly-returned |website=The Prague Post |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nCzech Deputy Prime Minister [[Andrej Babi\u0161]] called for [[NATO]] intervention against human trafficking in the Mediterranean.<ref>\"[http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/finance-minister-andrej-babis-calls-on-nato-to-destroy-human-smugglers-ships Finance Minister Andrej Babi\u0161 calls on NATO to destroy human smugglers\u2019 ships]\". Radio Prague. 9 September 2015.</ref> After talks with NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] on migrant crisis issue Babi\u0161 said: \"NATO is not interested in refugees, though Turkey, a NATO member, is their entrance gate to Europe and smugglers operate on Turkish territory\".<ref name=\"CN\">\"[http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czech-minister-babis-criticises-nato-s-stance-on-refugees/1256815 Czech minister Babis criticises NATO\u00b4s stance on refugees]\". CeskeNoviny.cz. 10 September 2015.</ref> Opposition [[TOP09]]'s [[Miroslav Kalousek]] said that \"confident and wealthy countries such as the [[Czech Republic]] should not be afraid to accept 3,000 refugees\" and accused [[Milo\u0161 Zeman|President Zeman]] of giving rise to hatred to refugees; however he also shares disagreement with proposed quotas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kalousek: Sebev\u011bdom\u00e1 zem\u011b jako \u010cesko by se nem\u011bla b\u00e1t t\u0159\u00ed tis\u00edc uprchl\u00edk\u016f |language=Czech |url=http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/domaci/1582002-kalousek-sebevedoma-zeme-jako-cesko-se-nemela-bat-tri-tisic-uprchliku |accessdate=13 September 2015 |publisher=[[\u010cT24]] |date=10 September 2015}}</ref> Former [[Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Karel Schwarzenberg]] has said that accepting 80,000 refugees would be suitable.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karel Schwarzenberg: \u0158veme, jako by n\u00e1m uprchl\u00edci \u0159ezali krky |language=Czech |url=http://nazory.euro.e15.cz/rozhovory/karel-schwarzenberg-rveme-jako-by-nam-uprchlici-rezali-krky-1226853 |accessdate=15 September 2015 |publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta E15 |date=14 September 2015}}</ref> Minister of Human Rights and Equal Opportunities [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Dienstbier Jr.|Ji\u0159\u00ed Dienstbier]] said the country is able to accept 7,000 \u201415,000 refugees now and should express solidarity and help other countries facing the strongest influx of refugees without quotas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Republic can accept 7,000\u201315,000 refugees now \u2013 minister |url=http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czech-republic-can-accept-7-000-15-000-refugees-now-minister/1259195 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |publisher=[[\u010cTK]] |date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n{{flagu|Denmark}} \u2013 Denmark temporarily closed rail links with Germany in September to stop migrants from illegally entering the country, and the [[European route E45|E45 Motorway]] due to migrants on the road.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34203366 Migrant crisis: Denmark-Germany rail links suspended]\". BBC News. 9 September 2015.</ref> Denmark used the second highest amount on asylum seekers among European nations in 2015, compared to [[GDP]] (0.47 percent of GDP, after Sweden at 0.5 percent, followed by Germany and Italy at 0.2 percent, with remaining lower).<ref name=IMFCost>{{cite web | title=The Refugee Surge in Europe: Economic Challenges | website=[[IMF]] | date=16 January 2016 | url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/sdn/2016/sdn1602.pdf | accessdate=26 December 2015|author1=S. Aiyar |author2=B. Barkbu |author3=N. Batini |author4=H. Berger |author5=E. Detragiache |authorlink5= Enrica Detragiache |author6=A. Dizioli |author7=C. Ebeke |author8=H. Lin |author9=L. Kaltani |author10=S. Sosa |author11=A. Spilimbergo |author12=P. Topalova }}</ref> This is expected to rise in 2016.<ref name=IMFCost/>\nIn December 2015, the Danish Government announced that it would introduce new laws that will allow confiscation of cash above 3,000 [[Danish krone|DKK]] (c. \u20ac402) and valuables worth more than 3,000 DKK from asylum seekers to pay the cost of their stay. Items of sentimental value (such as [[wedding ring]]s, personal [[mobile phone]]s and personal [[laptop]]s) would not be taken.<ref name=\"The Independent DK 2015\">{{cite news | title=Denmark has responded to critics of its plan to strip jewellery from refugees | website=The Independent | date=22 December 2015 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europerefugee-crisis-denmark-government-defends-plan-to-strip-refugees-valuables-to-pay-for-their-stay-a6782916.html | accessdate=22 December 2015|author=Emma Henderson}}</ref> In January 2016, the limit was changed to 10,000 DKK (c. \u20ac1,340) and the law was passed.<ref name=TheLocal15>{{cite web | title=As Danes debate, Swiss already seizing refugees' cash | website=The Local | date=15 January 2016 | url=http://www.thelocal.dk/20160115/as-danes-debate-swiss-already-seizing-refugees-cash | accessdate=25 January 2016|author=Nina Larson/AFP}}</ref><ref name=TheLocal26>{{cite web | title=Denmark passes controversial bill to take migrants' valuables | website=The Local | date=26 January 2016 | url=http://www.thelocal.dk/20160126/danish-parliament-to-vote-on-controversial-migrant-bill | accessdate=26 January 2016|author=S\u00f6ren Billing/AFP}}</ref> Similar laws already exist in Switzerland (limit 1,000 Swiss francs [c. \u20ac913]),<ref name=TheLocal15/> the Netherlands (limit \u20ac5,895)<ref>{{cite web | title=Holland kan ogs\u00e5 inddrage asylans\u00f8geres v\u00e6rdigenstande | website=Jyllands Posten | date=26 January 2016 | url=http://jyllands-posten.dk/international/europa/ECE8393704/holland-kan-ogsaa-inddrage-asylansoegeres-vaerdigenstande/| accessdate=26 January 2016|author=Ritzau}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Netherlands claimed more than \u00a3500,000 from refugees in four years | website=The Guardian | date=25 January 2016 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/25/netherlands-claimed-500000-from-refugees-cost-of-living| accessdate=26 January 2016|author=Gordon Darroch}}</ref> and some [[States of Germany|federal states of Germany]] (limit varies, \u20ac750 in [[Bavaria]] and \u20ac350 in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]).<ref>{{cite web | title=Tyskland tager ogs\u00e5 flygtninges penge | website=Politiken | date=22 January 2016 | url=http://politiken.dk/udland/fokus_int/Flygtningestroem/ECE3028305/tyskland-tager-ogsaa-flygtninges-penge/| accessdate=25 January 2016|author=Erik Jensen}}</ref> The Danish law was condemned from several sides, including by the [[UNHCR]],<ref name=TheLocal26/><ref name=\"Channel 4 News 2015\">{{cite web | title=Yes, Denmark really wants to strip refugees of jewellery | website=Channel 4 News | date=18 December 2015 | url=http://www.channel4.com/news/yes-denmark-really-wants-to-strip-refugees-of-jewellery | accessdate=22 December 2015|quote=The UN refugee agency UNHCR told Channel 4 News the idea \"beggars belief.}}</ref> and caused one Danish politician, [[Jens Rohde]], to defect from the [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] party to the [[Danish Social Liberal Party|Social Liberal Party]].<ref name=\"Zawadzki Dec 2015\">{{cite web | last=Zawadzki | first=Sabina | title=Danish MEP quits party over plan to take refugee valuables | website=Reuters | date=20 December 2015 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-denmark-idUSKBN0U30EE20151220 | accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> The Danish Police said that this would be unenforceable<ref name=\"DW.COM 2015\">{{cite web | title=Danish police refuse to seize refugee jewelry and cash \u2013 News \u2013 22.12.2015 | website=DW.COM | date=22 December 2015 | url=http://www.dw.com/en/danish-policerefuse-to-seizerefugee-jewelry-and-cash/a-18934564 | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> and a review two months after the law came into effect showed that there had been no confiscations.<ref>{{cite web | title=Loven der satte Danmark p\u00e5 alverdens forsider er aldrig blevet brugt | website=nyheder.tv2.dk | date=5 April 2016 | url=http://nyheder.tv2.dk/krimi/2016-04-05-loven-der-satte-danmark-pa-alverdens-forsider-er-aldrig-blevet-brugt | accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nStarting on 6 September 2015, large groups of migrants who declined to apply for asylum in Germany started passing the Danish borders with the majority heading for Sweden.<ref name=Denm1>{{cite news|url=http://jyllands-posten.dk/politik/ECE8091454/Overblik%3A+Det+skete+da+flygtningestr%C3%B8mmen+n%C3%A5ede+Danmark/ |title=Overblik: Det skete da flygtningestr\u00f8mmen n\u00e5ede Danmark |newspaper=[[Jyllands-Posten]] |date=7 October 2015 |accessdate=19 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151014024126/http://jyllands-posten.dk/politik/ECE8091454/Overblik%3A+Det+skete+da+flygtningestr%C3%B8mmen+n%C3%A5ede+Danmark/ |archivedate=14 October 2015 }}</ref> Initially the Danish police attempted to register all migrants in accordance with EU rules, but many refused (instead wishing to seek asylum in Sweden), eventually resulting in a scuffle of about 50 people on 9 September at the [[Padborg station|Padborg rail station]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/world/europe/migrants-refugee-tensions-in-europe.html|title=Migrant Tide Bringing Out Europe's Best and Worst |author=Melissa Eddy |newspaper=The New York Times |date=9 September 2015 |accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=Denm2>{{cite news |url=http://nyhederne.tv2.dk/krimi/2015-09-09-motorvej-spaerret-i-begge-retninger-flygtninge-gaar-fra-padborg-mod-sverige |title=Motorvej sp\u00e6rret i begge retninger: Flygtninge g\u00e5r fra Padborg mod Sverige |author=Melissa Eddy |newspaper=[[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV2 News Denmark]] |date= 9 September 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September, Denmark suspended all rail and ferry links with Germany (reopened the following day). On the same day parts of the [[European route E45|E45]] motorway was closed for vehicles to avoid accidents as hundreds of migrants were walking along it in southern [[Jutland]] towards Sweden.<ref name=\"Denm2\" /> It was reopened a few hours later when the walking migrants exited the motorway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politiken.dk/udland/fokus_int/Flygtningestroem/ECE2834738/flygtninge-drejer-af-den-soenderjyske-motorvej-er-nu-genaabnet/ |title=Flygtninge drejer af: Den s\u00f8nderjyske motorvej er nu gen\u00e5bnet |author=Kristian Corfixen |newspaper=[[Politiken]] |date= 9 September 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015 }}</ref> After initial uncertainty surrounding the rules, it was decided that migrants wishing to continue to other [[Nordic countries]] and refusing to seek asylum in Denmark would be allowed to pass.<ref name=\"Denm1\" /> In the five weeks following 6 September alone, approximately 28,800 migrants passed the Danish borders. 3,500 of these applied for asylum in Denmark and the remaining continued to other Nordic countries.<ref name=\"Denm3\">{{cite news |url=http://nyhederne.tv2.dk/2015-10-12-28800-flygtninge-og-migranter-er-kommet-til-danmark-paa-fem-uger |title=28.800 flygtninge og migranter er kommet til Danmark p\u00e5 fem uger |author=Jonas Hamidavi R. Moestrup |newspaper= [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV2 News Denmark]] |date= 12 October 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter Sweden introduced ID checks on the Danish border to prevent undocumented migrants from coming to Sweden, Denmark also reintroduced border controls on the [[Denmark\u2013Germany border|Danish-German border]] in January 2016, wanting to avoid predicted accumulation of illegal migrants on their way to Sweden as one of the reasons for this decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politiko.dk/nyheder/regeringen-indfoerer-midlertidig-graensekontrol-til-tyskland|title=Regeringen indf\u00f8rer midlertidig gr\u00e6nsekontrol til Tyskland |website=politiko.dk |accessdate=22 January 2016|date=4 January 2016}}</ref> As of December 2019, the border control remains.\n\nIn October 2017 the Danish migration agency ''Udl\u00e6ndingestyrelsen'' rejected over 600 asylum applications because the applicants had lied about their national identity in order to achieve preferential treatment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/over-600-asylansoegere-faar-afslag-efter-snyd-med-deres-identitet|title=Over 600 asylans\u00f8gere f\u00e5r afslag efter snyd med deres identitet|work=DR|access-date=12 October 2017|language=da}}</ref>\n\n===France===\n{{See also|Calais Jungle}}\n{{flagu|France}} \u2013 On 23 September 2015, after the Czech Republic, Hungary, Romania and Slovakia voted against a plan to relocate asylum-seekers arriving in Greece, Italy and Hungary among other member states, French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] warned the four former [[Eastern Bloc]] countries against rejecting the EU mandatory migrant quotas: \"Those who don't share our values, those who don't even want to respect those principles, need to start asking themselves questions about their place in the European Union.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/migrant-crisis-hungarian-pm-viktor-orban-proposes-eu-border-force-patrol-greek-frontier-1520934 |title=Migrant crisis: Hungarian PM Viktor Orban proposes EU border force to patrol Greek frontier |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Migrants at Eastern Railway Station - Keleti, 2015.09.04 (1).jpg|thumb|Migrants in Budapest railway station, with most heading to Germany, 4 September 2015]]\n\n[[File:Calais2015k.jpg|thumb|Sudanese migrants in Calais, October 2015]]\nMigrants entering France illegally by train from Italy were returned to Italy by French police since border controls were introduced in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/21/world/europe/migrants-journeys-stall-in-italy-near-the-french-border.html|title=Migrants' Journeys Stall in Italy, Near the French Border|date=22 July 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/top-french-court-approves-border-controls-italy-173759866.html|title=Top French court approves border controls with Italy|date=29 June 2015|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> Due to \"poor housing\", lower social benefits and a thorough asylum application process France is not commonly considered attractive enough to seek asylum in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11880391/Refugees-shun-France-land-of-red-tape-unemployment-and-poor-housing.html|title=EU migrant crisis: Refugees shun France over red tape, unemployment and poor housing \u2013 Telegraph|date=21 September 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2016|last1=Samuel|first1=Henry}}</ref> Thus many of them seek to enter the [[United Kingdom]], resulting in camps of [[migrants around Calais]], where one of the [[Eurotunnel]] entrances is located. During the summer of 2015, at least nine people died in attempts to reach Britain, including falling from, or being hit by trains, and drowning in a canal at the Eurotunnel entrance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3980758/calais-migrant-eurotunnel-deaths/ |title=Why Thousands of Migrants Are Risking Their Lives at Calais |author=Naina Bajekal/Calais |work=Time |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=1 August 2015}}</ref> Migrants from the camps also attempt to enter trucks bound for the UK, with some truck drivers being threatened by migrants, and cargo being stolen or damaged.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jul/05/calais-lorry-drivers-need-more-protection-migrants|title=Calais drivers need more protection from migrants, says lorry group|author=Haroon Siddique|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn response, a UK financed fence was built along the A 216 highway in [[Calais]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33833536|title=Will new mile-long Calais fence stop migrants?|work=BBC News|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/refugee-crisis-hundreds-of-migrants-storm-calais-motorway-attempting-to-board-lorries-heading-to-the-a6775346.html|title=Refugee crisis: Hundreds of migrants storm Calais motorway attempting to board lorries heading to the UK|author=Lizzie Dearden|date=16 December 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> At the camp near Calais, known as the ''[[Calais jungle|Jungle]]'', riots broke out when authorities started to demolish the illegally constructed campsite on 29 January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chrisafis|first1=Angelique|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|last3=Quinn|first3=Ben|title=Calais 'Jungle' camp: clashes as authorities demolish homes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/29/french-authorities-begin-clearance-of-part-of-calais-jungle-camp|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307205334/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/29/french-authorities-begin-clearance-of-part-of-calais-jungle-camp|archivedate=7 March 2016|date=1 March 2016}}</ref> Amid the protests, which included hunger strikes, thousands of refugees living in the camp were relocated to France's \"first international-standard refugee camp\" of [[La Liniere refugee camp]] in [[Grande-Synthe]] which replaced the predecessor encampment at [[Basroch refugee camp]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nach R\u00e4umung des \"Dschungels\": Frankreich er\u00f6ffnet neues Fl\u00fcchtlingslager am \u00c4rmelkanal|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/grande-synthe-frankreich-eroeffnet-fluechtlingslager-am-aermelkanal-a-1081052.html|newspaper=Spiegel Online|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210038/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/grande-synthe-frankreich-eroeffnet-fluechtlingslager-am-aermelkanal-a-1081052.html|archivedate=7 March 2016|language=German|date=7 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=France opens new refugee camp, amid protest|url=http://www.euronews.com/2016/03/07/france-opens-new-refugee-camp-amid-protest/|website=euronews.com|accessdate=7 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307205734/http://www.euronews.com/2016/03/07/france-opens-new-refugee-camp-amid-protest/|archivedate=7 March 2016|date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n{{Main|European migrant crisis (Finland)}}\n[[File:Natsit ja ISIS on samaa paskaa.jpg|thumb|right|A pro-migration demonstration in [[Helsinki]], Finland, showing a sign saying ''Natsit & ISIS = samaa paskaa'', [[Finnish language|Finnish]] for \"Nazis & ISIS = the same shit\".]]\n{{flagu|Finland}} \u2013 Many migrants arrived over the land border from Sweden. They were stopped from using ferries by carrier's responsibility rules. On 14 September, a former prime minister [[Matti Vanhanen]] noted that the government needed to regain control on who enters the country and to divert asylum seekers to special camps. He did not think that it would be appropriate that the asylum seekers could continue to freely move around.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uusisuomi.fi/kotimaa/113969-matti-vanhanen-suomi-valmistautuu-rajatarkastuksiin-syy-loytyy-pohjois-suomesta|title=Matti Vanhanen: Suomi valmistautuu rajatarkastuksiin \u2013 syy l\u00f6ytyy Pohjois-Suomesta |work=Uusi Suomi|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Later on the same day, the Minister of the Interior [[Petteri Orpo]], who is also a member of the National Coalition Party, noted that tightened border controls would be imposed on the northern border stations by the end of the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-1442202525958.html|title=Orpo: Pohjois-Suomeen tehostettu rajavalvonta|author=STT-IS|work=Ilta-Sanomat|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> On 14 November 2015 Finnish prime minister [[Juha Sipil\u00e4]] noted that border controls need to be tightened and he expressed his concern that Schengen Agreement and freedom of movement was not working. He stressed, that border controls will be restored if Schengen agreement is not fixed. Furthermore, he noted, that Finnish National Bureau of Investigation will improve its cyber surveillance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-1447477033932.html|title=Sipil\u00e4: Rajavalvontaa tiivistet\u00e4\u00e4n \u2013 vapaa liikkuvuus ei toimi|author=IS|work=Ilta-Sanomat}}</ref> On the same day Finnish President [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] (elected from the National Coalition Party) was referred to have noted that national solutions needed to be formed if the Schengen agreement could not be repaired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uusisuomi.fi/kotimaa/139133-presidentti-niinisto-hurjan-ennustuksensa-toteutumisesta-valitettavasti-silla-tiella|title=Presidentti Niinist\u00f6 hurjan ennustuksensa toteutumisesta: \"Valitettavasti sill\u00e4 tiell\u00e4 ollaan\" |work=Uusi Suomi}}</ref>\nOn 13 September 2015, it was reported that the local authorities had estimated the flow of 300 asylum seekers per day entering via the northern land [[Finnish\u2013Swedish border|border from Sweden]] into [[Tornio]], which is the main route of migration flow into [[Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2015091320344649_uu.shtml|title=Turvapaikanhakijoiden m\u00e4\u00e4r\u00e4 r\u00e4j\u00e4hti Torniossa: \"Satoja tullut t\u00e4n\u00e4\u00e4n\" | author=Sami Koski | work=Iltalehti | date=2015-09-13 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> The total number of asylum seekers for the year was reported to be over 2.6 times the total amount for the whole of the previous year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2015091420349291_uu.shtml | title=Viime viikolla enn\u00e4tyksellinen m\u00e4\u00e4r\u00e4 turvapaikanhakijoita | author=Olli Waris | work=Iltalehti | date=2015-09-14 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> During October 2015, 7,058 new asylum seekers arrived in Finland. In mid-October the number of asylum seekers entering Finland during 2015 reached 27,000, which is, in relation to the country's size, the fourth-largest in Europe.<ref name=yle>{{cite news | title=Interior Ministry: Finland set to reject two thirds of asylum seekers | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/interior_ministry_finland_set_to_reject_two_thirds_of_asylum_seekers/8446795 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-11-11 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> In late November, the number passed 30,000, nearly ten-fold increase compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite news | title=Eurajoki resorting to containers to house asylum seekers | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/eurajoki_resorting_to_shipping_containers_to_house_asylum_seekers/8455009 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-11-13  | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref><ref name=yle3>{{cite news | title=Reception centres use containers to house new arrivals | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/reception_centres_use_containers_to_house_new_arrivals/8486826 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-11-28 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nMore than 60 percent of asylum seekers who arrived during 2015 came from [[Iraq]].<ref name=yle2>{{ cite news | title=Disappointed Iraqis cancel asylum applications | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/disappointed_iraqis_cancel_asylum_applications/8479598 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-11-24 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> In late October, The Finnish Immigration Service (Migri) changed its guidelines about areas in Iraq which are recognized as safe by the Finnish authorities,<ref name=yle2 /> putting Iraqi asylum seekers under closer scrutiny.<ref>{{cite news | title=Finland adopts one-stop approach to slash asylum processing queues | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/finland_adopts_one-stop_approach_to_slash_asylum_processing_queues/8420646 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-11-30 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> The Interior Minister [[Petteri Orpo]] estimated that two in three of recent asylum seekers come to Finland in hopes of higher standard of living. In November, the Permanent Secretary of the Interior Ministry stated that approximately 60 to 65 percent of the recent applications for asylum will be denied.<ref name=yle />\n\nIn September, the processing time of an asylum application was estimated to be extended from normal six months up to two years.<ref>{{cite news | title=Turvapaikkahakemusten k\u00e4sittelyajat venyv\u00e4t \u2013 \"T\u00e4\u00e4ll\u00e4 on tuhansia turvapaikanhakijoita monta vuotta\" | url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/turvapaikkahakemusten_kasittelyajat_venyvat__taalla_on_tuhansia_turvapaikanhakijoita_monta_vuotta/8295512 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-09-10 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref> In late November, the reception centers were reported to be running out of space, forcing the authorities resorting to refurbished [[Intermodal container|shipping containers]] and tents to house new asylum seekers.<ref name=yle3 /> Interior Minister Petteri Orpo has announced that special repatriation centers would be established. These centers would be inhabited by the asylum seekers whose applications were declined. While he stressed that these camps would not be prisons, he described the inhabitants would be under strict surveillance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interior Minister: Finland to set up asylum seeker repatriation centres | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/interior_minister_finland_to_set_up_asylum_seeker_repatriation_centres/8502217 | work=[[YLE]] | date=2015-12-03 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, [[Yle]], Finland's national public-broadcasting company, reported that a [[Russia]]n border guard had admitted that the [[Federal Security Service]] was enabling migrants to enter Finland.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/russian_border_guard_to_stt_russian_security_service_behind_northeast_asylum_traffic/8620174 | title=Russian border guard to STT: Russian security service behind northeast asylum traffic | work=[[YLE]] | date=2016-01-24 | accessdate=2017-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, hundreds Muslim asylum seekers from [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]] converted to Christianity after having had their first asylum application rejected by the Finnish Immigration Service (Migri), in order to re-apply for asylum on the grounds of religious persecution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://svenska.yle.fi/artikel/2017/10/04/stort-finlandskt-fenomen-hundratals-muslimer-blir-kristna|title=Stort finl\u00e4ndskt fenomen \u2013 hundratals muslimer blir kristna|date=4 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421104613/https://svenska.yle.fi/artikel/2017/10/04/stort-finlandskt-fenomen-hundratals-muslimer-blir-kristna|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\n{{flagu|Germany}} \u2013 Junior coalition partner, Vice Chancellor [[Sigmar Gabriel]] said that Germany could take in 500,000 refugees annually for the next several years.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34185353 Migrant crisis: Germany 'can take 500,000 asylum seekers a year']\". BBC News. 8 September 2015.</ref> German opposition to the government's admission of the new wave of migrants has been an increasingly tense political debate, coupled with a rise in anti-immigration protests.<ref name=Hill>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Jenny |title=Immigration fuels rising tension in Germany |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33700624 |accessdate=18 August 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=30 July 2013}}</ref> [[Pegida]], an anti-immigration movement flourished briefly in late 2014, followed by a new wave of anti-immigration protests in the late summer of 2015.<ref name=Fenton>{{cite news |last1=Fenton |first1=Siobhan |title=Pegida |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/german-farright-extremists-clash-with-police-in-protest-outside-dresden-refugee-camp-10415880.html |accessdate=18 August 2015 |work=The Independent |date=25 July 2015 |location=London}}</ref> Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] insisted that Germany has the economic strength to cope with the influx of migrants and reiterated that there is no legal maximum limit on the number of migrants Germany can take.<ref>{{cite web |title=Germany: 'No Limit' To Refugees We'll Take In |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1547326/germany-no-limit-to-refugees-well-take-in |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=6 September 2015 |date=5 September 2015}}</ref> In September 2015, enthusiastic crowds across the country welcomed arriving refugees and migrants.<ref>{{cite web |title=Germans welcome thousands of newly arrived refugees |url=http://www.dw.com/en/germans-welcome-thousands-of-newly-arrived-refugees/a-18696722 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=6 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Horst Seehofer]], leader of the [[Christian Social Union in Bavaria]] (the sister party of Merkel's [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]]) and then [[Bavaria]]n Minister President, attacked Merkel's policies in sharp language,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=Merkel splits conservative bloc with green light to refugees |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/09/06/uk-europe-migrants-germany-criticism-idUKKCN0R60T920150906 |agency=Reuters |date=6 September 2015}}</ref> threatened to sue the government in the high court, and hinted that the CSU might topple Merkel.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} Many MPs of Merkel's CDU party also voiced dissatisfaction with Merkel. Seehofer criticised Merkel's decision to allow in migrants, saying that \"we're now in a state of mind without rules, without system and without order because of a German decision.\"<ref>\"[http://www.politico.eu/article/viktor-orban-bavaria-hardline-hero-seehofer-migration-borders/ Viktor Orb\u00e1n, Bavaria\u2019s hardline hero]\". ''[[Politico]]''. 23 September 2015.</ref> Seehofer estimated as many as 30 percent of asylum seekers arriving in Germany claiming to be from Syria are in fact from other countries,<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11891219/Refugee-crisis-Many-migrants-falsely-claim-to-be-Syrians-Germany-says-as-EU-tries-to-ease-tensions.html Refugee crisis: Many migrants falsely claim to be Syrians, Germany says as EU tries to ease tensions]\". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. 25 September 2015.</ref> and suggested to reduce EU funding for member countries that reject mandatory refugee quotas.<ref>\"[http://www.dw.com/en/berlin-calls-for-sanctions-on-eu-states-that-reject-refugee-quotas/a-18714957 Berlin calls for sanctions on EU states that reject refugee quotas]\". [[Deutsche Welle]]. 15 September 2015.</ref> The Bavarian Interior Minister [[Joachim Herrmann (CSU)|Joachim Herrmann]] (CSU) accused the Berlin government of pushing its policy forward without consulting the federal states, which would have had to cope with the consequences.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nMeanwhile, [[Yasmin Fahimi]], secretary-general of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]], the junior partner of the ruling coalition, praised Merkel's policy allowing migrants in Hungary to enter Germany as \"a strong signal of humanity to show that Europe's values are valid also in difficult times\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], Germany's most populous state, was hiring more than 3,600 new teachers to manage the influx of an estimated 40,000 new refugee children in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/24/world/europe/where-therefugees-pour-into-germany-a-24-hour-window.html|title=Where the Refugees Pour into Germany, a 24-Hour Window|author=Alison Smale|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 September 2015|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, there were talks inside the governing coalition to stop family unification for migrants for two years, and to establish \"Transit Zones\" on the border and \u2013 for migrants with low chances to get asylum approved \u2013 to be housed there until their application is approved. The issues are in conflict between the CSU who favours those new measures and threaten to leave the coalition without them, and the SPD who opposes them. Merkel has agreed to the measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germany-coalition-split-on-transit-zones/av-18824248|title=Germany: Coalition split on transit zones|work=DW.COM|access-date=4 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104013756/http://www.dw.com/en/germany-coalition-split-on-transit-zones/av-18824248|archive-date=4 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[November 2015 Paris attacks]] prompted reevaluation of German officials' stance on the EU's policy toward migrants.<ref name=ParisAttacksMigrants>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/11/14/world/europe/ap-eu-germany-migrants-rising-tensions.html|title=Paris Attacks Provoke Fresh Migrant Fears in Europe|author=Eldar Emric, Demetri Nellas, and the Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> There appeared to be a consensus among officials, with the notable exception of Angela Merkel herself, that a higher level of scrutiny was needed in vetting migrants with respect to their mission in Germany.<ref name=ParisAttacksMigrants/> However, while not officially limiting the influx numerically, Merkel has tightened asylum policy in Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/29/world/europe/merkel-whilerefusing-to-halt-migrant-influx-works-to-limit-it.html?ref=Europe|title=Merkel, While Refusing to Halt Migrant Influx, Works to Limit It|author=Alison Smale|newspaper=The New York Times|date=28 November 2015|accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Asylum in Germany|Angela Merkel#Domestic policy}}\n[[File:Drehscheibe K\u00f6ln-Bonn Airport - Ankunft Fl\u00fcchtlinge 5. Oktober 2015-0308.jpg|thumb|Migrants in Germany, October 2015]]\n\n[[Germany]]'s asylum practice is generally to be based on article 16a of its [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany|Basic Law]], as well as international regulations like the [[Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees]]<ref>Deutscher Bundestag: ''Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany'', print version in English, November 2012 ([https://www.bundestag.de/blob/284870/ce0d03414872b427e57fccb703634dcd/basic_law-data.pdf PDF] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075359/https://www.bundestag.de/blob/284870/ce0d03414872b427e57fccb703634dcd/basic_law-data.pdf |date=4 March 2016 }})</ref> Germany has been the most sought-after final destination in the EU migrant and refugee crisis.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/> Between January and December 2015, 1,091,894 arrivals of asylum seekers were registered in Germany's \"EASY\" system for the first distribution of asylum seekers among Germany's federal states; however, asylum applications in 2015 were only 476,649, because many asylum seekers had not formally applied for asylum yet or did not stop in Germany and moved on to other EU states.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015: Mehr Asylantr\u00e4ge in Deutschland als jemals zuvor|url=http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Pressemitteilungen/DE/2016/01/asylantraege-dezember-2015.html|publisher=BMI|date=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n:'''Further developments'''\nGermany has a quota system to distribute asylum seekers among [[States of Germany|all German states]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/07/world/german-quota-system-highlights-possible-path-and-pitfalls-for-handling-crisis.html|title=German Quota System Highlights Possible Path and Pitfalls for Handling Crisis |author1=Katrin Bennhold |author2=Melissa Eddy |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=6 September 2015 |date=6 September 2015}}</ref> In September 2015 however the federal states, responsible for accommodation, criticised the Government in [[Berlin]] for not providing enough help to them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschlandenminister-warnen-vor-noch-mehr-fluechtlingen-a-1052575.html |title=L\u00e4nderinnenminister: \"Sie \u00f6ffnen die Grenzen und lassen uns im Stich\" |author=Melanie Amann, Matthias Gebauer und Horand Knaup |newspaper=Der Spiegel |accessdate=11 September 2015 |date=11 September 2015 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Interior Minister announced on 13 September 2015 the introduction of temporary controls on the southern border with Austria and explained the measure with reference to ''security concerns''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/14/world/europe/germany-emergency-measures-european-migrant-crisis.html|title=Germany Announces Emergency Border Controls Amid Migrant Crisis|author1=Melissa Eddy |author2=Alison Smale |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=13 September 2015 |date=13 September 2015}}</ref>\nThe restrictions incorporated a temporary suspension of rail travel from Austria and allowed spot checks on automobiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2015/09/13/germany-introduces-temporary-controls-along-austrian-border/|title=Germany introduces 'temporary' controls along Austrian border|publisher=euronews|date=13 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/14/world/europe/germany-emergency-measures-european-migrant-crisis.html|title=Germany Orders Curbs at Border in Migrant Crisis|author1=Melissa Eddy |author2=Rick Lyman |author3=Alison Smale |newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> In September 2019, following the rise in the number of migrants reaching Italy after having been rescued from drowning by activists, Interior Minister Horst Seehofer said that Germany would accept one in four migrants previously rescued and brought to Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/verteilung-von-fluechtlingen-in-europa-bundesregierung-pocht-auf-langfristige-solidarische-loesung/25021288.html|title=Bundesregierung pocht auf langfristige \"solidarische\" L\u00f6sung|accessdate=16 September 2019|website=Tagesspiegel}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 October, the German [[Tabloid journalism|tabloid]] [[Bild]] claimed to possess a secret document stating that the number of asylum seekers would increase to 1.5 million by the end of 2015. This report was immediately disclaimed by the German ministry of the interior which restated its own estimate of 800,000 applicants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bild.de/politik/inland/fluechtlingskrise/fluechtlingskrise-deutsche-behoerden-warnen-vor-zusammenbruch-der-versorgung-42892328.bild.html|title=Beh\u00f6rden warnen in der Fl\u00fcchtlingskrise: Zusammenbruch der Versorgung droht|author=FRANZ SOLMS-LAUBACH und PETER TIEDE|work=Bild|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> Germany has followed a policy of treating migrants under 18 years of age as \"children first and refugees second,\" giving them \u2212 according to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] \u2212 mostly the same rights as German children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/29/world/europe/distinguishing-minors-from-adults-in-a-tide-of-young-migrants.html?ribbon-ad-idx=29&rref=world&module=Ribbon&version=origin&region=Header&action=click&contentCollection=World&pgtype=article|title=Distinguishing Minors From Adults in a Tide of Young Migrants|author=Katrin Bennhold|newspaper=The New York Times|date=28 October 2015|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> In late October 2015, the small village of [[Sumte]], population 102, was told by [[Lower Saxony, Germany|Lower Saxony]] officials that it would receive 750 asylum-seekers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/world/europe/german-village-of-102-braces-for-750-asylum-seekers.html|title=German Village of 102 Braces for 750 Asylum Seekers|author=Andrew Higgins|newspaper=The New York Times|date=31 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n\nIn February 2016, the German government admitted that it had lost track of around 13 percent of the 1.1 million people registered as asylum seekers on arrival in 2015, because they never arrived at the refugee accommodation they were assigned. The German government said that probably many of the missing asylum seekers simply went to other European countries, while others continued to live illegally in Germany.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/12174803/Germany-admits-130000-asylum-seekers-lost-raising-fears-over-crime-and-terrorism.html Germany admits 130,000 asylum seekers 'lost' raising fears over crime and terrorism] J. Huggler, The Daily Telegraph, 26 February 2016</ref> Merkel's immigration policies are being criticised in the Christian Social Union, e.g. by the CSU-chairman [[Horst Seehofer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/fluechtlinge-horst-seehofer-unterstellt-angela-merkel-herrschaft-des-unrechts-a-1076528.html|title=Streit \u00fcber Fl\u00fcchtlingspolitik: Seehofer unterstellt Merkel \"Herrschaft des Unrechts\" \u2013 SPIEGEL ONLINE \u2013 Politik|first=SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg|last=Germany|newspaper=Spiegel Online|date=9 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, [[Angela Merkel]] travelled to African countries Mali and Niger. The diplomatic visit took place in order to discuss how their governments could improve conditions which cause people to flee those countries and how illegal migration through and from these countries could be reduced.<ref name=\"spiegel_10.10.2016\">{{cite magazine|title=Hunderte Millionen gegen die Flucht|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/angela-merkel-in-niger-hunderte-millionen-gegen-die-flucht-a-1116005.html|accessdate=13 October 2016|magazine=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 Germany security officials cracked down on the militant [[salafist]] organisation ''Die Wahre Religion'' as these preachers had targeted newly arrived migrants with their violent form of Islam.<ref name=\"nyt19november2016\">{{cite news|title=Germany Cracks Down on Salafists to Shield Refugees|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/world/europe/germany-salafists-refugees.html|accessdate=24 February 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=19 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe migrant crisis has spurred right-wing electoral preferences across Germany with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) gaining 12% of the vote in the [[2017 German federal election]]. These developments have prompted debates over the reasons for increased right-wing populism in Germany. Literature argues that the increased right-wing preferences are a result of the European migrant crisis which has brought thousands of people, predominantly from Muslim countries to Germany, and spurred a perception among a share of Germans that refugees constitute an ethnic and cultural threat to Germany.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lucassen|first1=Geertje|last2=Lubbers|first2=Marcel|title=Who Fears What? Explaining Far-Right-Wing Preference in Europe by Distinguishing Perceived Cultural and Economic Threats|journal=Comparative Political Studies|date=2012|volume=45|issue=5}}</ref>\n\n===Greece===\n[[File:Refugees on a boat crossing the Mediterranean sea, heading from Turkish coast to the northeastern Greek island of Lesbos, 29 January 2016.jpg|thumb|Migrants crossing the [[Aegean Sea]] from Turkey to the Greek island of [[Lesbos]], January 2016]]\n[[File:20151213 Syrians refugees from Turkey plastic boat airport area of Lesvos Greece.ogv|thumb|upright=1.3636364|A group of Syrian refugees arrive by boat from Turkey to airport area of Mytilini, Lesvos island, Greece, 13 December 2015]]\n[[File:Arbeitsbesuch Mazedonien (20270358044).jpg|thumb|Migrants at the Greece\u2013North Macedonia border near [[Gevgelija]], 24 August 2015]]\n\nMigrants arrive from the Middle East making the {{convert|4|mi|km|0|order=flip|adj=on}} water crossing to the [[Greek islands]] of [[Chios]], [[Kos]], [[Lesbos]], [[Leros]], [[Kastellorizo]], [[Agathonisi]], [[Farmakonisi]], [[Rhodes]], [[Samos]], [[Symi]] and other islands which are close to Turkey and are thus a quick and easy access border into Europe.<ref name=Yeginsu>{{cite news |last1=Yeginsu |first1=Ceylan |title=Amid Perilous Mediterranean Crossings, Migrants Find a Relatively Easy Path to Greece |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/17/world/europe/turkey-greece-mediterranean-kos-bodrum-migrants-refugees.html|accessdate=16 August 2015 |work=The New York Times |date=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=Neely>{{cite news |last1=Neely |first1=Bill |title=Migrants Crisis: Refugees Attempt to Reach Greek Island of Lesbos |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/europes-border-crisis/migrants-crisis-refugees-attempt-reach-greek-island-lesbos-n409011 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |publisher=NBC News |date=13 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=Daley>{{cite news |last1=Daley |first1=Suzanne |title=On Island of Lesbos, a Microcosm of Greece's Other Crisis: Migrants |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/05/world/europe/lesbos-greece-migrant-refugee-crisis.html |accessdate=14 August 2015 |work=The New York Times |date=4 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Refugees and migrants outnumber Kastelorizo's residents|url=http://en.protothema.gr/refugees-and-migrants-outnumber-kastelorizos-residents/|accessdate=24 February 2016|work=Protothema|date=20 February 2016}}</ref> Some arrive via the [[Evros (regional unit)|Evros]] border crossing from Turkey. \nAs of June 2015, 124,000 migrants had arrived into Greece, a 750 percent increase from 2014, mainly refugees stemming from the wars in Syria, Iraq, and Afghanistan. Greece appealed to the European Union for assistance, whilst the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights|UNCHR]] European Director Vincent Cochetel said facilities for migrants on the Greek islands were \"totally inadequate\" and the islands in \"total chaos\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-33818193 |title=Migrant 'chaos' on Greek islands \u2013 UN refugee agency |work=BBC News |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=7 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrontex's Operation Poseidon, aimed at patrolling the [[Aegean Sea]], is badly underfunded and undermanned, with only 11 coastal patrol vessels, one ship, two helicopters, two aircraft and a budget of \u20ac18 million.<ref name=PopFrontexGreece>{{cite news |last1=Pop |first1=Valentina |title=Greek Government Holds Emergency Meeting Over Soaring Migrant Arrivals |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/greek-government-holds-emergency-meeting-over-soaring-migrant-arrivals-1438959148 |accessdate=19 August 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=7 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHuman traffickers charge illegal immigrants $1,000 to $1,500 for the 25-minute boat ride from [[Bodrum]], Turkey to Kos.<ref name=Yeginsu /> In August 2015, \"hundreds\" of boats made the crossing carrying illegal immigrants every night.<ref name=Yeginsu /> The migrants travel onward to [[Thessaloniki]] in the mainland of Greece and estimate that it will cost them \u20ac3,000 to \u20ac4,000 to reach Germany, and \u20ac10,000 or \u20ac12,000 to reach Britain.<ref name=Yeginsu /> Desperate migrants have fought brawls over places in boats leaving Bodrum for Kos.<ref name=KilledbyFumes>{{cite news |title=40 migrants 'killed by fumes' in hold of boat off Libya |url=http://www.independent.ie/world-news/africa/40-migrants-killed-by-fumes-in-hold-of-boat-off-libya-31453815.html |accessdate=17 August 2015 |work=Irish Independent |date=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAirlines charge passengers usually less than $400 for oneway economy class tickets from Turkey to Germany or Britain,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turkishairlines.com/|title=Turkish Airlines \u00ae \u2013 Flights to 110+ countries from \u0130stanbul|website=turkishairlines.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishairways.com/travel/home/public/en_us|title=Book Flights, Holidays & Check In Online \u2013 British Airways|website=britishairways.com}}</ref> but a rule in the [[Schengen Agreement]] requires airlines to check that all passengers have a visa or are exempt from visa.<ref>[http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:42000A0922(02)&from=EN The Schengen acquis] See Article 26</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the photos of dead 3-year-old [[Alan Kurdi]], who drowned when he and his family were in a small inflatable boat which capsized shortly after leaving Bodrum trying to reach the Greek island of Kos, made headlines around the world. Konstantinos Vardakis, the top EU diplomat in [[Baghdad]], told ''The New York Times'' that at least 250 Iraqis per day had been landing on Greek islands between mid-August and early September 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/09/world/middleeast/iraq-migrants-refugees-europe.html |title=A New Wave of Migrants Flees Iraq, Yearning for Europe |author=Tim Arango |newspaper=The New York Times |date=7 September 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January 2016, the European Commission accused Greece of neglecting its obligations under the Schengen agreement to carry out external border controls, saying that a visit by EU inspectors in November 2015 found that Greece was failing to identify and register arrivals properly, to fingerprint everyone and to check travel documents for authenticity and against security databases.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: EU threatens Greece over border controls|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35416741|work=BBC News|date=27 January 2016}}</ref> On 12 February, the EU gave Greece a three months deadline to fix its border controls, or other member states could be authorized to extend border controls for up to two years instead of the normal six months.<ref>{{cite news|title=EU issues deadline for Greece to remedy migration 'deficiencies'|url=http://www.dw.com/en/eu-issues-deadline-for-greece-to-remedy-migration-deficiencies/a-19044686|work=Deutsche Welle|date=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February, NATO announced that it was going to deploy ships in the Aegean Sea to deter people smugglers taking migrants from Turkey to Greece, the first 3 ships being the [[Royal Canadian Navy]]'s {{HMCS|Fredericton|FFH 337}}, [[Turkish Naval Forces]]'s {{TCG|Barbaros|F-244}} and [[German Navy]]'s [[Berlin-class replenishment ship|''Bonn'' (A1413)]] from NATO's [[Standing NATO Maritime Group 2|SNMG2]]. NATO chief [[Jens Stoltenberg]] said the mission would not be about \"stopping or pushing back refugee boats\", but about intelligence gathering and sharing information with Turkey and Greece, both NATO allies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrant crisis: Nato deploys Aegean people-smuggling patrols|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35549478|work=BBC News|date=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2016, the Greek government asked the EU for \u20ac480 million in emergency funds to shelter 100,000 refugees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Europe Migrant crisis: Greece seeks emergency funds from EU to shelter refugees |url=http://www.balkanews.org/index.php/2016/03/01/europe-migrant-crisis-greece-seeks-emergency-funds-from-eu-to-shelter-refugees/ |work=First Post |date=1 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307140022/http://www.balkanews.org/index.php/2016/03/01/europe-migrant-crisis-greece-seeks-emergency-funds-from-eu-to-shelter-refugees/ |archivedate=7 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nNorth Macedonia closed its border with Greece on 9 March 2016 where 12,000 to 13,000 migrants were stuck at [[Idomeni]] on the Greek side, while the total number of migrants throughout Greece are estimated to be more than 50,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=More than 50,000 migrants and refugees stranded in Greece|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/207172/article/ekathimerini/news/more-than-50000-migrants-and-refugees-stranded-in-greece|accessdate=28 March 2016|publisher=\u0397 \u039a\u0391\u0398\u0397\u039c\u0395\u03a1\u0399\u039d\u0397|date=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] Greek authorities on a number of [[Aegean islands]] have called for emergency measures to curtail a growing flow of refugees from Turkey, the number of migrants and refugees willing to make the journey across the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] has increased noticeably. At Athens officials voiced worries that Turkish monitors overseeing the deal in Greece had been abruptly pulled out after the failed coup with little sign of them being replaced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aegean islands alarm as refugee numbers rise after Turkey coup attempt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/30/refugee-numbers-rise-greece-aegean-turkey-coup-attempt|work=The Guardian|language=en}}</ref> The [[Association of Greek Tourism Enterprises]] (SETE) warned about the prospect of another flare-up in the refugee/migrant crisis due to the Turkish political instability.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sector group: Coup attempt in Turkey to negatively affect Greek tourism|url=http://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1133579/sector-group-coup-attempt-in-turkey-to-negatively-affect-greek-tourism|publisher=naftemporiki|language=en|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Greek volunteers of the \"[[Hellenic Rescue Team]]\" and human rights activist Efi Latsoudi were awarded the [[Nansen Refugee Award]] by the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] (UNHCR) \"for their tireless volunteer work\" to aid refugees arriving in Greece during the 2015 refugee crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/news/press/2016/9/57cdec884/greek-volunteers-share-unhcr-nansen-refugee-award.html|title=Greek Volunteers share UNHCR Nansen Refugee Award|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|last=Refugees}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Hellenic Rescue Team received the award \"Mother Teresa\" by the Harmony Foundation. The Greek team was rewarded for their \"heroic actions\" and their effort to save human lives while risking their own during the migrant and refugee crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/mother-teresa-award-goes-to-the-hellenic-rescue-team |title=\"Mother Teresa\" award goes to the Hellenic Rescue Team|website=balkaneu.com|date=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\n{{flagu|Hungary}} \u2013 Hungary has finished construction of the first phase of a [[Hungary\u2013Serbia border fence|fence]] on its southern border with Serbia in late August 2015, according to the Hungarian Ministry of Defence. The fence consists of three strands of NATO razor wire, and is 175 kilometers long. The next phase involves construction of a wire fence which will be approximately 4 meters high. In August, describing Hungary as, \"under siege from human traffickers\", Minister of the Prime Minister's Office [[J\u00e1nos L\u00e1z\u00e1r]] announced that the government would \"defend this stretch of our borders with force\", deploying 9,000 police to keep undocumented migrants out.<ref name=BorderHunters>{{cite news |last1=Feher |first1=Margit |title=Hungary Deploys 'Border Hunters' to Keep Illegal Immigrants Out |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hungary-unleashes-border-hunters-to-keep-illegal-immigrants-out-1439916449 |accessdate=18 August 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHungary's Prime Minister [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] wrote in the ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'': \"Europe's response is madness. We must acknowledge that the European Union's misguided immigration policy is responsible for this situation\".<ref>{{cite news| title=Migration crisis: Hungary PM says Europe in grip of madness |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/03/migration-crisis-hungary-pm-victor-orban-europeresponse-madness |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 September 2015}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n also demanded an official EU list of \"safe countries\" to which migrants can be returned.<ref>\"[https://news.yahoo.com/hungary-pm-rejects-merkels-moral-imperialism-refugee-crisis-130722708.html Hungary PM rejects Merkel's 'moral imperialism' in refugee crisis]\". Yahoo News. 23 September 2015.</ref> He said that \"the moral, human thing is to make clear: 'Please don't come. Why do you have to go from Turkey to Europe? Turkey is a safe country. Stay there. It's risky to come'.\"<ref>\"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/hungarys-leader-to-migrants-please-dont-come/2015/09/03/d5244c6d-53d8-4e82-b9d7-35ec41ca2944_story.html \u2018People in Europe are full of fear\u2019 over refugee influx]\". ''The Washington Post''. 3 September 2015.</ref> Hungary has adopted a list of countries deemed safe for transiting purposes. If an asylum seeker has passed through those countries, it is assumed that he could have found asylum there, and therefore he is not eligible for asylum in Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hungary adopts list of safe countries of origin and safe third countries|publisher=asylumineurope.org|url=http://www.asylumineurope.org/news/23-07-2015/hungary-adopts-list-safe-countries-origin-and-safe-third-countries}}</ref> Speaking at [[United Nations General Assembly]], Prime Minister Viktor Orb\u00e1n called for \"global quota\" system to distribute refugees to all countries.<ref>\"[http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/hungary-pm-tells-us-australia-to-take-some-of-europes-migrants-1225399 Hungary PM Tells US, Australia to Take Some of Europe's Migrants]\". [[NDTV]]. 2 October 2015.</ref> [[File:P31 L.\u00c9. Eithne Operations 28 June 2015.jpg|thumb|Rescued male migrants are brought to southern Italian ports, 28 June 2015]]\n\nMigrants taking the Western Balkan route cross into the [[Schengen Area]] first in Greece. In June 2015, Hungary said it was contemplating countermeasures against the influx of illegal immigrants from Serbia, a non-EU and non-Schengen state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_HUNGARY_MIGRATION |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621171147/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_HUNGARY_MIGRATION |archivedate=21 June 2015 |title=Hungary seeks to tighten south border, hold illegal migrants |work=Associated Press |author=Pablo Gorondi |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2015, the Hungarian government announced the construction of a {{convert|4|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}}, {{convert|175|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} fence along its southern border with Serbia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/17/us-hungary-immigration-idUSKBN0OX17I20150617 |title=Hungary to fence off border with Serbia to stop migrants |agency=Reuters |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_HUNGARY_BORDER_FENCE |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621171828/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_HUNGARY_BORDER_FENCE |archivedate=21 June 2015 |title=Hungary's leader says Hungary will protect Europe's borders |work=Associated Press |author=Pablo Gorondi |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> The [[European Commission]] warned EU members against steps that contravene EU obligations and urged members like Hungary to find other ways to cope with an inflow of illegal migrants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rferl.mobi/a/european-commission-hungary-serbia-wall-fence-illegal-migrants/27079829.html |title=EU Warns Against New 'Walls' As Hungary Plans Fence on Serbia Border |publisher=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> The first phase of the construction was finished at the end of August and Prime Minister [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] announced that it would be fully completed by the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mno.hu/hatarontul/orban-nyar-vegere-megepul-a-kerites-1297022 |title=Orb\u00e1n: Ny\u00e1r v\u00e9g\u00e9re meg\u00e9p\u00fcl a ker\u00edt\u00e9s |publisher=mno.hu |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2015, Hungary's prime minister, Viktor Orb\u00e1n, defended the country's management of the migrant situation internally, notwithstanding chaos at Budapest's [[Budapest Keleti railway station|main international rail station]], while criticising Germany and Europe overall for not dissuading migrants from entering Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/04/world/europe/hungary-train-station-migrant-crisis.html|title=Hungary Defends Handling of Migrants Amid Chaos at Train Station |author1=Anemona Hartocollis |author2=Dan Bilefsky |author3=James Kanter |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=3 September 2015 |date=3 September 2015}}</ref> On the same day, Hungarian police let migrants board a train in Budapest heading west, then stopped it in [[Bicske]] and tried to transport migrants to a registration camp there. The migrants refused to cooperate and remained on the train, which did not travel further west.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/migrants-lay-train-tracks-hungary-seeking-passage-west-114937335.html |title=Migrants cling to Hungarian train west, lawmakers debate sealing border |agency=Reuters |accessdate=3 September 2015 |date=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Syrian refugees strike in front of Budapest Keleti railway station. Refugee crisis. Budapest, Hungary, Central Europe, 3 September 2015.jpg|thumb|Migrants in a [[hunger strike]] in front of the [[Budapest Keleti railway station]], 3 September 2015]]\nOn 4 September 2015, about a thousand of the migrants at Railway Station East (Keleti P\u00e1lyaudvar) set off by foot toward Austria and Germany.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/hungary-train-migrants-stand-firm-face-off-police-104257639.html |title=Over 1,000 migrants leave Budapest train station on foot for Austria |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/05/world/europe/migrant-crisis-hungary.html|title=Blocked by Rail, Migrants Set Out for Germany on Foot |author=Dan Bilefsky |newspaper=The New York Times |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref> On the same night, the Hungarian government decided to send buses to transport illegal migrants to [[Hegyeshalom]], on the border with Austria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34159780 |title=Migrant crisis: Hungary to bus migrants to Austria border |work=BBC News |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015, it was reported that the Hungarian police were blocking the route from Serbia, and that the regular entry point was heavily manned with officers, soldiers and helicopters hovering above,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/refugee-crisis-live-updates/a-18712845|title=+++ Refugee crisis \u2013 live updates +++|work=DW.COM|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> sealing this border with a razor wire<ref name=Wire1>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2015/09/15/hungary-seals-border-with-razor-wire/|title=Hungary seals border with razor wire|publisher=euronews|date=15 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=Wire2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/world/europe/hungary-detains-migrants-in-border-crackdown.html|title=Hungary Detains Migrants in Border Crackdown|author1=Helene Bienvenu |author2=Dan Bilefsky |newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> and detaining migrants crossing the border illegally with the threat of arrest and criminal charges.<ref name=Wire2 /> On 15 September 2015, Hungary sealed its border with Serbia. Several hundred migrants broke the fence between Hungary and Serbia twice on Wednesday, 16 September, and threw chunks of concrete and water bottles over the fence. Hungarian police reacted with tear gas and water cannons at [[Horgo\u0161]] 2 border crossing. [[Belgrade]] protested these actions. A 20-year-old [[Iraqi refugee]] was sentenced to deportation and one-year entry ban in Hungary, as well as \u20ac80 in court fees, according to the new law put into action a few days before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/kaos-na-madjarskoj-granici-izbjeglice-probili-ogradu-cuje-se-pucnjava-policija-mlati-ljude/842284.aspx#lightbox[galerija]/0/|title=Kaos na ma\u0111arskoj granici: Izbjeglice probili ogradu, \u010dula se pucnjava, policija mlatila ljude|work=index.hr|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> On 18 September, Hungary started building another fence, this time along the border with Croatia, a fellow EU member state, but not part of the Schengen Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/policija-zatvorila-granicu-prema-srbiji--izbjeglice-do-daljnjega-ostaju-kod-nas/1420334/|title=U\u017dIVO: SUZAVAC PRIMIRIO IZBJEGLICE NA GRANICI KOD ZAPRE\u0160I\u0106A! Hrvatski policajci izba\u010deni s vlaka u Ma\u0111arskoj: 'Nisu razoru\u017eani, samo su ih evidentirali. Ni\u0161ta dramati\u010dno se nije dogodilo...' |work=jutarnji.hr|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Within two weeks, tens of thousands of refugees crossed from Croatia into Hungary, most of whom went toward the Austrian border.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bbj.hu/politics/more-than-24000-refugees-enter-hungary-over-weekend_104760|title=More than 24,000 refugees enter Hungary over weekend|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 October 2015, Hungary announced that it would close its [[green border]] with Croatia to migrants,<ref name=HungaryCroatia2/> and since 17 October onward, thousands of migrants daily were diverted to Slovenia instead.<ref name=SloveniaCroatia2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/18/world/europe/hungary-closes-border-changing-refugees-path.html|title=Hungary Closes Border, Changing Refugees' Path|author1=Barbara Surk |author2=Stephen Castle |newspaper=The New York Times|date=17 October 2015|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2016 Hungary declared a state of emergency for the whole of the country, and was deploying 1500 soldiers to the borders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hungarytoday.hu/news/breaking-news-hungary-declares-state-emergency-migrant-crisis-turns-unpredictable-96001|title=Breaking News: Hungary Declares State Of Emergency As Migrant Crisis Turns Unpredictable|work=Hungary Today|accessdate=21 March 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.novinite.com/articles/173459/Hungary+Declares+State+of+Emergency+Over+Migrants Hungary Declares State of Emergency Over Migrants] (novinite.com 9 March 2016)</ref> In August 2017 the state of emergency was extended to March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wtop.com/europe/2017/08/hungary-extends-state-of-emergency-due-to-migrant-crisis/|title=Hungary extends state of emergency due to migrant crisis|date=30 August 2017|work=WTOP|access-date=30 August 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831085120/http://wtop.com/europe/2017/08/hungary-extends-state-of-emergency-due-to-migrant-crisis/|archive-date=31 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\n{{Main|Lampedusa immigrant reception center|Immigration to Italy}}\n{{flagu|Italy}} \u2013 Some Italian towns and cities have refused instructions from the national government to house migrants.<ref name=Legorno>{{cite news |last1=Legorno |first1=Giovanni |title=Italian Towns Push Back on Growing Burden of Europe's Migrant Crisis |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/italian-towns-push-back-on-growing-burden-of-europes-migrant-crisis-1430085784 |accessdate=18 August 2015 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=28 April 2015}}</ref> The [[Mafia Capitale investigation]] revealed that the [[Organized crime in Italy|Italian Mafia]] profits from the migrant crisis and exploits refugees.<ref>\"[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0d0371d0-31f4-11e5-8873-775ba7c2ea3d.html Italy\u2019s Mafia learns to profit from the migration crisis]\". ''[[Financial Times]]''. 24 July 2015</ref><ref>\"[http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/latenightlive/how-the-mafia-profits-from-the-mediterranean-migrant-crisis/6573084 'Bigger than drugs': how the Mafia profits from the Mediterranean migrant crisis]\". ABC News. 29 June 2015</ref> [[Pope Francis]] thanked the [[Italian navy]] for migrant rescue effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/04/18/pope-thanks-italy-for-migrant-rescue-effort-says-huge-numbers-means-europe-must/|title=Pope thanks Italy for migrant rescue effort, says huge numbers means Europe must pitch in more|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=19 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925172832/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/04/18/pope-thanks-italy-for-migrant-rescue-effort-says-huge-numbers-means-europe-must/|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[murder of Ashley Ann Olsen]] in her Italian apartment by an illegal immigrant from [[Senegal]] rapidly acquired political significance in the context of the European migrant crisis. The police chief of [[Florence]] addressed safety worries, \"assuring the public that Florence remained safe\" in the wake of the Olsen murder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pianigiani |first1=Gaia |title=Italy Arrests Suspect in Death of American Woman|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/15/world/europe/ashley-ann-olsen-italy-arrest.html |work=New York Times |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, thousands of migrants have been trying every month to cross the Central Mediterranean to Italy, risking their lives on unsafe boats including fishing trawlers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/24/libyas-people-smugglers-how-will-they-catch-us-theyll-soon-move-on |title=Libya's people smugglers: inside the trade that sells refugees hopes of a better life &#124; World news |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2018-06-28}}</ref> Many of them are fleeing poverty-stricken homelands or war-torn countries and seeking economic opportunity within the EU.<ref name=\"Boatsform Libya\">{{cite news |last1=Scammell |first1=Rosie |title=Mediterranean migrant crisis: number of arrivals in Italy in 2015 passes 50,000 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/07/mediterranean-migrant-arrivals-italy-passes-50000 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=7 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/11549216/The-EU-migrant-crisis-explained-in-90-seconds.html |title=Video: The EU migrant crisis explained in 90 seconds \u2013 Telegraph |date=22 April 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=28 August 2015 |location=London |first=Joe |last=Daunt}}</ref> Italy, and, in particular, its southern island of [[Lampedusa]], receives enormous numbers of Africans and Middle-Easterners transported by smugglers and NGOs operating along the ungoverned coast of the [[failed state]] of Libya.<ref name=\"Boatsform Libya\" /><ref name=MappingBBC>{{cite news |title=Mapping Mediterranean migration |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-24521614 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boat People at Sicily in the Mediterranean Sea.jpg|thumb|left|Migrants arrived in [[Lampedusa]] ]]\n\nIn 2014, 170,100 migrants arrived in Italy by sea, a 296 percent increase compared to 2013. 141,484 of the travellers ferried over from Libya. Most of the migrants had come from [[Syria]], [[Eritrea]], and various countries in [[West Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Analisi: Paolo Gentiloni |url=https://pagellapolitica.it/dichiarazioni/analisi/5221/paolo-gentiloni |work=Pagella Politica |date=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom January to April 2015, about 1600 migrants died on the route from Libya to Lampedusa, making it the deadliest migrant route in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/about-700-believed-dead-in-shipwreck-off-libya-says-unhcr-1429432174? |title=Hundreds of Migrants Believed Dead in Shipwreck Off Libya, Says UNHCR |accessdate=19 April 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=19 April 2015}}</ref> As a consequence of the April 2015 Libya [[List of migrant vessel incidents on the Mediterranean Sea|migrant shipwrecks]], the EU launched a military operation known as [[EU Navfor Med|Operation Sophia]]. More than 13,000 migrants had been rescued from the sea in the course of the operation as of April 2016.<ref name=\"auto11\">\"[http://www.dw.com/en/on-the-mediterranean-refugee-patrol-with-the-bundeswehr/a-19209234 On the Mediterranean refugee patrol with the Bundeswehr]\". [[Deutsche Welle]]. 22 April 2016.</ref>\n\nThere were 153,842 Mediterranean sea arrivals to Italy in 2015, 9 percent less than the previous year; most of the refugees and migrants came from [[Eritrea]], [[Nigeria]], and [[Somalia]], whereas the number of Syrian refugees sharply decreased, as most of them took the Eastern Mediterranean route from Turkey to Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertaciviliimmigrazione.interno.it/dipim/site/it/documentazione/statistiche/servizi_civili/2016/1_2016_Statistiche_2015_sbarchix_esiti_domande_di_asilo_e_posti_in_strutture_accoglienza.html |title=Statistiche immigrazione |publisher=Italian Ministry of the Interior |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328233432/http://www.libertaciviliimmigrazione.interno.it/dipim/site/it/documentazione/statistiche/servizi_civili/2016/1_2016_Statistiche_2015_sbarchix_esiti_domande_di_asilo_e_posti_in_strutture_accoglienza.html |archivedate=28 March 2016 }}</ref>\n[[File:Messina1.jpg|thumb|[[Eritrea]]n migrants in [[Messina]], October 2015]]\nThe first three months of 2016 saw an increase in the number of migrants rescued at sea being brought to southern Italian ports.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-eu-idUSKCN0XA1EO EU sees 'alarming' migrant buildup in Libya, warns Italy]\". Reuters. 13 April 2016.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-wants-austria-to-explain-threat-to-close-border-with-italy-1460719198 Tensions Mount Between Austria and Italy as Migrant Numbers Rise]\". ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. 15 April 2016.</ref><ref>\"[http://navaltoday.com/2016/03/17/german-warship-rescues-615-from-the-mediterranean/ German warship rescues 615 from the Mediterranean]\". ''Naval Today.'' 17 March 2016.</ref> In April 2016, nearly 6,000 mostly sub-Saharan African migrants have landed in Italy in just four days.<ref>\"[http://qz.com/663014/photos-in-the-last-four-days-6000-migrants-have-arrived-to-sicily-by-boat-from-libya/ In the last four days, 6,000 migrants have arrived in Sicily by boat]\". ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]].'' 16 April 2016.</ref> In June 2016, over 10,000 migrants have been rescued in just four days.<ref name=\"DW\">\"[http://www.dw.com/en/italian-coastguard-and-navy-rescue-3300-migrants-off-coast-of-libya/a-19358699 Italian coastguard and navy rescue 3,300 migrants off coast of Libya]\". ''[[Deutsche Welle]]''. 27 June 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, 181,100 migrants arrived in Italy by sea.<ref>\"[https://www.thelocal.it/20170106/italys-boat-migrant-numbers-surged-20-in-2016 Italy boat migrant numbers surge 20% in 2016]\". ''[[The Local]]''. 6 January 2017.</ref> In April 2017, more than 8,000 migrants were rescued near Libya and brought to Italy in just three days.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/18/8000-migrants-rescued-mediterranean-brought-italy-easter-long/ More than 8,000 migrants rescued in Mediterranean and brought to Italy over Easter long weekend ]\". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. 18 April 2017.</ref> Based on UN-data, about 80,000 refugees were registered at Italian refugee centers in the first half of 2017, an increase of 14 percent compared to the same time period in 2016. In June 2017, 10,000 asylum seekers were picked up in the Mediterranean sea by the Italian coastguard and other naval vessels in just a couple of days. EU ambassador Maurizio Massari has expressed concern about the recent uptake of refugee arrivals on Italian's coastline, which would reach 200,000 in 2017. As a result, foreign aid vessels docking in Italian ports may no longer be able to do so because of stricter admission policies and exceeded limits in Italian asylum centers.<ref>\n[https://www.blick.ch/news/ausland/das-land-droht-mit-krassen-massnahmen-gegen-fluechtlinge-hilfeschrei-aus-italien-id6919283.html Hilfeschrei aus Italien!] Das Land droht mit krassen Massnahmen gegen Fl\u00fcchtlinge (in German). ''Blick \u2013 Ausland''. Retrieved 29 June 2017.</ref> In February 2017 Italian government accepted to fund Libyan coastguard. Since then many migrants were forced to go back to Libya.<ref name=\"auto12\"/>\n\nIn July 2017, Italy drew up a code of conduct for NGO rescue vessels delivering migrants to Italian ports. These rules include\n* Except in situations of imminent danger, not to enter the [[territorial waters]] of Libya.\n* Never to switch off the [[Automatic identification system|Automatic Identification System]] (AIS) and [[Long-range identification and tracking (ships)|LRIT]] transponders if they are installed on the ship.\n* Not to signal human traffickers with flares or radio to coordinate with them when to send out their [[Dinghy|dinghies]].\n* Not to transfer those rescued onto other vessels.\n* Commit to carrying a policeman to travel on board whenever requested in order to identify and prosecute human traffickers among the migrants.\nHuman Rights Watch and Amnesty International have criticised the code of conduct and some NGOs like [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|MSF]] refused to sign. Italian authorities feared that rather than saving lives, the NGO operations encouraged more people to try the very dangerous passage facilitated by human traffickers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-msf-idUSKBN1AS0L1|title=MSF suspends Mediterranean rescues as migrant dispute mounts|last=|first=|date=12 August 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2017/08/03/text-of-italys-code-of-conduct-for-ngos-involved-in-migrant-rescue|title=Italy's code of conduct for NGOs involved in migrant rescue: text|date=3 August 2017|website=euronews|access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref> NGO ships not behaving according to the code could be refused access to Italian ports.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAfter the entry into force of the NGO code, in July 2017 arrivals decreased by 52.5 percent compared to the same month of 2016, from 23,552 to 11,183,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/notizie/2017-07-31/migranti-luglio-si-inverte-trend-sbarchi-dimezzati-133105.shtml?uuid=AEZMsb6B&refresh_ce=1|title=Migranti, si inverte il trend: a luglio sbarchi dimezzati|date=31 July 2017|website=ilsole24ore.com|access-date=16 September 2017|language=it}}</ref> and in August 2017 arrivals decreased by 85 percent, form 21,294 to 3,914.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interno.gov.it/sites/default/files/cruscotto_giornaliero_14_settembre_2017.pdf|title=Cruscotto giornaliero 14 settembre 2017|date=14 September 2017|website=interno.gov.it|access-date=16 September 2017|language=it|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916225451/http://www.interno.gov.it/sites/default/files/cruscotto_giornaliero_14_settembre_2017.pdf|archivedate=16 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also all NGO, except Sos M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e, have withdrawn their ships from the Mediterranean.\n\nFrom January to November 2017, some 114,600 migrants arrived in Italy by sea.<ref>\"[http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/north-africa/2017/11/23/Italy-says-1-100-migrants-from-Libyan-coast-rescued-in-one-day.html Italy: 1,100 migrants rescued from Libyan coast in one day]\". Al Arabiya. 23 November 2017.</ref> Approximately 5,000 African migrants were rescued in waters off the coast of Libya between 18\u201320 May 2017.<ref>\"[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/05/5000-refugees-rescued-route-italy-libya-170520134511012.html 5,000 refugees rescued on route to Italy from Libya]\". Al Jazeera. 20 May 2017.</ref>\n\nSince 2013, the country took in over 700,000 migrants,<ref>{{cite web |title=What will Italy's new government mean for migrants? |url=https://www.thelocal.it/20180521/what-will-italys-new-government-mean-for-migrants |website=The Local |date=21 May 2018}}</ref> mainly from sub-Saharan Africa.<ref>{{cite news |title=African migrants fear for future as Italy struggles with surge in arrivals |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-italy-migrants-africa/african-migrants-fear-for-future-as-italy-struggles-with-surge-in-arrivals-idUSKBN1A30QD |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Latvia===\n\n{{flagu|Latvia}} \u2013 Latvia decided to receive 250 migrants in the next two years according to the EU plan. [[National Alliance (Latvia)|National Alliance party]] expressed its disapproval of such decision. On 4 August 2015 around 250 activists gathered in [[Riga]] on a protest against Government's decision on receiving migrants.\n\n===Lithuania===\n{{flagu|Lithuania}} \u2013 Lithuania decided to receive 325 migrants, although after the increase of migrant flow in August 2015, its government did not discount the possibility of accepting a greater number of migrants later in the same year.<ref name=DELFI>{{cite news |title=PM says Lithuanian government not considering to accept more refugees |url=http://en.delfi.lt/lithuania/politics/pm-says-lithuanian-government-not-considering-to-accept-morerefugees.d?id=68893804 |accessdate=3 September 2015 |work=BNS |date=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Malta===\n{{Main|Demographics of Malta#Immigration}}\n\n{{flagu|Malta}} \u2013 Prime Minister [[Joseph Muscat]] called the crisis \"an ugly period\" for Europe, and said that Malta will take in 75 migrants from Italy and Greece.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=Migrant wall will not stop problem, Joseph Muscat says|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150913/local/migrant-wall-will-not-stop-problem-joseph-muscat-says.584315|accessdate=13 September 2015|work=[[The Times (Malta)|The Times]]|date=13 September 2015}}</ref> He also called for a 'global system of refugee quotas'.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/hungary/11903664/Hungary-and-Malta-call-for-global-migrant-quotas-to-ease-Europe-burden.html Hungary and Malta call for 'global migrant quotas' to ease Europe burden]\". ''The Daily Telegraph''. 1 October 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:02015-10-02 Der anti-islamische Protest in Polen.JPG|thumb|Anti-immigration rally in [[Poland]] in 2015]]\n\nBetween 2008 and 2012, Malta received on average the highest number of [[asylum seekers]] compared to its national population: 21.7 applicants per 1,000 inhabitants.<ref name=\"UNHCR\">{{cite web|url=http://unhcr.org/asylumtrends/UNHCR%20ASYLUM%20TRENDS%202012_WEB.pdf |title=UNHCR |accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>{{rp|13}} In 2011, most of these asylum applications were submitted by nationals of [[Somalia]], [[Nigeria]], [[Eritrea]] and [[Syria]].<ref name=\"UNHCR\"/>{{rp|26}} In 2012, more than half of the requests were by [[Somalia]]n nationals alone.<ref name=\"UNHCR\"/>{{rp|45}} In a 2013 news story, ''The Guardian'' reported, \"Before Malta joined the EU in 2004, immigration levels were negligible. Because it is located close to north Africa, it has now become a gateway for migrants seeking entry to Europe.\"<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/04/malta-needs-eu-help-immigration-crisis Malta needs EU help to cope with its immigration crisis]\". ''[[The Guardian]]''. 4 August 2013.</ref> Following the arrival of asylum seekers, Malta was unable to cope with accommodating asylum seekers in a manner which was congruent with EU standards on the reception of asylum seekers, particularly standards related to housing.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn 2015, very few migrants arrived in Malta compared to previous years, since most of those rescued were taken to [[Italy]]. In September, 78 migrants rescued by the [[Armed Forces of Malta]] refused to be brought to Malta.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rescued migrants refusing to be brought to Malta|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150926/local/rescued-migrants-refusing-to-be-brought-to-malta.585856|accessdate=26 September 2015|work=[[The Times (Malta)|The Times]]|date=26 September 2015}}</ref> They insisted on going to Italy, and were eventually taken there.<ref>{{cite news|title=It-78 immigrant li ma riedux jid\u0127lu f'Malta se jittie\u0127du l-Italja|url=http://www.tvm.com.mt/mt/news/it-78-immigrant-li-ma-riedux-jidhlu-fmalta-se-jittiehdu-l-italja/|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[TVM (Malta)|TVM]]|date=27 September 2015|language=mt}}</ref>\n\n===Melilla and Ceuta (Spain)===\n{{Main|Morocco\u2013Spain border|Melilla border fence|Ceuta border fence}}\n[[Melilla]] and [[Ceuta]], two autonomous Spanish cities on the north coast of Africa bordering [[Morocco]], are the only EU territories to share a land border with an African country.<ref>\"[https://theweek.com/articles/572833/spanish-city-africa-become-hugely-symbolic-europes-migrant-crisis This Spanish city in Africa has become hugely symbolic of Europe's migrant crisis]\". ''[[The Week]]''. 21 August 2015.</ref> The number of undocumented migrants hoping to reach the EU via Melilla or Ceuta grew in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.euronews.com/en/293928/ |title=euronews \u2013 Over 100 migrants attempt to storm Melilla enclave |publisher=euronews.com |accessdate=28 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726000233/http://m.euronews.com/en/293928/ |archive-date=26 July 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Between January and September 2015, only 100 people out of 3700 hopefuls have managed to cross the Melilla border fence, down from 2100 people from 19,000 attempts the previous year.<ref name=\"Morel 2015\">{{cite web | last=Morel | first=Sandrine | title=Uneasy calm descends over Melilla, Spain's heavily fortified African enclave | website=The Guardian | date=8 September 2015 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/08/melilla-fences-spain-morocco-migration-europe | accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, 165 people were rescued from fourteen attempts to cross the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] to reach Ceuta.<ref name=\"Edwards 2015\">{{cite web | last=Edwards | first=Sam | title=A decade of violence at Spain's forgotten African border shows why Europe's new fences alone are bound to fail | website=El Pa\u00eds | date=21 November 2015 | url=http://blogs.elpais.com/trans-iberian/2015/11/a-decade-of-violence-at-spains-forgotten-african-border-shows-why-europes-new-fences-alone-are-bound.html | accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a report published on 17 November 2015, [[Amnesty International]] called on Spain to cease cooperation with Morocco on immigration matters because of alleged human rights abuses on the Melilla and Ceuta borders. Amnesty said it has \"photographs, images and evidence\" of \"blows with sticks, feet and stones\" on migrants attempting to get to Spain.<ref name=\"Bloul 2015\">{{cite web | last=Bloul | first=Scheherazade | title=Amnesty International Calls for Spain to Cease Cooperation with Morocco on Migration Policy | website=Morocco World News | date=17 November 2015 | url=http://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2015/11/172878/amnesty-international-calls-on-spain-to-cease-cooperation-with-morocco-on-migration-policy/ | accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref> Other reports accuse Spain of using rubber bullets and tear gas to prevent migrants from reaching Spanish territory. The Spanish Government said that it has now banned its border guards from using rubber bullets to repel migrants.<ref name=\"The Local.es Dec 2015\">{{cite web | title=Two dead as migrants storm Spain's African border at Ceuta | website=The Local | date=25 December 2015 | url=http://www.thelocal.es/20151225/two-dead-as-migrants-storm-spanish-border | accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nMigrants have been found trying to smuggle themselves into Ceuta and Melillia in cars and suitcases, including in March 2016, when migrants were discovered hiding in \"impossibly small spaces\" in a car at the Melilla border crossing, with some in the dashboard area and some under the back seat. According to the authorities, people are found hiding in cars almost every day.<ref name=\"Mailonline March 2016\">{{cite web | last=Calderwood | first=Imogen  | title=Spanish Civil Guard discover migrants hiding in cars' false bottoms | website=Mail Online | date=25 March 2016 | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3509873/Spanish-Civil-Guard-discover-six-immigrants-hidden-false-bottoms-vehicles-operated-mafia-smuggling-ring.html | accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> Also, in May 2015, an 8-year-old boy from [[Ivory Coast]] was found in a suitcase being smuggled into Ceuta, when the police opened the case, they found him in a \"terrible state\".<ref name=\"BBC News Ceuta 2015\">{{cite web | title=Ivory Coast boy smuggled to Spain inside suitcase | website=BBC News | date=8 May 2015 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-32660135 | accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref> And in December 2016, one migrant was found in a suitcase, carried by a Moroccan woman, trying to get into Ceuta.<ref name=\"BBC News Ceuta 2017\">{{cite web | title=Spain Ceuta: Migrants found hidden in car and suitcase | website=BBC News | date=2 January 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38490868 | accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref> On 1 January 2017, there was an attempt by 1100 migrants to cross the Ceuta border fence. 50 Moroccans and five Spanish border guards prevented them from crossing the fence, but one border guard lost an eye during the attempt.<ref name=\"BBC News Ceuta 2017\" />\n\n===Norway===\n{{See also|Norway\u2013Russia border barrier}}\nThe number of migrants crossing from [[Russia-Norway border|Russia into Norway]] increased from a handful in the first half of 2015 to 420 asylum seekers crossing by bicycle in September 2015 alone.<ref name=ArcticRoute>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/10/world/europe/bypassing-the-risky-sea-refugees-reach-europe-through-the-arctic.html?hpw&rref=world&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0|title=Avoiding Risky Seas, Migrants Reach Europe With an Arctic Bike Ride|author=Andrew Higgins |newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 October 2015|accessdate=9 October 2015}}</ref> As of 11 December 2015 over 4,000 migrants had crossed the Northern border, and the Norwegian government vowed to send all migrants with Russian residence visa back to Russia even if they were from countries experiencing conflicts such as [[Norwegian Army#War in Afghanistan|Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"no-ru-limbo-local\">{{cite news|work=[[The Local]]|title=Russia sends denied migrants back to Norway|url=http://www.thelocal.no/20151130/norway-irked-as-russia-sends-back-asylum-seekers|date=30 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"no-ru-limbo-sputnik\">{{cite news|work=Sputnik|language=Norwegian Bokm\u00e5l|title=Grensen til Russland er ikke den farligste for Norge|trans-title=The border with Russia is not the most dangerous for Norway|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123132908/http://no.sputniknews.com/norden/20151107/885081/russland-norge-flyktninger-grense.html|archivedate=23 January 2016|url=http://no.sputniknews.com/norden/20151107/885081/russland-norge-flyktninger-grense.html|date=7 November 2015}}</ref> In 2016, 5,500 [[asylum-seeker]]s illegally entered Norway from Russia.<ref name=\"NYTimesFence\"/><ref name=\"PancevskyColdShoulder\">{{cite news|last1=Pancevsky|first1=Bojan|title=Norway builds Arctic border fence as it gives migrants the cold shoulder|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/norway-builds-arctic-border-fence-as-it-gives-migrants-the-cold-shoulder-hf37jlwqq|accessdate=6 September 2016|newspaper=[[The Times of London]]|date=4 September 2016}}</ref> Norway began sending migrants back to conflict-torn countries of origin, such as Afghanistan, defying Amnesty International. The number of migrants returned from Europe to Afghanistan between 2015\u201316 nearly tripled from 3290 to 9460.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4968868/eu-betraying-afghanistan-dangerous-aid-policy/|title=Europe is Betraying Afghanistan By Sending Its Refugees Home|website=Time}}</ref> Because it is illegal to drive from Russia to Norway without proper legal permission, and crossing on foot is prohibited, the migrants make the crossing on bicycles.<ref name=\"Osborne\">{{cite news|last1=Osborne|first1=Samuel|title=Norway to build border fence with Russia to keep out refugees|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/norway-border-fence-russia-refugees-refugee-crisis-schengen-syria-war-a7208806.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=25 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"HovlandArcticRoute\">{{cite news|last1=Hovland|first1=Kjetil Malkenes|title=Syrian Refugees Take Arctic Route to Europe More than 150 refugees have entered Norway from Arctic Russia this year|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/syrian-refugees-take-arctic-route-to-europe-1441273767|accessdate=6 September 2016|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=3 September 2015}}</ref> It was in 2016 decided that a barrier will be located at the [[Storskog]] border crossing.<ref name=\"NYTimesFence\"/> It will be built of steel and will stand {{convert|660|ft|m}} long and {{convert|11|ft|m}} to {{convert|12|ft|m}} high.<ref name=\"NYTimesFence\"/> Norwegian officials aim to complete the barrier before winter temperatures harden the ground.<ref name=\"NYTimesFence\">{{cite news|title=Norway Will Build a Fence at Its Arctic Border With Russia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/25/world/europe/russia-norway-border-fence-refugees.html|accessdate=6 September 2016|agency=Reuters|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Statistics Norway reported that of recently arrived [[Syrians in Norway|migrants from Syria]] there was a high proportion (67 percent) with only basic education (Norwegian: ''Grunnskole'').<ref>{{cite book |title=Innvandrere og norskf\u00f8dte med innvandrerforeldre fra Syria |date=26 June 2018 |publisher=[[Statistics Norway]] |page=26 |url=https://www.ssb.no/befolkning/artikler-og-publikasjoner/_attachment/355170?_ts=1645efbce30 |accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Slovakia===\n{{flagu|Slovakia}} \u2013 Government of Slovakia stated that it would help with migration into Europe by receiving 200 migrants according to the EU plan, but on condition that the migrants are [[Christianity|Christians]].<ref name=Troianoski /> Slovak Prime Minister [[Robert Fico]] said: \"I have only one question: who bombed Libya? Who caused problems in North Africa? Slovakia? No!\" The Prime Minister proposed temporary refuge in his country for 500 migrants who have submitted requests for asylum in Austria, whose accommodation for refugees is overfilled, but as for 200 migrants that Slovakia will receive according to the EU plan, requires that these 500 are Christians as well. On 15 September 2015, Fico was reported saying that all crossing the border illegally would be detained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rt.com/news/315293-schengen-border-control-toughened/|title=End of Schengen? EU countries toughen border control|work=RT English|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Fico rejected European Commission plan to distribute migrants among EU member states, saying: \"As long as I am prime minister, mandatory quotas will not be implemented on Slovak territory.\"<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/eu/11887390/This-East-West-split-over-EU-refugee-quotas-will-have-long-lasting-consequences.html This East-West split over EU refugee quotas will have long-lasting consequences]\". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]].'' 24 September 2015.</ref> [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|S&D]] Group leader has proposed to suspend Fico's [[Direction \u2013 Social Democracy|SMER]] party from the [[Party of European Socialists]] (PES).<ref>\"[http://www.euractiv.com/sections/justice-home-affairs/refugee-crisis-reveals-fundamental-splits-european-political-parties Refugee crisis reveals fundamental splits in European political parties]\". EurActiv. 24 September 2015.</ref>\n\n===Slovenia===\n{{See also|Slovenian border barrier}}\n[[File:Ministrica obiskala pripadnike Slovenske vojske in URSZR, ki pomagajo v nastanitvenem centru in na meji 01.JPG|thumb|Migrants in Slovenia, November 2015]]\nSlovenia established temporary controls on the otherwise unsupervised border with Hungary in the north east on 17 September 2015, following Germany and Austria's similar actions.<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenia Reinstating Controls at Border with Hungary|url = http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenia-reinstating-controls-at-border-with-hungary|publisher = sloveniatimes.com|accessdate = 19 September 2015}}</ref> On 18 September, Slovenia experienced the first larger and largely illegal border crossing occurrences, coming mostly from Croatia, already overwhelmed by the large influx of migrant groups.\n\nOn the evening of 18 September, the Slovenian riot police were forced to use [[pepper spray]] on a bridge at the [[Harmica]] border to prevent migrants and activists from illegally crossing the border from Croatia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/latest-un-agency-calls-joint-european-response-113758508.html|title=Slovenian police pepper spray migrants at border|publisher=Yahoo!|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy midday of 19 September, the country had registered around 1500 migrants, with all of them being accommodated in temporary reception camps or asylum centres. The largest traffic was seen at [[Obre\u017eje, Bre\u017eice|Obre\u017eje border crossing]], [[Dobova|Dobova border crossing]] and [[Bre\u017eice]]. Prime Minister [[Miro Cerar]] visited the reception centre in Bre\u017eice on Saturday, stressing that Slovenia had the situation under control, while criticising the Croatian government for being uncooperative.<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenia Admits Some 1,500 Refugees, Some Proceed to Austria|url = http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenia-admits-some-1-500-refugees-some-proceed-to-austria|publisher = sloveniatimes.com|accessdate = 19 September 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Slovenska vojska pri re\u0161evanju migrantske situacije z ve\u010d zmogljivostmi 01.jpg|alt=large group of migrants moving along a road, being directed by the army and police|left|thumb|Arrival of migrants in Dobova, Slovenia]]\nThere were also various humanitarian and non-governmental organisations aiding the migrants on the border, coming mostly from Slovenia, Croatia and Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title = Begunce z Obre\u017eja pospe\u0161eno odva\u017eajo v notranjost dr\u017eave|url = http://www.dolenjskilist.si/2015/09/19/140941/novice/novice_splosno/Begunce_z_Obrezja_pospeseno_odvazajo_v_notranjost_drzave/|website = Dolenjski list|accessdate = 19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 18 October, the country began receiving large numbers of refugees, which soon exceeded the upper admission limit of 2,500. On 22 October, the police reported 12,600 migrant arrivals in 24 hours, reportedly a record, and more than Hungary had received in any one day. The Slovenian government also passed a law giving the army more powers and asked the EU for aid. The latter responded by sending the commissioner for migration to Slovenia, and announcing a \"mini EU summit\".<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenia calls for EU help amid record influx of refugees|url = http://www.euronews.com/2015/10/22/slovenia-calls-for-eu-help-amid-record-influx-of-refugees/|website = euronews|accessdate = 24 October 2015|date = 22 October 2015}}</ref> On the same day the Slovenian government accused the Croatian police of leading migrants through cold waters in an effort to bypass the Slovene controls by crossing the green border, and released a night time thermovision video apparently showing the events on the preceding night.<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenian police helicopter films Croatian police officers directing migrants to Slovenia across the green border and the Sotla river|url = http://www.policija.si/eng/index.php/component/content/article/13-news/1739-slovenian-police-helicopter-films-croatian-police-officers-directing-migrants-to-slovenia-across-the-green-border-and-the-sotla-river|website = policija.si|accessdate = 24 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = \u0160efic: Croatian travesty on inhuman Slovenians :: Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|url = https://www.rtvslo.si/news-in-english/sefic-croatian-travesty-on-inhuman-slovenians/376964|website = rtvslo.si|accessdate = 24 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy 24 October, Slovenia had reported more than 56,000 total migrant arrivals.<ref>{{cite web|title = V \u017dIVO: Pretep v sprejemnem centru Bre\u017eice, policija je uporabila plinski razpr\u0161ilec|url = http://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/samo-vceraj-in-danes-je-preko-zelene-meje-pri-rigoncah-v-slovenijo-vstopilo-okoli-13-000-tujcev.html|publisher = 24ur.com|accessdate = 24 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November, Prime Minister Cerar announced that Slovenia would impose ''temporary technical hurdles'' to control migrants, but that the country would not close border crossings.<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenia to impose \"hurdles\" on border to control migrant flow :: Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|url = http://www.rtvslo.si/news-in-english/slovenia-to-impose-hurdles-on-border-to-control-migrant-flow/378324|website = rtvslo.si|accessdate = 11 November 2015}}</ref> On 11 November, Slovenian military personnel began the construction of the fence consisting of razor wire.<ref>{{cite web|title = Slovenian troops start erecting border fence :: Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|url = http://www.rtvslo.si/news-in-english/slovenian-troops-start-erecting-border-fence/378397|website = rtvslo.si|accessdate = 11 November 2015}}</ref> The Austrian minister of the interior [[Johanna Mikl-Leitner]] expressed full support for the Slovenian government's action on the border with Croatia.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://orf.at/stories/2309111/2309109/|title = ORF|access-date = 11 November 2015|via = |language = German}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2016, German press noted that Slovenia decided to deploy army on the border facing Croatia, to assist the police. It was noted, that the bill did not approve military action, however noting that the army was still authorized to use force in the case of emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/slovenia-deploys-army-to-schengen-zone-border-to-tackle-refugee-influx/a-19066844|title=Slovenia deploys army to Schengen zone border to tackle refugee influx|work=DW.COM|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Spain===\nFrom 2000 until at least 2016, dealing with irregularly arriving migrants on the Spanish [[Canary Islands]], Spain developed a purportedly efficient plan to manage that inflow, consisting in four aspects:\n*Strengthening bilateral ties and close cooperation with local actors in all origin and transit countries\n*Bilateral partnership agreements with those countries\n*Security, intelligence and policy strategies and joint actions\n*Legal avenues and resettlement policies through agreements with those countries.<ref>[http://www.iris-france.org/80796-eu-spain-and-the-refugee-crisis/ 'EU, Spain and the refugee crisis']. Interview with refugee expert Patricia Lisa, Research Fellow at [[Elcano Royal Institute|Real Instituto Elcano]], October 2016, on IRIS (Institut de Relations Internationales et Strat\u00e9giques, a French think tank). Retrieved 26 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Spain]] saw a huge increase in the number of asylum applicants, fast catching up to Italy and Greece in terms of popularity as a destination country, with nearly 8300 people trying to enter in the first half of this year itself.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThe International Organization for Migration recorded a 217 percent increase in the first seven months of 2017 compared with the same period in 2016, when more than 8,000 arrived throughout the year.<ref name=hrw2017>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/07/31/spain-migrants-held-poor-conditions|title=Spain: Migrants Held in Poor Conditions|date=31 July 2017|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=5 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Authorities believe that Spain is ill-equipped to handle the surging numbers of migrants. Reports of women and children being kept in inhumane conditions have surfaced, pushing governments and organizations to devise short-term policies to help curb the pressure.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} \nSeveral deaths were recorded in 2017 on a daily basis, both at the destination and during the journey, but this does not deter migrants, who are more economic migrants than war refugees, coming mostly from Western African nations such as Gambia, Guinea, Senegal etc.<ref name=hrw2017/>\n\n===Sweden===\n\nDuring all of 2015, migration authorities reported 500 cases of suspected terrorism links or war criminals to [[Swedish Security Service]].<ref name=\"sydsvenskan_5juli2016\">{{cite news|title=Migrationsverket anm\u00e4ler allt fler terrorhot|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/2016-07-05/migrationsverket-anmaler-allt-fler-terrorhot|accessdate=20 August 2016|newspaper=Sydsvenskan|date=5 July 2016}}</ref> Twenty individuals were denied asylum in 2015 due to [[war crimes]].<ref name=\"sydsvenskan_5juli2016\" />\n\nIn November 2015, Sweden reintroduced border controls for arrivals, including the [[\u00d6resund Bridge]]. This did not have so much effect on the inflow of asylum seekers, since they had the right to apply for asylum once they were on Swedish ground. In December 2015, Sweden passed a temporary law that allows the government to oblige all transport companies to check that their passengers carry valid photographic identification before border crossing. The new law came into effect on 21 December 2015 and is valid until 21 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riksdagen.se/sv/Dokument-Lagar/Utskottens-dokument/Betankanden/Arenden/201516/JuU24/|title=S\u00e4rskilda \u00e5tg\u00e4rder vid allvarlig fara f\u00f6r den allm\u00e4nna ordningen eller den inre s\u00e4kerheten i landet \u2013 riksdagen.se|author=Riksdagsf\u00f6rvaltningen|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> The government decided that the new rules will apply from 4 January 2016 until 4 July 2016. The new law led to the mandatory train change and passage through border control at [[Copenhagen Airport, Kastrup Station|Copenhagen Airport station]] for travellers between Copenhagen and Sweden, and with a reduction in service frequency.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35159183 Migrant crisis: Sweden operator cancels trains on bridge link] BBC News website. Retrieved 23 December 2015<!-- News sites have somewhat misunderstood the thing. Direct trains are cancelled but it will be possible to travel with a train change, although SJ cancel all their operations. This info has to be reassessed in January 2016. --></ref>\n\nOn the first day of border controls this led to a reduction in the number of migrants arriving to southern Sweden from the previous hundreds to some dozens.<ref name=sds_5jan2016>{{cite news|title=Bara 48 asyls\u00f6kande till Sk\u00e5ne under m\u00e5ndagen|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/sverige/bara-48-asylsokande-till-skane-under-mandagen/|accessdate=5 January 2016|work=[[Sydsvenskan]]|date=5 January 2016}}</ref> Within hours of Swedish border control becoming effective, Denmark in turn created a border control between Denmark and Germany.<ref name=sds_4Jan2016>{{cite news|title=F\u00e4rre \u00e4n 100 nobbade p\u00e5 Kastrup|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/sverige/inga-koer-vid-kritiserade-kontrollen/|accessdate=5 January 2016|work=[[Sydsvenskan]]|date=4 January 2016}}</ref> The migration pattern also changed with the majority of those arriving by ferry from Germany to [[Trelleborg]] instead of by train to [[Hyllie]] station,<ref name=sds_5jan2016/> bypassing the border control between Denmark and Germany.<ref name=sds_4Jan2016/> Migrants then started taking taxis in greater numbers over the \u00d6resund Bridge in order to evade identification.<ref name=sds_7jan2016>{{cite news|title=Pappersl\u00f6sa tar taxi \u00f6ver Bron|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/sverige/papperslosa-tar-taxi-over-bron/|accessdate=8 January 2016|work=[[Sydsvenskan]]|date=7 January 2016}}</ref> Three days later, a Danish cab driver was arrested for human trafficking near the \u00d8resund Bridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/udland/dansk-taxachauffoer-anholdt-menneskesmugling-til-sverige|title=Dansk taxachauff\u00f8r anholdt for menneskesmugling til Sverige|website=DR}}</ref> In January 2016 newspaper [[Sydsvenskan]] reported that the migration flow had led to an increase of [[MRSA]] infections in southernmost [[Sk\u00e5ne]] province where many migrants are received, from 160 cases in 2005 to more than 635 cases in 2015.<ref name=\"ssd_2Jan2016\">{{cite news|title=Flyktingstr\u00f6m bakom stor \u00f6kning av MRSA |url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/sverige/flyktingstrom-bakom-stor-okning-av-mrsa/ |accessdate=7 February 2016 |newspaper=[[Sydsvenskan]] |date=2 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129114648/http://www.sydsvenskan.se/sverige/flyktingstrom-bakom-stor-okning-av-mrsa/ |archivedate=29 January 2016 }}</ref> In January 2016 interior minister [[Anders Ygeman]] said that Sweden was rejecting about 45 percent of asylum applications, which meant that around 60,000\u201380,000 of the 160,000 asylum-seekers who applied for asylum in 2015 could be deported in coming years.<ref name=\"telegrah_28Jan2016\">{{cite news|title=Sweden and Finland plan to expel up to 100,000 failed asylum seekers|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/sweden/12126599/Sweden-plans-to-expel-up-to-80000-failed-asylum-seekers.html|accessdate=21 February 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sweden to deport up to 80,000 asylum-seekers|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/sweden-to-deport-up-to-80000-asylum-seekers/|agency=Associated Press|date=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] in 2016, an estimated 20 to 30 percent of asylum seekers suffered from [[mental disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialstyrelsen.se/nyheter/2016/detstoraantaletasylsokandeharpaverkatvardochtandvard|title=Det stora antalet asyls\u00f6kande har p\u00e5verkat v\u00e5rd och tandv\u00e5rd |last=|first=|date= |website=socialstyrelsen.se |language=sv|access-date=2017-12-28|quote=Belastningen har ocks\u00e5 \u00f6kat inom psykiatrin, 20\u201330 procent av de asyls\u00f6kande uppskattas vara drabbade av psykisk oh\u00e4lsa.}}</ref>\n\nOf the 162 000 who migrated to Sweden in 2015, by May 2016 only 500 had found employment, where employment constituted more than 1 hour of work per week or state-subsidised schemes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/162-000-kom-till-sverige-500-fick-jobb|title=162.000 kom till Sverige \u2013 500 fick jobb|last=Nyheter|first=SVT|date=2016-05-31|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2018-05-11|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn late June 2016 the [[Riksdag|Swedish parliament]] voted for more restrictive policy with a large majority in favour. As a result, residence permits will be temporary and immigration of family members will be curtailed, along with higher demands of proof to be able to support immigrating relatives. These measures are to be valid for three years.<ref name=\"dn_21June2016\">{{cite news|title=Ny sk\u00e4rpt asyllag klubbad|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/ny-skarpt-asyllag-klubbad/|accessdate=21 June 2016|newspaper=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|date=21 June 2016}}</ref> The law applies retroactively on everyone who arrived 24 November onwards and came into effect 20 July 2016. These measures puts Sweden in line with the minimum line of requirements mandated by the EU.<ref name=\"ssd_20July2016\">{{cite news|title=Sk\u00e4rpt asyllag tr\u00e4der i kraft|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/2016-07-20/skarpt-asyllag-trader-i-kraft|accessdate=20 July 2016|newspaper=[[Sydsvenskan]]|date=20 July 2016}}</ref> Thirty individuals were denied asylum January\u2013June 2016 due to [[war crimes]].<ref name=\"sydsvenskan_5juli2016\"/>\n\nIn August 2016 four workers at asylum centres for refugee children were reported to have been infected by [[tuberculosis]] and health services reported a marked increase in tuberculosis infections due to the crisis.<ref name=\"ssd_18augusti2016\">{{cite news|title=Anst\u00e4llda p\u00e5 flyktingboenden smittade av tuberkulos|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/2016-08-17/anstallda-pa-flyktingboenden-i-malmo-smittade-av-tuberkulos|accessdate=20 August 2016|newspaper=[[Sydsvenskan]]|date=18 August 2016}}</ref> In 2015 an increase of 22 percent on the previous year was noted, this was largely attributed to an increased inflow of migrants over that year.<ref name=\"dn_2016-02-28\">{{cite news|title=Tuberkulos \u00f6kar kraftigt i Sverige|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/tuberkulos-okar-kraftigt-i-sverige/|accessdate=21 August 2016|newspaper=Dagens Nyheter|date=28 February 2016}}</ref> 90 percent of people infected with tuberculosis were born abroad.<ref name=\"dn_2016-02-28\"/>\n\nIn October 2016 a leaked internal memo from the cabinet showed that spending cuts to all public services had become necessary due to the escalating costs of the migration crisis.<ref name=\"svd_25October2016\">{{cite news|title=Internt mejl visar: Nya besparingar kr\u00e4vs|url=http://www.svd.se/internt-mejl-visar-nya-besparingar-kravs/om/flykten-till-europa|accessdate=27 November 2016|newspaper=Svenska Dagbladet|date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 police described gangs of recently arrived youth making the central shopping mall of Gothenburg unsafe at night with muggings and violence over drug trade between gangs of Moroccan, Afghani and Syrian origin. Police work is made difficult by the [[Swedish Migration Agency]] which has neglected to identify arriving migrants leading to an arrested individual's fingerprint matching a handful of identities. When offered help from social services the youth declined and preferred a life on the streets supporting themselves with crime.<ref name=\"expr14jan2017\">{{cite news|title=Brottsplats Nordstan \u2013 s\u00e5 ser vardagen ut|url=http://www.expressen.se/gt/droger-och-valdsbrott--ny-vardag-i-nordstan/|accessdate=18 January 2017|newspaper=Expressen|date=14 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017 border police reported that it had been possible to verify the identities of 77 migrants from [[Morocco]] using fingerprint matches checked against the Moroccan fingerprint database. It was found that out of the 77,   65 had lied about their identity and of the 50 claiming to be underage, all but two were adult.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svd.se/falska-identiteter-vanliga-hos-ensamkommande-fran-marocko|title=Falsk identitet vanligt bland asyls\u00f6kande fr\u00e5n Marocko|last=frida.svensson@svd.se|first=Frida Svensson {{!}}|work=SvD.se|access-date=29 May 2017|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017 the [[Swedish National Board of Forensic Medicine]] started aiding the [[Swedish Migration Agency]] with determining the age of migrants claiming to be under 18. The first batch of 518 investigations indicated that 442 were likely adult. Of the 442, 430 were men and 12 women.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rmv.se/aktuellt/de-forsta-medicinska-aldersbedomningarna-klara/|title=De f\u00f6rsta medicinska \u00e5ldersbed\u00f6mningarna klara \u2013 R\u00e4ttsmedicinalverket|work=R\u00e4ttsmedicinalverket|access-date=31 May 2017|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\nUp until 2017, the [[Swedish Migration Agency]] awarded [[Temporary resident|temporary residence permits]] also to people considered [[War crime|war criminals]] and [[Terrorism|security threats]]. This allowed these individuals to claim [[welfare]] benefits and [[Healthcare in Sweden|healthcare]] from the state of Sweden.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/migrationsverket-4|title=S\u00e5 ska Sverige stoppa misst\u00e4nkta terrorister|last=Nyheter|first=SVT|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=4 July 2017|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Falkenberg]], [[Falkenberg Municipality|the municipality]] created gender segregated housing for [[unaccompanied minor]]s, as the boys would sexually harass the girls and the girls did previously not dare to go out into the communal areas of the accommodations without wearing the veil. With the segregated housing, the girls were able to make better use of the facilities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/halland/uppdelat-boende-ska-starka-ensamkommande-flickor|title=sv: Uppdelat boende ska st\u00e4rka ensamkommande flickor|last=|first=|date=|work=Sydsvenskan|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, the [[Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden]] (HFD) ruled that illegal immigrants, such as those who stay in hiding after their asylum applications had been rejected in order to evade deportation, had no right to welfare benefits. A woman was denied welfare benefits (''sv:socialbidrag'') by the council of [[V\u00e4nn\u00e4s]]<nowiki/> and she took the council to court. The first instance (sv:''f\u00f6rvaltningsr\u00e4tten)'' ruled in the woman's favour, but the council took the case to the highest court HFD which ruled in favour of the council.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dagensjuridik.se/2017/06/papperslosa-som-haller-sig-undan-utvisning-har-inte-ratt-till-bidrag-dom-fran-hfd|title=\"Pappersl\u00f6sa\" som h\u00e5ller sig undan utvisning har inte r\u00e4tt till bidrag \u2013 dom fr\u00e5n HFD|work=Dagens Juridik|access-date=10 November 2017|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017 [[Swedish Radio]] reported that few recently arrived migrants who have low education are willing to improve their schooling; about 3 to 4 percent are taking classes two years after receiving a residence permit. Migrants are not generally aware that in order to find steady employment in the job market of Sweden, completed [[Education in Sweden#Secondary school|secondary education]] is a frequent requirement.<ref name=\"sr19July2017\">{{cite news|title=sv: F\u00e5 l\u00e5gutbildade nyanl\u00e4nda vill studera|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=6738611|accessdate=23 July 2017|publisher=Swedish Radio|date=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 staff at the [[Swedish Migration Agency]] reported rising levels of death threats and harassment from migrants applying for residence. The nature of the threats changed with staff members being sought out at their homes or receiving threatening messages on private phones or in social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/stockholm/anstallda-pa-migrationsverket-hotas-ofta|title=Personal p\u00e5 Migrationsverket uts\u00e4tts f\u00f6r hot under asylprocessen|last=Nyheter|first=SVT|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=13 September 2017|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, [[Swedish Public Employment Service]] statistics showed that of the 24 034 recently arrived migrants in Stockholm, 9 324 were women of whom 3 percent had found non-subsidised employment and 14 710 were men, of whom 7 percent had found non-state-subsidised employment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dn.se/sthlm/mycket-fa-nyanlanda-kvinnor-far-jobb/|title=Mycket f\u00e5 nyanl\u00e4nda kvinnor f\u00e5r jobb \u2013 DN.SE|date=2017-11-08|work=DN.SE|access-date=2018-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323104603/https://www.dn.se/sthlm/mycket-fa-nyanlanda-kvinnor-far-jobb/|archive-date=23 March 2018|url-status=|language=sv-se}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, researcher Pernilla Andersson Joona at Stockholm University found that 50 percent of recently arrived migrants had less than the Swedish 9-year basic education (Swedish: ''grundskolekompetens'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arbetsmarknadsnytt.se/forskare-lattast-fa-nyanlanda-i-arbete-med-subventionerade-anstallningar/|title=Forskare: L\u00e4ttast f\u00e5 nyanl\u00e4nda i arbete med subventionerade anst\u00e4llningar|website=arbetsmarknadsnytt.se|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330161753/http://arbetsmarknadsnytt.se/forskare-lattast-fa-nyanlanda-i-arbete-med-subventionerade-anstallningar/|archive-date=30 March 2018|url-status=|access-date=2018-03-31}}</ref>\n\n===Switzerland===\n{{flagu|Sweden}} \u2013 As of 26 November, Sweden had received 146,000 asylum seekers in 2015, with a record of 39,000 applications in October. Most asylum seekers were Afghan, followed by Syrians and Iraqis.<ref name=dn1>[http://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/manga-flyktingar-soker-sig-till-sverige-trots-nya-atgarder/ M\u00e5nga flyktingar s\u00f6ker sig till Sverige \u2013 trots nya \u00e5tg\u00e4rder] {{in lang|sv}} Dagens Nyheter, 27 October 2015</ref> In the beginning of November, the authorities warned they could no longer offer housing to all asylum seekers and on 12 November temporary border control was enacted (on the Swedish side) which reduced the number of migrants somewhat (migrants could still apply for asylum).<ref name=dn1/> On 26 November 2015, Prime Minister [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]] said the system for welcoming migrants was about to collapse and that the cabinet would propose major new restrictions and measures to reduce the inflow of migrants. He called on other European countries to take more responsibility.<ref>David Crouch (24 November 2015) [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/24/sweden-asylum-seekers-refugees-policy-reversal Sweden slams shut its open-door policy towards refugees] ''The Guardian''.</ref> The government in December decided to introduce \"carrier's responsibility\" for trains and buses on the [[\u00d6resund bridge]] which would introduce Swedish de facto border controls on the Danish side.<ref>[http://www.regeringen.serattsdokument/proposition/2015/12/prop.-20151667/ S\u00e4rskilda \u00e5tg\u00e4rder vid allvarlig fara f\u00f6r den allm\u00e4nna ordningen eller den inre s\u00e4kerheten i landet]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (Swedish)</ref>\n\nIn 2016, there were reports that multiple [[We Are Sthlm sexual assaults|sexual harassment incidents]] had been reported at the [[We Are Sthlm]] festival over the course of several years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Swedish police probe 'cover-up of migrant sex assaults'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-35285086|work=BBC News|date=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a non-EU member country but full participant in the [[Schengen Agreement]], the [[Swiss Confederation]] was directly affected by the migrant crisis with most of the refugees arriving from [[Italy]] at border crossings in the Southern cantons of [[Ticino]] and [[Valais]]. In the crisis year 2015, almost 40,000 asylum seekers were applying for refugee status. In 2016, this number dropped by 31 percent, and in the first quarter of 2017 by another 57 percent, compared to the same time period in 2016. Most of the asylum seekers arriving in Switzerland originate from [[Eritrea]] (49 percent), followed by [[Afghanistan]] (30 percent) and [[Syria]]. Despite relative restrictive admission policies, and increased patrolling of illegal border crossings, the Swiss have attempted to admit refugees throughout the course of the migrant crisis, and distributed those asylum seekers to the appropriate cantons and city states.\n\nRefugees first receive a temporary residence permit \"N\" valid for 6 months while they await approval of their status. Asylum seekers who are not admitted but cannot return to their home country because of health or safety considerations receive a residence permit \"F\" that allows them to stay in Switzerland. Persons receiving a \"B\" permit are admitted refugees according to the [[Geneva Convention]] with a full residence allowance for 12 months and possible extensions. Almost 50 percent of the asylum seekers receive residence permits or are allowed to stay, and about 10 percent of those rejected can be placed in another Schengen country.\n\nWith 3.4 asylum seekers per 1000 inhabitants in 2016, Switzerland processed more asylum applications than the European average at 2.5, Germany at the top of the list with almost 10 asylum seekers/1000. About 2.5 percent of asylum seekers in Switzerland are employed; the numbers are higher at 30 percent for those with temporary permits and at 24 percent for admitted refugees.<ref>Serm\u00een Faki, Priska Wallimann (April 2017). [http://www.blick.ch/news/politik/blick-erklaert-asylland-schweiz-in-zahlen-id6551880.html \"Asylland Schweiz in Zahlen\"](in German). Blick News Politik. Retrieved 21 April 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, 85.8 percent of refugees in Switzerland received [[welfare]] payments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.srf.ch/news/schweiz/neue-sozialhilfestatistik-80-prozent-der-asylbewerber-und-fluechtlinge-beziehen-sozialhilfe|title=SRF News: Neue Sozialhilfestatistik \u2013 80 Prozent der Asylbewerber und Fl\u00fcchtlinge beziehen Sozialhilfe|last=hesa|first=SRF 4 News 11:00 Uhr/sda/bfs/schubeca/kurn|work=Schweizer Radio und Fernsehen (SRF)|access-date=2017-12-25|language=de-CH}}</ref>\n\n=== Portugal ===\n{{flagu|Portugal}} \u2013 In the next two years, Portugal is willing to offer shelter to 1,500 of the refugees flooding into Europe from the Mediterranean Sea. A source has told Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias that the Ministry of Foreign Affairs has already presented its counter-proposal to the European Commission (EC), which wanted Portugal to absorb 2,400 refugees.<ref>{{cite web |title=Portugal prepares for migrants |url=http://theportugalnews.com/news/portugal-prepares-for-migrants/35809 |publisher=theportugalnews.com |accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref>\n=== Romania ===\n{{flagu|Romania}} \u2013 The [[European Commission]] asked Romania to accept 6,351 refugees under an EU quota scheme. The EurActiv reported that \"Romanian Prime Minister [[Victor Ponta]] said that his country will request admission to the EU's [[Schengen Area|Schengen borderless area]] if mandatory quotas to accept refugees are decided by the Union\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/justice-home-affairs/romania-accept-refugees-if-admitted-schengen-317426 | title=Romania to accept refugees if admitted to Schengen |publisher=EurActiv |date=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n===UK===\n{{flagu|United Kingdom}} \u2013 British Home Secretary [[Theresa May]] said that it was important to help people living in war zone regions and refugee camps, \"not the ones who are strong and rich enough to come to Europe\".<ref>\"[http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/refugee-policy-of-chancellor-merkel-divides-europe-a-1053603.html Mother Angela: Merkel's Refugee Policy Divides Europe]\". ''[[Der Spiegel]].'' 21 September 2015.</ref> British [[UKIP]] politician [[Nigel Farage]] stated that the exodus from Libya had been caused by [[2011 military intervention in Libya|NATO military intervention]], approved by [[David Cameron]] and [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], in the [[Libyan Crisis (2011\u2013present)|civil war in Libya]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nigel-farage/11548171/Nigel-Farage-David-Cameron-directly-caused-Libyan-migrant-crisis.html |title=Nigel Farage: David Cameron 'directly caused' Libyan migrant crisis |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 April 2015 |author=Holehouse, Matthew |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\n{{flagu|Poland}} \u2013 In 2015, just before the [[2015 Polish parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] that were to happen that year, government officials with then Prime Minister [[Ewa Kopacz]] stated that the country was ready to take 2,000 refugees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://msw.gov.pl/en/news/909,Preparations-for-taking-2000-refugees.html |title=Preparations for taking 2,000 refugees |author=JSK Internet |work=Ministry of the Interior}}</ref> \nHowever, after the [[Law and Justice]] party won the elections, the rhetoric was changed. Both the government of Poland and \nPresident [[Andrzej Duda]] rejected the European Union's proposal of compulsory migrant quotas, the latter stating: \"I won't agree to a dictate of the strong. I won't back a Europe where the economic advantage of the size of a population will be a reason to force solutions on other countries regardless of their national interests\".<ref>\"[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-08/polish-president-blasts-eu-dictate-of-the-strong-on-migrants Poland's Duda Blasts EU `Dictate of the Strong' on Migrants]\". Bloomberg. 8 September 2015.</ref>\n\n\n==Statistics==\n{{image frame|content={{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Total EU arrivals 2014-2016 (June).png{{!}}Total monthly Mediterranean Sea arrivals in the EU, 2014\u20132016, according to UNHCR's data\n| photo2a= Refugee crisis in Europe Q1-Q4 2015.svg{{!}}Asylum applicants in EU and EFTA states, January\u2013December 2015. The height of the bars indicate the number of asylum applicants per country. Colours indicate the percentage of asylum applicants in relation to the population.\n| photo3a= UNHCR2.png{{!}}Refugee and migrant deaths in the Mediterranean Sea, 2011\u20132016, according to the UNHCR\n| size = 270\n| spacing = 1\n| color = #FFFFFF\n| border = 3\n| color_border = gray\n| text = Mediterranean Sea Arrivals<ref name=\"UNHCRarrivals\">{{cite web|title=Refugees/Migrants Emergency Response \u2013 Mediterranean|url=http://data.unhcr.org/mediterranean/regional.php|publisher=UNHCR}}</ref>]]\nAsylum applicants in EU and EFTA states in 2015, Deaths in the Mediterranean Sea<ref name=\"UNHCRarrivals\"/>\n| text_background = #FFDEAD\n}}\n| width = 278\n}}\n===Arrivals===\n====2014====\nAccording to the [[International Organization for Migration]] (IOM), up to 3,072 people died or disappeared in 2014 in the Mediterranean while trying to migrate to Europe.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/04/15/migrant-boat-capsizes-off-libya-400-feared-dead/ |title=Migrant boat capsizes off Libya, 400 feared dead |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=19 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930071234/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/04/15/migrant-boat-capsizes-off-libya-400-feared-dead/ |archive-date=30 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Overall estimates are that over 22,000 migrants died between 2000 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=IOM Releases New Data on Migrant Fatalities Worldwide: Almost 40,000 Since 2000|url=https://www.iom.int/statements/iom-releases-new-data-migrant-fatalities-worldwide-almost-40000-2000|website=IOM \u2013 International Organization for Migration|publisher=International Organization for Migration|accessdate=15 June 2017|date=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Brian|first1=Tara|last2=Laczko|first2=Frank|title=Fatal Journeys. Tracking Lives Lost during Migration|url=https://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/fataljourneys_countingtheuncounted.pdf|website=IOM online bookstore|publisher=IOM \u2013 International Organization for Migration|accessdate=15 June 2017|page=12|date=2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, circa [[#Migrant arrivals versus \"illegal\" border crossings|252,000 new migrants]] arrived \"irregularly\" in the European Union, often coming from Syria, Somalia or Eritrea, often having travelled oversea from Libya.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> 220,194 migrants crossed EU sea borders in the Central, Eastern and Western Mediterranean (a 266 percent increase compared to 2013). Half of them had come from Syria, Eritrea and Afghanistan.<ref name=\"FrontexARA2015\">{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2015.pdf#page=59 |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2015 |page=57 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=27 April 2015}}</ref> \n\nOf those arriving in Southern Europe in 2014, the vast majority (170,664, a 277 percent increase compared to 2013) arrived in Italy through Libya, whereas a minority (50,834, a 105 percent increase) arrived in Greece through Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annual_Risk_Analysis_2015.pdf#page=21 |title=Annual Risk Analysis 2015 |page=59 |publisher=[[Frontex]] |date=27 April 2015}}</ref> 62,000 applied for [[Right of asylum|asylum]] in Italy, but most Syrians and Eritreans, who comprised almost half of the arrivals in Italy in 2014, did not stop in Italy but instead continued moving towards northern Europe, in particular Germany and Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/5592bd059.html#14 |title=The sea route to Europe: The Mediterranean passage in the age of refugees |page=14 |publisher=[[UNHCR]]}}</ref>\n\n====2015====\n[[File:Number of migrants in Hungary per week.pdf|thumb|Number of migrants in Hungary per week, May\u2013September 2015]]\n[[International Organization for Migration|IOM]] and [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]] estimated that 1,005,504 migrants and refugees arrived in Europe from 1 January to 21 December 2015, three to four times more than in 2014.<ref name=\"Miles One Million 2015\">{{cite news | last=Miles | first=Tom | title=EU gets one million migrants in 2015, smugglers seen making $1 billion | agency=Reuters | date=22 December 2015 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-idUSKBN0U50WI20151222 | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Just 3 percent (34,215) came by land to Bulgaria and Greece; the rest came by sea to Greece, Italy, Spain, Cyprus and Malta. The vast majority arrived by sea in Greece (816,752); 150,317 arrived by sea in Italy, with a slight drop from 170,000 in 2014. Half of those crossing the Mediterranean were from Syria, 20 percent were from Afghanistan and 7 percent from Iraq. IOM estimated that a total of 3,692 migrants and refugees lost their lives in the Mediterranean in 2015 \u2013 over 400 more than in 2014 \u2013 of whom 2,889 in the Central Mediterranean and 731 in the Aegean sea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irregular Migrant, Refugee Arrivals in Europe Top One Million in 2015: IOM |url=https://www.iom.int/news/irregular-migrant-refugee-arrivals-europe-top-one-million-2015-iom|publisher=IOM|date=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A million refugees and migrants flee to Europe in 2015|url=http://www.unhcr.org/567918556.html|work=UNHCR|date=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a shift took place, with Greece overtaking Italy as the primary point of arrival and surpassing in the first six months of 2015 the numbers for the whole of 2014: 67,500 people arrived in Italy, mainly coming from [[Eritrea]] (25 percent), [[Nigeria]] (10 percent) and [[Somalia]] (10 percent), whereas 68,000 arrived on the islands of Greece, mainly coming from [[Syria]] (57 percent) and [[Afghanistan]] (22 percent).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/5592bd059.html#11 |title=The sea route to Europe: The Mediterranean passage in the age of refugees |page=11 |publisher=[[UNHCR]]}}</ref> In total, 137,000 migrants crossed the Mediterranean into Europe in the first six months of 2015.<ref name=MediterraneanCrisis2015>{{cite news |title=Mediterranean Crisis 2015 at six months: refugee and migrant numbers highest on record |url=http://www.unhcr.org/5592b9b36.html |accessdate=14 August 2015 |publisher=UNHCR |date=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1 January to 17 April 2015, 21,191 migrants reached the Italian coast, with a decrease during the month of March due to bad weather conditions, and a surge since 10 April, bringing the number of arrivals in line with the number recorded in the same period in 2014. However, the death toll in the first four months of 2014 was 96, compared with 500 in the same period in 2015; this number excluded the victims of the [[April 2015 Libya migrant shipwrecks|shipwrecks on 13 and 19 April]].<ref>{{cite news |title=IOM Applauds Italy's Weekend Rescue at Sea of 2,800 Migrants |url=http://www.iom.int/cms/en/sites/iom/home/news-and-views/press-briefing-notes/pbn-2015/pbn-listing/iom-applauds-italys-weekend-resc.html |publisher=International Organization for Migration |date=13 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Migrant Deaths Soar in Mediterranean |url=http://www.iom.int/cms/en/sites/iom/home/news-and-views/press-briefing-notes/pbn-2015/pbn-listing/migrant-deaths-soar-in-mediterra.html |publisher=International Organization for Migration |date=17 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cameron|first=Bobby Thomas|date=2015|title=Migration in the Mediterranean Region and Policy Implications|url=https://thercs.org/blogsnews-and-blognews-and-blog/news-and-blog/migration-in-the-mediterranean-region-and-policy-implications/|journal=Commonwealth Voices|publisher=Royal Commonwealth Society|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn early August 2015, the UNHCR said that 250,000 migrants had arrived in Europe by sea so far in 2015, 124,000 in Greece and 98,000 in Italy.<ref name=BBCnavyrescues>{{cite news |title=European migrant crisis: Italy navy rescues 50 from dinghy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33882177 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=12 August 2015}}</ref> According to [[Frontex]], July set a new record for a single month, with 107,500 migrants estimated to have entered the EU.<ref name=JulySetsRecord>{{cite news |title=European Union border agency: Number of migrants entering EU hits new monthly record in July |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/08/18/european-union-border-agency-number-migrants-entering-eu-hits-new-monthly/ |accessdate=18 August 2015 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=18 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925110912/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/08/18/european-union-border-agency-number-migrants-entering-eu-hits-new-monthly/ |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nFrontex detected 615,492 illegal EU-border-crossings in the third quarter of 2015 and 978,338 in the fourth quarter,<ref>{{cite web|title=FRAN Quarterly \u2013 Quarter 4 (2015)|url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/FRAN_Q4_2015.pdf|publisher=Frontex}}</ref> bringing the number of detections of illegal EU-border-crossings in 2015 to 1.82 million (872,938 in Greece, 764,038 in Hungary and Croatia and 153,946 in Italy). However, there were in 2015 only an estimated one million ''individuals'' irregularly entering the EU: most migrants following the Western Balkan route were double-counted as 'illegally crossing an EU border', first when arriving in Greece, and again when entering the EU for the second time through Hungary or Croatia.<ref name=\"Frontex2016\">{{cite web|title=Risk analysis for 2016|url=http://frontex.europa.eu/assets/Publications/Risk_Analysis/Annula_Risk_Analysis_2016.pdf|publisher=Frontex}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\nIn January and February 2016, over 123,000 migrants landed in Greece, compared to about 4,600 in the same period of 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/03/11/world/europe/europe-tries-to-shut-down-routes-as-migrant-flow-intensifies.html|title=Europe Tries to Shut Down Routes as Migrant Flow Intensifies|author1=LARRY BUCHANAN |author2=SERGIO PE\u00c7ANHA |newspaper=The New York Times|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref> In March, following the closing of the Western Balkan route by North Macedonia and the entry into force of the EU\u2013Turkey deal on 20 March, the number of migrants arriving in Greece dropped to 26,460, less than half the figure recorded in February. Syrians, Afghans and Iraqis continued to account for the largest share of the migrants arriving in Greece.<ref name=\"FrontexMarch2016\">{{cite news|title=Number of migrants arriving in Greece dropped in March|url=http://frontex.europa.eu/news/number-of-migrants-arriving-in-greece-dropped-in-march-aInDt3|work=Frontex|date=18 April 2016}}</ref> This downward trend continued in April, when only 2,700 migrants arrived in Greece, decreasing by 90 percent compared to the previous month.<ref name=\"FrontexApril2016\">{{cite news|title=Number of migrants arriving in Greece dropped 90 per cent in April|url=http://frontex.europa.eu/news/number-of-migrants-arriving-in-greece-dropped-90-in-april-6e7oBw|work=Frontex|date=13 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, due to improved weather conditions, the number of mainly African migrants [[Immigration to Italy|crossing the sea to Italy]] doubled between February and March, reaching nearly 9,600 in March 2016, compared to 2,283 in March 2015.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://migration.iom.int/docs/Q3_Overview_Arrivals_to_Europe.pdf|title=Migration Flows to Europe \u2013 Quarterly Overview|last=|first=|date=October 2017|publisher=International Organisation of Migration|access-date=4 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FrontexMarch2016\"/> In April, on the contrary, the number of migrants arriving in Italy (8,370) dropped by 13 percent compared to the previous month and by 50 percent compared to the same month in 2015; despite this, Italy exceeded the totals for Greece for the first time since June 2015.<ref name=\"FrontexApril2016\"/> On 16 April, a [[List of migrant vessel incidents on the Mediterranean Sea|shipwreck]] of a large boat between Libya and Italy was reported, in which as many as 500 people may have died, in one of the worst disasters since April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Massive loss of life reported in latest Mediterranean tragedy|url=http://www.unhcr.org/57178bcf6.html|publisher=UNHCR|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe mass influx of migrants into Europe was not seen favorably in many European Union countries. Many citizens disapproved of the EU's handling of the migrant crisis, with 94 percent of Greeks and 88 percent of Swedes disapproving of the measures taken, among other countries with similar disapproval rates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2016/06/07/euroskepticism-beyond-brexit/pm_2016-06-07_brexit-03/|title=Overwhelming majorities unhappy with EU's handling of refugees|date=6 June 2016}}</ref> This contributed to the creation and implementation of the [[European Union\u2013Turkey relations#EU-Turkey deal on migrant crisis|EU\u2013Turkey Refugee Agreement]], which was signed in March 2016. From that point on, the numbers of refugees entering Greece decreased. In February 2016, the last full month before the deal, 57,066 migrants arrived in Greece via the sea; from that point on, discounting March, the highest number of migrants reaching Greece via the sea was 3,650 (in April).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.unhcr.org/mediterranean/country.php?id=83|title=UNHCR Refugees/Migrants Response \u2013 Mediterranean|first=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|last=(UNHCR)}}</ref> While there is no direct connection to the implementation of the EU\u2013Turkey deal, the number of migrants arriving in Italy in that same time period has increased. From March 2016 to October 2016, 140,358 migrants arrived in Italy via the sea, averaging to 20,051 per month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.unhcr.org/mediterranean/country.php?id=105|title=UNHCR Refugees/Migrants Response \u2013 Mediterranean|first=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|last=(UNHCR)}}</ref> Overall the number of migrants arriving into the EU dropped, but the EU still worked to create agencies and plans to mitigate the crisis. In addition to the EU\u2013Turkey Refugee Agreement, the European Border and Coast Guard Agency was launched on 6 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frontex.europa.eu/news/european-border-and-coast-guard-agency-launches-today-CHIYAp|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20171009193452/http://frontex.europa.eu/news/european-border-and-coast-guard-agency-launches-today-CHIYAp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-10-09|title=Frontex \u2013 News \u2013 European Border and Coast Guard Agency launches today}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\nData released by the International Organization of Migration (IOM) for the third quarter of 2017 recorded 146,287 total arrivals to Europe, of which 137,771 were by sea. This is less than half the total recorded by the end of September 2016. The greatest decrease in influx was noted on the Eastern Mediterranean route. Despite an 86 percent drop in the number of migrant and refugee arrivals in September 2017 when compared to September 2016, Greece has observed a steady increase in the number of migrants from September 2016 till date. Further, while Italy also noted lower number of migrant arrival in 2017, there was a significant jump in the number of migrants reaching Spain, with over 16,000 having arrived in the country. Like Spain, the island-nation of Cyprus registered approximately an 8-fold increase in the number of migrants arriving last year and this year.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/pdfscache/13562.pdf|title=Asylum Quarterly Report \u2013 explained|last=|first=|date=|website=EC Europa|access-date=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nClosure of segments of certain heavy-traffic routes such as the Central and Eastern Mediterranean is responsible for the marked decrease in the number of migrants from the Middle East in 2017. However, the Western Mediterranean route is still in full use to facilitate the growing number of illegal immigrants from Africa. Nigerians topped the list of illegal immigrants into Italy in 2017, forming 16 percent of arrivals there.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn February 2017 [[Italian government]] accepted to fund Libyan coastguard. Since then many migrants were forced to go back to Libya.<ref name=\"auto12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/migrants-deaths-in-mediterranean-reach-record-percentage-1.3652139|title=Migrants deaths in Mediterranean reach record percentage|first=Sally|last=Hayden|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, approximately 825,000 persons acquired citizenship of a member state of the European Union, down from 995,000 in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquisition of citizenship in the EU \u2013 EU Member States granted citizenship to over 800 thousand persons in 2017 \u2013 Moroccans, Albanians and Indians were the main recipients |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STAT-19-1550_en.htm |website=europa.eu |publisher=European Commission}}</ref> The largest groups were nationals of Morocco, Albania, India, Turkey and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Acquisition of citizenship statistics |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Acquisition_of_citizenship_statistics |website=ec.europa.eu |publisher=Eurostat}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\nOn 7 October 2018 at least 10 migrants are believed to have died in a boat off the coast of [[Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/video/migrants-in-mediterranean-sea-face-rescue-delays-1312356931718|title='The potential for loss of life is a lot higher now' in Mediterranean Sea|website=NBC News}}</ref> Helena Maleno founder of the group Walking Borders told the reporters the migrants constantly appealed for help from [[Spain]] and Morocco before they died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/dozens-migrants-feared-dead-mediterranean-sea-morocco-n916121|title=Dozens of migrants feared dead after waiting 36 hours for rescue|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n====2019====\nIn August 2019, more than 270 Europe-bound migrants were rescued by the Libyan coastguard from Tripoli's Mediterranean coast; they were travelling in four different boats, and included 18 women and two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.660citynews.com/2019/08/17/libya-intercepts-boats-with-over-270-europe-bound-migrants/|title=Libya intercepts boats with over 270 Europe-bound migrants|accessdate=17 August 2019|website=660 News}}</ref> According to a UN report, more than 45,000 migrants had reached Europe by sea by August, of whom 859 had reportedly died on the way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://haberlutfen.com/un-45000-refugees-enter-europe-in-2019/|title=UN: 45,000+ refugees enter Europe in 2019|accessdate=23 August 2019|website=haberlutfen}}</ref> In September 2019, Libya's coastguard intercepted another 108 Europe-bound migrants of the Mediterranean coast; 13 were women, and seven children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymotherlode.com/news/middle-east/839021/libyas-coast-guard-intercepts-108-europe-bound-migrants.html|title=Libya's coast guard intercepts 108 Europe-bound migrants|accessdate=3 September 2019|website=My Mother Lode}}</ref> On 8 October, Italian authorities rescued 22 Europe-bound migrants from a boat carrying about 50 people. At the time of this rescue, the bodies of 13 women were also reportedly found, and it later emerged that others were still missing. On 16 October, Italian authorities found the bodies of at least 12 people who had died in the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twnews.co.uk/gb-news/bodies-of-migrants-who-died-at-sea-located-by-italian-authorities|title=Bodies of migrants who died at sea located by Italian authorities|accessdate=16 October 2019|website=The World News}}</ref> In November, Italian coast guards rescued 149 Europe-bound migrants after their boat capsized. Italian coastguards later found five dead bodies and confirmed that the death toll from the incident was at least 18.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.heraldonline.com/news/nation-world/world/article237939289.html|title=Italy recovers 5 more bodies from sunken migrant boat |accessdate=1 December 2019|website=The Herald}}</ref>\n\n===Asylum applications===\n\n{|  class=\"wikitable toptextcells\"\n|+Extra EU 28 Asylum applicants by year\n|-\n| {{Graph:Chart\n|legend=Asylum applicants by year\n|type=rect\n|width=650\n|x=1998,1999,2000,2001,2002,2003,2004,2005,2006,2007,\n2008,2009,2010,2011,2012,2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019\n|y1=313645, 380450 ,406585 ,424180 ,421470 ,344800 ,276675 ,234675 ,197410,222635\n|y2=,,,,,,,,,,\n225150 ,263835 ,259400 ,309045 ,335290 ,431100 ,626965 ,1322850 ,1260920, 712250, 647170, 721090\n|y1Title=EU27\n|y2Title=EU28\n|showValues=\n}}\n|-\n| Source Eurostat: EU 27;<ref>http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=migr_asyctz&lang=en</ref> EU28.<ref>http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=migr_asyappctza&lang=en</ref>\n|-\n|+Extra EU 28 Asylum applicants by year and sex\n|-\n| {{Graph:Chart\n|legend=Asylum applicants by sex\n|type=stackedrect\n|width=650\n|x=2008,2009,2010,2011,2012,2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019\n|y1=160420 ,178230 ,169765 ,211880 ,220275 ,283225 ,440705 ,954095 ,852405, 476805, 414450, 455755\n|y2=64635 ,85455 ,89475 ,97045 ,114925,141900 ,186080 ,367460 ,406570, 235200, 232540, 265130\n|y3=100 ,145 ,155 ,135 ,90 ,90 ,175 ,1070, 1950, 245, 185, 205\n|y1Title=Men\n|y2Title=Women\n|y3Title=Sex unknown\n}}\n|-\n| Source Eurostat<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/submitViewTableAction.do |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416165655/http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/submitViewTableAction.do |archive-date=16 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{,}}<ref>http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?query=BOOKMARK_DS-057066_QID_-3AC69FCF_UID_-3F171EB0&layout=TIME,C,X,0;SEX,L,Y,0;CITIZEN,L,Z,0;GEO,L,Z,1;AGE,L,Z,2;ASYL_APP,L,Z,3;UNIT,L,Z,4;INDICATORS,C,Z,5;&zSelection=DS-057066CITIZEN,EXT_EU28;DS-057066UNIT,PER;DS-057066ASYL_APP,ASY_APP;DS-057066INDICATORS,OBS_FLAG;DS-057066GEO,EU28;DS-057066AGE,TOTAL;&rankName1=UNIT_1_2_-1_2&rankName2=AGE_1_2_-1_2&rankName3=CITIZEN_1_2_-1_2&rankName4=INDICATORS_1_2_-1_2&rankName5=ASYL-APP_1_2_-1_2&rankName6=GEO_1_2_0_1&rankName7=TIME_1_0_0_0&rankName8=SEX_1_2_0_1&sortC=ASC_-1_FIRST&rStp=&cStp=&rDCh=&cDCh=&rDM=true&cDM=true&footnes=false&empty=false&wai=false&time_mode=NONE&time_most_recent=false&lang=EN&cfo=%23%23%23%2C%23%23%23.%23%23%23</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable toptextcells sortable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+Number of extra EU 28 asylum applicants<ref>Eurostat, [http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/en/web/products-datasets/-/MIGR_ASYAPPCTZA Asylum and first time asylum applicants by citizenship, age and sex Annual aggregated data (rounded)], Last update: 18/02/20</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"| Year!!2008!!2009!!2010!!2011!!2012!!2013!!2014!!2015!!2016!!2017\n!2018\n|- style=\"background:wheat;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|EU28||225,150||263,835||259,400||309,040||335,290||431,090||626,960||1,322,825||1,259,955||712,235\n|647,165\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Germany||26,845||32,910||48,475||53,235||77,485||126,705||202,645||476,510||745,155||222,560\n|184,180\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |France||41,840||47,620||52,725||57,330||61,440||66,265||64,310||76,165||84,270||99,330\n|120,425\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Greece||19,885||15,925||10,275||9,310||9,575||8,225||9,430||13,205||51,110||58,650\n|66,965\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Italy||30,140||17,640||10,000||40,315||17,335||26,620||64,625||83,540||122,960||128,850\n|59,950\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Spain||4,515||3,005||2,740||3,420||2,565||4,485||5,615||14,780||15,755||36,605\n|54,050\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |United Kingdom||-||31,665||24,335||26,915||28,800||30,585||32,785||40,160||38,785||34,780\n|38,840\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Netherlands||15,250||16,135||15,100||14,590||13,095||13,060||24,495||44,970||20,945||18,210\n|24,025\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Belgium||15,165||21,615||26,080||31,910||28,075||21,030||22,710||44,660||18,280||18,340\n|22,530\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Sweden||24,785||24,175||31,850||29,650||43,855||54,270||81,180||162,450||28,790||26,325\n|21,560\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Switzerland||16,520||15,900||15,425||23,615||28,400||21,305||23,555||39,445||27,140||18,015\n|15,160\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Austria||12,715||15,780||11,045||14,420||17,415||17,500||28,035||88,160||42,255||24,715\n|13,710\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Cyprus||3,920||3,200||2,875||1,770||1,635||1,255||1,745||2,265||2,940||4,600\n|7,765\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Finland||3,670||4,910||3,085||2,915||3,095||3,210||3,620||32,345||5,605||4,990\n|4,500\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Poland||8,515||10,590||6,540||6,885||10,750||15,240||8,020||12,190||12,305||5,045\n|4,110\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Ireland||3,855||2,680||1,935||1,290||955||945||1,450||3,275||2,245||2,930\n|3,670\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Denmark||2,350||3,720||5,065||3,945||6,045||7,170||14,680||20,935||6,180||3,220\n|3,570\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Slovenia||255||190||240||355||295||270||385||275||1,310||1,475\n|2,875\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Norway||14,395||17,125||10,015||8,990||9,675||11,930||11,415||31,110||3,485||3,520\n|2,660\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Bulgaria||745||855||1,025||890||1,385||7,145||11,080||20,365||19,420||3,695\n|2,535\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Luxembourg||455||480||780||2,150||2,050||1,070||1,150||2,505||2,160||2,430\n|2,335\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Romania||1,175||960||885||1,720||2,510||1,495||1,545||1,260||1,880||4,815\n|2,135\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Malta||2,605||2,385||175||1,890||2,080||2,245||1,350||1,845||1,930||1,840\n|2,130\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Czech Republic||1,645||1,235||775||750||740||695||1,145||1,515||1,475||1,445\n|1,690\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Portugal||160||140||155||275||295||500||440||895||1,460||1,750\n|1,285\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Croatia||-||-||-||-||-||1,075||450||210||2,225||975\n|800\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Iceland||70||35||40||75||115||125||170||345||1,125||1,085\n|775\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Hungary||3,175||4,665||2,095||1,690||2,155||18,895||42,775||177,135||29,430||3,390\n|670\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Lithuania||520||450||495||525||645||400||440||315||430||545\n|405\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Latvia||55||60||65||340||205||195||375||330||350||355\n|185\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Slovakia||895||805||540||490||730||440||330||330||145||160\n|175\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Liechtenstein||20||280||105||75||70||55||65||150||80||150\n|165\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |Estonia||15||40||35||65||75||95||155||230||175||190\n|95\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#eee;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|Total||256,155||297,175||284,985||341,795||373,550||464,505||662,165||1,393,875||1,291,785||735,005\n|669,025\n|}\n\n====2014====\nAccording to [[Eurostat]], [[Member state of the European Union|EU member states]] received 626,065 asylum applications in 2014, the highest number since the 672,000 applications received in 1992. The main countries of origin of asylum seekers, accounting for almost half of the total, were [[Syria]] (20 percent), [[Afghanistan]] (7 percent), [[Kosovo]] (6 percent), [[Eritrea]] (6 percent) and [[Albania]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The number of asylum applicants in the EU jumped to more than 625 000 in 2014|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/6751779/3-20032015-BP-EN.pdf/35e04263-2db5-4e75-b3d3-6b086b23ef2b|publisher=EUROSTAT}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, decisions on asylum applications in the EU made at the first instance resulted in more than 160,000 asylum seekers being granted protection status, while a further 23,000 received protection status on appeal. The rate of recognition of asylum applicants was 45 percent at the first instance and 18 percent on appeal. The main beneficiaries of protection status, accounting for more than half of the total, were Syrians (68,300 or 37 percent), Eritreans (14,600 or 8 percent) and Afghans (14,100 or 8 percent).<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |title=EU Member States granted protection to more than 185 000 asylum seekers in 2014 |url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/6827382/3-12052015-AP-EN.pdf/6733f080-c072-4bf5-91fc-f591abf28176 |publisher=EUROSTAT}}</ref>\n\nFour states \u2013 Germany, Sweden, Italy and France \u2013 received around two-thirds of the EU's asylum applications and granted almost two-thirds of protection status in 2014. Sweden, Hungary and Austria were among the top recipients of EU asylum applications ''per capita'', when adjusted for their own populations, with 8.4 asylum seekers per 1,000 inhabitants in Sweden, 4.3 in Hungary and 3.2 in Austria.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web |url=http://m.euronews.com/en/304485/ |title=euronews \u2013 Data raises questions over EU's attitude towards asylum seekers |publisher=euronews.com |accessdate=28 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328233348/http://m.euronews.com/en/304485/ |archive-date=28 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/08/28/world/europe/countries-under-strain-from-european-migration-crisis.html|title=Which Countries Are Under the Most Strain in the European Migration Crisis? |newspaper=The New York Times |date=28 August 2015 |accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Asylum in the EU |url=http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/home-affairs/e-library/docs/infographics/asylum/infographic_asylum_en.pdf |publisher=European Commission}}</ref>\n\n====2015====\nIn 2015, EU member states received 1,255,640 first time asylum applications, a number more than double that of the previous year. The highest number of first time applicants was registered in Germany (with 441,800 applicants, or 35 percent of all applicants in EU states), followed by Hungary (174,400 or 14 percent), Sweden (156,100 or 12 percent), Austria (85,500 or 7 percent), Italy (83,200 or 7 percent) and France (70,600 or 6 percent). Compared with the population, the highest number was registered in Hungary (with 17.7 asylum seekers per 1,000 inhabitants), Sweden (16), Austria (10), Finland (5.9) and Germany (5.4). The three main countries of citizenship of asylum applicants, accounting for more than half of the total, were Syria (362,800 or 29 percent), Afghanistan (178,200 or 14 percent) and Iraq (121,500 or 10 percent), followed by Kosovo (5 percent), Albania (5 percent), Pakistan (4 percent), Eritrea (3 percent), Nigeria (2 percent) and Iran (2 percent).<ref name=\"asylum2015\">{{cite web|title=Record number of over 1.2 million first time asylum seekers registered in 2015|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/7203832/3-04032016-AP-EN.pdf/790eba01-381c-4163-bcd2-a54959b99ed6|publisher=EUROSTAT}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Top recipients of asylum applications in the EU-28 (2015).png|left|thumb|upright=1.364|Number of first time asylum applications received by the top ten recipients in the EU-28, January\u2013December 2015. The top ten recipients account for more than 90 percent of the asylum applications received in the EU-28.<ref>{{cite web|title=Asylum and first time asylum applicants by citizenship, age and sex Monthly data (rounded)|url=http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=migr_asyappctzm|publisher=Eurostat}}</ref>]]\n333,350 asylum applicants were granted protection in the EU in 2015 following a positive decision on their asylum application. The main beneficiaries of protection status were citizens of Syria (50 percent of persons granted protection in the EU), Eritrea (8 percent), Iraq (7 percent), Afghanistan (5 percent), Iran (2 percent), Somalia (2 percent) and Pakistan (2 percent). The EU countries who granted protection to the highest number of asylum seekers were Germany (who granted protection to 148,200 people), Sweden (34,500), Italy (29,600) and France (26,000). The rate of recognition, i.e. the share of positive decisions in the total number of decisions, was 52 percent for first instance decisions in the EU and 14 percent for decisions on appeal. The citizenships with the highest recognition rates at first instance were Syria (97.2 percent), Eritrea (89.8 percent), Iraq (85.7 percent), Afghanistan (67 percent), Iran (64.7 percent), Somalia (63.1 percent) and Sudan (56 percent).<ref>{{cite news|title=EU Member States granted protection to more than 330 000 asylum seekers in 2015|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/7233417/3-20042016-AP-EN.pdf/34c4f5af-eb93-4ecd-984c-577a5271c8c5|work=Eurostat|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the first three months of 2015, the number of new asylum applicants in the EU was 184,800, increasing by 86 percent if compared with the same quarter in the previous year but remaining stable if compared to the last quarter of 2014. More than half applied for [[asylum in Germany]] (40 percent) or Hungary (18 percent). The main nationalities of the applicants were Kosovo (48,875 or 26 percent), Syria (29,100 or 16 percent) and Afghanistan (12,910 or 7 percent).<ref name=\"asylumQ1\">{{cite web|title=185 000 first time asylum seekers in the EU in the first quarter of 2015|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/6887997/3-18062015-CP-EN.pdf/4457b050-26f9-4cf1-bf27-9ffb73ff8c7b|publisher=EUROSTAT|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> In the second quarter of 2015, 213,200 people applied for asylum in the EU, up by 15 percent compared with the previous quarter. 38 percent applied for asylum in Germany, followed by Hungary (15 percent) and Austria (8 percent). The main countries of citizenship of asylum seekers, accounting for more than half of the total, were Syria (21 percent), Afghanistan (13 percent), Albania (8 percent), Iraq (6 percent) and Kosovo (5 percent).<ref name=\"asylumQ2\">{{cite web|title=Over 210 000 first time asylum seekers in the EU in the second quarter of 2015|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/6996925/3-18092015-BP-EN.pdf/b0377f79-f06d-4263-aa5b-cc9b4f6a838f|publisher=EUROSTAT|date=18 September 2015}}</ref> In the third quarter of 2015 (July\u2013September), EU countries received 413,800 first time asylum applications, almost double the number registered in the previous quarter. Germany and Hungary were the top recipients, with 26 percent each of total applicants. One third of asylum seekers were Syrians (33 percent), followed by Afghans (14 percent) and Iraqis (11 percent).<ref name=\"asylumQ3\">{{cite web|title=More than 410 000 first time asylum seekers registered in the third quarter of 2015|url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/7105334/3-10122015-AP-EN.pdf/04886524-58f2-40e9-995d-d97520e62a0e|publisher=Eurostat}}</ref> In the fourth quarter of 2015, there were 426,000 first time applicants, mainly Syrians (145,130), Afghans (79,255) and Iraqis (53,585). The top recipients were Germany (38 percent), Sweden (21 percent) and Austria (7 percent).<ref name=\"Asylum quarterly report\">{{cite web |title=Asylum quarterly report |url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Asylum_quarterly_report |publisher=EUROSTAT}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, the German government announced that it expected to receive 800,000 asylum applications by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Europe migrant crisis: Germany 'will cope with surge' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33992563 |work=BBC News |date=19 August 2015}}</ref> Data released by Germany's Federal Office for Migration and Refugees (BAMF) in January 2016 showed that Germany received 476,649 asylum applications in 2015, mainly from Syrians (162,510), Albanians (54,762), Kosovars (37,095), Afghans (31,902), Iraqis (31,379), Serbians (26,945), Macedonians (14,131), Eritreans (10,990) and Pakistanis (8,472). In 2015, Germany made 282,762 decisions on asylum applications; the overall asylum recognition rate was 49.8 percent (140,915 decisions were positive, so that applicants were granted protection). The most successful applicants were Syrians (101,419 positive decisions, with a 96 percent recognition rate), Eritreans (9,300 positive decisions; 92.1 percent recognition rate) and Iraqis (14,880 positive decisions; 88.6 percent recognition rate).<ref>{{cite web|title=476.649 Asylantr\u00e4ge im Jahr 2015|url=http://www.bamf.de/SharedDocs/Meldungen/DE/2016/201610106-asylgeschaeftsstatistik-dezember.html|publisher=BAMF|date=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Asylgesch\u00e4ftsstatistik 12/2015|url=http://www.bamf.de/SharedDocs/Anlagen/DE/Downloads/Infothek/Statistik/Asyl/201512-statistik-anlage-asyl-geschaeftsbericht.html?nn=1367522|publisher=BAMF|date=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nSweden received 162,877 asylum applications in 2015, mainly from Syrians (51,338), Afghans (41,564), Iraqis (20,857), Eritreans (7,231) and Somalis (5,465).<ref name=sma2015>{{cite web|title=Applications for asylum received, 2015|url=http://www.migrationsverket.se/download/18.7c00d8e6143101d166d1aab/1451894593595/Inkomna+ans%C3%B6kningar+om+asyl+2015+-+Applications+for+asylum+received+2015.pdf|publisher=[[Swedish Migration Agency]]}}</ref> In 2015, Sweden granted protection to 32,631 asylum applicants, whereas it rejected 9,524 applications (the proportion of positive decisions out of materially considered applications was 77 percent). The main beneficiaries of protection were Syrians (18,523 positive decisions, with a 100 percent recognition rate), Eritreans (6,542 positive decisions; 100 percent recognition rate) and Afghans (1,088 positive decisions; 74 percent recognition rate).<ref>{{cite web|title=Asylum decisions, 2015|url=http://www.migrationsverket.se/download/18.7c00d8e6143101d166d1aad/1451894587413/Avgjorda+asyl%C3%A4renden+2015+-+Asylum+desicions+2015.pdf|publisher=[[Swedish Migration Agency]]}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n{{Side box |metadata=No\n|text={{Graph:Chart\n|legend=EU28 Asylum applicants by origin, in 2016\n|type=pie\n|width=120\n|x=Syria, Afghanistan, Iraq, Pakistan, Nigeria, Iran, Eritrea, Albania, Russia, Unknown, Somalia, Bangladesh, Gambia, Guinea, Serbia, Ukraine, Algeria, Morocco, Kosovo, Cote d'Ivoire, Sudan, Turkey, Stateless, Rest of the world\n|y1=339245, 186605, 130100, 49915, 47775, 41395, 34470, 32465, 27605, 20730, 20060, 17245, 16030, 14045, 13185, 12490, 11925, 11805, 11680, 11380, 11370, 11055, 10720,177615\n}}\n|below=Source: Eurostat, s\u00e9rie migr_asyappctza\n}}\n\nIn 2016, according to Eurostat, most of the non EU28 asylum seekers in EU 28 originated from Syria. Syria, Afghanistan and Iraq together make 50 percent of the grand total.<ref name=\"Asylum 2016\">{{cite news |title=Asylum applicants in the EU |url=http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/news/themes-in-the-spotlight/asylum2016|work=Eurostat|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\nThe second quarter of 2017 recorded a 54 percent decrease in the number of first time asylum applicants as compared to the second quarter of 2016, and 11 percent fewer applicants than the first quarter of 2017 as well. The greatest number of applications were from Syria, Afghanistan and Nigeria, giving a clear indication of the current nodes of this crisis. However, the number of Syrians and Afghans continued to be less than that of the same time in 2016, suggesting that perhaps, the peak of this crisis has passed. Initially looking at the noticeably fewer number of both migrants and applications indicates that this crisis may be on the decline. But the increasing number of illegal immigrants from Africa simply suggests that the direction of the crisis is changing. While Germany recorded the highest number of first time applicants (over 49,000), Spain saw a 30 percent increase in the number of asylum seekers, along with Cyprus and Bulgaria.<ref name=\"Asylum quarterly report\" />\n\n=== Illegal border crossings ===\n[[File:Migrants in Hungary 2015 Aug 003.jpg|thumb|Migrants along the Western Balkan route crossing from Serbia into Hungary, 24 August 2015]]\nIn September 2015, Europol estimated there were 30 000 suspected migrant smugglers, which rose to 55 000 in 2016 and a further 10 000 more in 2017. Of the smugglers, 63 percent are from Europe, 14 percent from the Middle East, 13 percent from Africa and 9 percent from Eastern Asia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/news-africa/1879124/europe-migrants-smugglers/|title=EU tracking 65,000 migrant smugglers: Europol|last=CARMICHAEL/AFP|first=by Lachlan|work=The Citizen|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrontex tracks and publishes data on numbers of illegal crossings along the main six routes twice a year. The following table shows the data for the period up to and including the year 2015:\n\n{| class=\"unsortable wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:200px;\"|Main migration routes into the European Union\n!colspan=11|Illegal border crossings (land and sea)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2006\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2007\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2008\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2009\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2010\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2011\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2012\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2013\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2014\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2015\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|2016\n|-\n!scope=row|Western African route\n|align=right|{{nts|31600}}\n|align=right|{{nts|12500}}\n|align=right|{{nts|9200}}\n|align=right|{{nts|2250}}\n|align=right|{{nts|200}}\n|align=right|{{nts|340}}\n|align=right|{{nts|170}}\n|align=right|{{nts|250}}\n|align=right|{{nts|275}}\n|align=right|{{nts|874}}\n|align=right|{{nts|671}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Western Mediterranean route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|6500}}\n|align=right|{{nts|6650}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|8450}}\n|align=right|{{nts|6400}}\n|align=right|{{nts|6800}}\n|align=right|{{nts|7840}}\n|align=right|{{nts|7164}}\n|align=right|{{nts|10231}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Central Mediterranean route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|39800}}\n|align=right|{{nts|11000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|4500}}\n|align=right|{{nts|64300}}\n|align=right|{{nts|15900}}\n|align=right|{{nts|40000}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\"|{{nts|170760}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\"|{{nts|153946}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\"|{{nts|181459}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Apulia and Calabria route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|807}}\n|align=right|{{nts|2788}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5259}}\n|align=right|{{nts|4772}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5000}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Circular Albania\u2013Greece route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|42000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|40000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|35300}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5300}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5500}}\n|align=right|{{nts|8700}}\n|align=right|{{nts|8840}}\n|align=right|{{nts|8932}}\n|align=right|{{nts|5121}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Western Balkan route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|3090}}\n|align=right|{{nts|2370}}\n|align=right|{{nts|4650}}\n|align=right|{{nts|6390}}\n|align=right|{{nts|19950}}\n|align=right|{{nts|43360}}\n|align=right|{{nts|764038}}\n|align=right|{{nts|130261}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Eastern Mediterranean route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|52300}}\n|align=right|{{nts|40000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|55700}}\n|align=right|{{nts|57000}}\n|align=right|{{nts|37200}}\n|align=right|{{nts|24800}}\n|align=right|{{nts|50830}}\n|align=right|{{nts|885386}}\n|align=right|{{nts|182277}}\n|-\n!scope=row|Eastern Borders route\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1335}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1050}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1050}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1050}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1600}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1300}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1270}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1920}}\n|align=right|{{nts|1349}}\n|-\n!scope=row|'''Totals'''\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|align=right|'''{{nts|104847}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|106908}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|146349}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|77932}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|106800}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|283175}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|1822260}}'''\n|align=right|'''{{nts|500248}}'''\n|-\n!scope=row colspan=12|<center>Source: [http://frontex.europa.eu/trends-and-routes/migratory-routes-map/ Frontex]</center>\n|}\n===Illegal border crossings by nationality===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Detected illegal border crossings to the EU by nationality\n! Country\n! 2014\n! 2015\n! 2016\n! 2017\n! 2018\n|-\n| {{flag|Afghanistan}}\n| <!-- 2014 --> \u2013\n| <!-- 2015 --> {{FORMATNUM:267485}}\n| <!-- 2016 --> {{FORMATNUM:54366}}\n| <!-- 2017 --> {{FORMATNUM:7576}}\n| <!-- 2018 --> {{FORMATNUM:12666}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Algeria}}\n| <!-- 2014 --> \u2013\n| <!-- 2015 --> {{FORMATNUM:3331}}\n| <!-- 2016 --> {{FORMATNUM:5140}}\n| <!-- 2017 --> {{FORMATNUM:7443}}\n| <!-- 2018 --> {{FORMATNUM:6411}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Bangladesh}}\n| <!-- 2014 --> {{FORMATNUM:4527}}\n| <!-- 2015 --> {{FORMATNUM:13098}}\n| <!-- 2016 --> {{FORMATNUM:9445}}\n| <!-- 2017 --> {{FORMATNUM:9384}}\n| <!-- 2018 --> \u2013\n|-\n| {{flag|Eritrea}}\n| <!-- 2014 --> {{FORMATNUM:34586}}\n| <!-- 2015 --> {{FORMATNUM:40349}}\n| <!-- 2016 --> {{FORMATNUM:21349}}\n| <!-- 2017 --> \u2013\n| <!-- 2018 --> \u2013\n|-\n| {{flag|Gambia}}\n| <!-- 2014 --> {{