b diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Consequences of the Iraqi Civil War]]\n[[Category:Consequences of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to Europe]]\n[[Category:Refugees of the Arab Winter]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMigrant(link changed toHuman migration) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_migrant_crisis"}
{"title_page": "Ordinary People (Slovakia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Ordinary People and<br>Independent Personalities\n| logo = File:Logo of Ordinary People.png\n| colorcode = {{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Igor Matovi\u010d]]\n| foundation = 28 October 2011\n| ideology = [[Conservatism]]<ref name=\"Visegrad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visegradgroup.eu/news/ordinary-people-files|title=The Visegrad Group: the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and Slovakia - Ordinary People files request to be registered as political party in Slovakia|first=Webra International|last=Kft.|date=28 October 2011|website=www.visegradgroup.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/slovakia.html|title=Slovakia|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|accessdate=4 March 2020|year=2020}}</ref><br>[[Social conservatism]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tomek|first1=Radoslav|last2=Dudik|first2=Andrea|date=28 February 2020|title=Contract Killing Looms Over Slovakia\u2019s Election|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-28/contract-killing-looms-over-slovakia-s-election|url-access=limited|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref><br>[[Populism]]<ref name=\"Wassenberg2019\">{{cite book|author=Birte Wassenberg|chapter=Euroscepticism at the EP elections in 2014: A reflection of the different patterns of opposition to the EU?|editor=Olivier Costa|title=The European Parliament in Times of EU Crisis: Dynamics and Transformations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5l7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA287|year=2019|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-97391-3|page=287}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=K\u0159t\u00ednov\u00e1|first=Andrea|title=Politick\u00e1 strana O\u013dANO jako p\u0159\u00edklad populistick\u00e9 strany |year=2009 |publisher=[[Masaryk University]]|location=Brno|url=https://is.muni.cz/th/u7wcs/bakalarka_OLANO.pdf |accessdate=10 December 2019|language=cs}}</ref><br>[[Christian democracy]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Istrate|first=Dominik|date=28 February 2020|title=A divided Slovakia heads for the polls|url=https://emerging-europe.com/news/a-divided-slovakia-heads-for-the-polls/|work=Emerging Europe}}</ref> <br>[[Liberalism]]<ref>{{cite news|date=3 March 2020|title=Matovi\u010d v debate Denn\u00edka N: Chcem vl\u00e1du, \u010do vydr\u017e\u00ed, a nie opakova\u0165 zn\u00e1me veci o Koll\u00e1rovi|url=https://dennikn.sk/1782162/matovic-na-debate-dennika-n-chcem-vladu-co-vydrzi-a-nie-opakovat-zname-veci-o-kollarovi/?ref=list}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Bratislava]]\n| international = \n| website = {{URL|http://obycajniludia.sk}}\n| country = Slovakia\n| native_name = Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia a nez\u00e1visl\u00e9 osobnosti\n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Freedom House|title=Nations in Transit 2013: Democratization from Central Europe to Eurasia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y1ZzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA517|date=24 December 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-3119-1|page=517}}</ref>\n| european = \n| europarl = {{nowrap|[[European People's Party group|European People's Party]]}}\n| colours = {{Color box|#808080|border=darkgray}} [[Gray]] {{Color box|#b2c800|border=darkgray}} [[Green]]\n| seats1_title = [[National Council of the Slovak Republic|National Council]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|53|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|14|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Regions of Slovakia|Self-governing regions]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|2|8|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = Local councils\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|304|20646|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| split = [[Freedom and Solidarity]]\n}}\n\n'''Ordinary People''' ({{lang-sk|Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia}}), full name '''Ordinary People and Independent Personalities'''<ref>{{Citation |title=Ordinary People and Independent Personalities party releases its election slate |newspaper=The Slovak Spectator |date=15 December 2011 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/44844/10/ordinary_people_and_independent_personalities_party_releases_its_election_slate.html |accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> ({{lang-sk|Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia a nez\u00e1visl\u00e9 osobnosti}}, O\u013daNO), is a [[Populism|populist]],<ref name=\"Wassenberg2019\"/> [[conservatism|conservative]]<ref name=\"Lansford2013\">{{cite book|author=Tom Lansford|title=Political Handbook of the World 2013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lUF1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1292|date=15 April 2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4522-5825-6|page=1292}}</ref> [[List of political parties in Slovakia|political party in Slovakia]]. It first ran four candidates on the list of the  [[Freedom and Solidarity]] (SaS) party in the [[2010 Slovak parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary election]] to the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]], and all four were elected. The party is led by [[Igor Matovi\u010d]], one of the original 4 MPs.\n\n==History==\nThe four Ordinary People MPs were Igor Matovi\u010d, Erika Jurinov\u00e1, Martin Fecko, Jozef Viskupi\u010d.<ref name=\"SaS chairman speaks about\"/> O\u013daNO sat in the National Council with the SaS and signed an agreement with the SaS that its members could not [[Crossing the floor|cross the floor]] to another group.  In June and July 2010,<ref name=\"SaS chairman speaks about\">{{cite news |title=SaS chairman speaks about its new MPs from the Ordinary People civic association |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=15 June 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39247/10/sas_chairman_speaks_about_its_new_mps_from_the_ordinary_people_civic_association.html |accessdate=}}</ref> it was rumoured that O\u013daNO would refuse to back the programme of the new centre-right coalition,<ref>{{cite news |title='Ordinary Man' MP Matovi\u010d accuses Fico of lying |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=5 August 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39711/10/ordinary_man_mp_matovic_accuse_fico_of_lying.html |accessdate=}}</ref> which included Freedom and Solidarity, and whose majority depended on Ordinary People.<ref name=\"Ordinary People faction will give\">{{cite news |title=SaS: Ordinary People faction will give up their parliamentary seats if they leave SaS caucus |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=3 August 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39698/10/sas_ordinary_people_faction_will_give_up_their_parliamentary_seats_if_they_leave_sas_caucus.html |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Matovi\u010d said that it was not the right time to become an independent party.<ref name=\"Ordinary People faction will give\"/> However, on 28 October 2011, Ordinary People filed a formal party registration, while Matovi\u010d announced that the party would compete in [[2012 Slovak parliamentary election|2012 parliamentary election]] as a separate electoral list, of independents and representatives of the [[Civic Conservative Party]] and the [[Conservative Democrats of Slovakia|Conservative Democrats]].<ref name=\"Visegrad\"/> In the 2012 election, the party came in third place overall, winning 8.55% of the vote and 16 seats.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2012/03/slovakias-election Slovakia turns left], [[The Economist]] (11 March 2012)</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2014 European elections]], O\u013daNO came in fourth place nationally, receiving 7.46% of the vote and electing 1 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ep2014.statistics.sk/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528053354/http://ep2014.statistics.sk/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |archivedate=2014-05-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 Slovak parliamentary elections|2016 Slovak parliamentary election]], Ordinary People ran in alliance with [[New Majority (Slovakia)|New Majority]]. They received 11.03% votes in Slovakia and consequently 19 MPs in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|Slovak Parliament]], 17 of whom came from Ordinary People.\n\nIn 2014\u20132019, the party was member of European Parliament group of [[European Conservatives and Reformists]] and in 2019 switched to the [[European People's Party group]].\n\nAt the [[2020 Slovak parliamentary election|February 2020 parliamentary election]], the Party received 34.6% of the vote, winning a 53 of 150 seats in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]]. Party leader [[Igor Matovi\u010d]] was appointed as the Prime Minister designate.\n\n==Political positions==\nIn 2019, Ordinary People suggested toughening restrictions on abortions. The proposal included a fee charge for abortion for women over 40 years of age. The proposal also featured written guidance to be given by the doctor to the woman before the procedure. This guidance included a detailed description of the medical procedure and the feelings that women can expect after the procedure.<ref>[https://www.zenyvmeste.sk/navrhu-olano-na-sprisnenie-potratov-chybal-jediny-hlas--podporil-ho-beblavy-ci-blahova--zdrzali-sa-petrik-i-poliacik N\u00e1vrhu O\u013dANO na spr\u00edsnenie potratov ch\u00fdbal jedin\u00fd hlas, podporil ho Beblav\u00fd \u010di Bl\u00e1hov\u00e1, zdr\u017eali sa Petr\u00edk i Polia\u010dik] {{in lang|sk}}, \u017deny v meste (26 September 2019)</ref>\n\nDuring the election campaign in 2019, the party's leader Igor Matovi\u010d promised that Ordinary People would not enter a government which would approve registered partnerships for same sex couples.<ref>[https://www.teraz.sk/slovensko/olano-nepojde-do-vlady-ktora-by-mal/418599-clanok.html O\u013daNO nep\u00f4jde do vl\u00e1dy, ktor\u00e1 by schv\u00e1lila registrovan\u00e9 partnerstv\u00e1] {{in lang|sk}}, teraz.sk (15 September 2019)</ref> O\u013daNO also rejects [[Human migration|migrant]] relocation quotas, proposed by the [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Slovensk\u00e9 volby vyhr\u00e1lo opozi\u010dn\u00ed hnut\u00ed, dominance Sm\u011bru skon\u010dila |url=https://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/slovenske-volby-vyhralo-opozicni-hnuti-dominance-smeru-skoncila/1860403 |website=\u010cesk\u00e9Noviny.cz |accessdate=1 March 2020 |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n=== National Council ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Vote\n! %\n! MPs\n! \u00b1\n! Place\n! Govt.\n|-\n![[2012 Slovak parliamentary election|2012]]\n| 218,537\n| 8.55\n|{{Composition bar|16|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 16\n| 3rd\n|{{no2|No}}\n|-\n![[2016 Slovak parliamentary election|2016]] \n| 287,611\n| 11.03\n|{{Composition bar|19|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 3\n| 3rd\n|{{no2|No}}\n|-\n![[2020 Slovak parliamentary election|2020]]\n|721,166\n|25,03\n|{{Composition bar|53|150|hex= {{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 34\n|1st\n|{{yes2|Yes}}\n|}\n\n=== European Parliament ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Vote\n! Vote %\n! Seats\n! Change\n! Place\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2014]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://volby.statistics.sk/ep/ep2014/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |title=Elections to the European Parliament 2014| website=Vo\u013eby SR| publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic |access-date=7 March 2016}}</ref> \n| 41,829\n| 7.46\n| {{Composition bar|1|13|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 1\n| 4th\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2019]]\n| 51,834\t\n| 5.25\n| {{Composition bar|1|14|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{nochange}} 0\n| 6th\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Political parties in Slovakia}}\n\n[[Category:Liberal conservative parties in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Populist parties]]\n[[Category:Freedom and Solidarity breakaway groups]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Slovakia]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Ordinary People and<br>Independent Personalities\n| logo = File:Logo of Ordinary People.png\n| colorcode = {{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Igor Matovi\u010d]]\n| foundation = 28 October 2011\n| ideology = [[Conservatism]]<ref name=\"Visegrad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visegradgroup.eu/news/ordinary-people-files|title=The Visegrad Group: the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and Slovakia - Ordinary People files request to be registered as political party in Slovakia|first=Webra International|last=Kft.|date=28 October 2011|website=www.visegradgroup.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/slovakia.html|title=Slovakia|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|accessdate=4 March 2020|year=2020}}</ref><br>[[Social conservatism]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tomek|first1=Radoslav|last2=Dudik|first2=Andrea|date=28 February 2020|title=Contract Killing Looms Over Slovakia\u2019s Election|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-28/contract-killing-looms-over-slovakia-s-election|url-access=limited|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref><br>[[Populism]]<ref name=\"Wassenberg2019\">{{cite book|author=Birte Wassenberg|chapter=Euroscepticism at the EP elections in 2014: A reflection of the different patterns of opposition to the EU?|editor=Olivier Costa|title=The European Parliament in Times of EU Crisis: Dynamics and Transformations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5l7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA287|year=2019|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-97391-3|page=287}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=K\u0159t\u00ednov\u00e1|first=Andrea|title=Politick\u00e1 strana O\u013dANO jako p\u0159\u00edklad populistick\u00e9 strany |year=2009 |publisher=[[Masaryk University]]|location=Brno|url=https://is.muni.cz/th/u7wcs/bakalarka_OLANO.pdf |accessdate=10 December 2019|language=cs}}</ref><br>[[Christian democracy]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Istrate|first=Dominik|date=28 February 2020|title=A divided Slovakia heads for the polls|url=https://emerging-europe.com/news/a-divided-slovakia-heads-for-the-polls/|work=Emerging Europe}}</ref> <br>[[Liberalism]]<ref>{{cite news|date=3 March 2020|title=Matovi\u010d v debate Denn\u00edka N: Chcem vl\u00e1du, \u010do vydr\u017e\u00ed, a nie opakova\u0165 zn\u00e1me veci o Koll\u00e1rovi|url=https://dennikn.sk/1782162/matovic-na-debate-dennika-n-chcem-vladu-co-vydrzi-a-nie-opakovat-zname-veci-o-kollarovi/?ref=list}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Bratislava]]\n| international = \n| website = {{URL|http://obycajniludia.sk}}\n| country = Slovakia\n| native_name = Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia a nez\u00e1visl\u00e9 osobnosti\n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Freedom House|title=Nations in Transit 2013: Democratization from Central Europe to Eurasia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y1ZzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA517|date=24 December 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-3119-1|page=517}}</ref>\n| european = \n| europarl = {{nowrap|[[European People's Party group|European People's Party]]}}\n| colours = {{Color box|#808080|border=darkgray}} [[Gray]] {{Color box|#b2c800|border=darkgray}} [[Green]]\n| seats1_title = [[National Council of the Slovak Republic|National Council]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|53|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|14|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Regions of Slovakia|Self-governing regions]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|2|8|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = Local councils\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|304|20646|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n| split = [[Freedom and Solidarity]]\n}}\n\n'''Ordinary People''' ({{lang-sk|Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia}}), full name '''Ordinary People and Independent Personalities'''<ref>{{Citation |title=Ordinary People and Independent Personalities party releases its election slate |newspaper=The Slovak Spectator |date=15 December 2011 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/44844/10/ordinary_people_and_independent_personalities_party_releases_its_election_slate.html |accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> ({{lang-sk|Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia a nez\u00e1visl\u00e9 osobnosti}}, O\u013daNO), is a [[Populism|populist]],<ref name=\"Wassenberg2019\"/> [[conservatism|conservative]]<ref name=\"Lansford2013\">{{cite book|author=Tom Lansford|title=Political Handbook of the World 2013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lUF1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1292|date=15 April 2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4522-5825-6|page=1292}}</ref> [[List of political parties in Slovakia|political party in Slovakia]]. It first ran four candidates on the list of the  [[Freedom and Solidarity]] (SaS) party in the [[2010 Slovak parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary election]] to the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]], and all four were elected. The party is led by [[Igor Matovi\u010d]], one of the original 4 MPs.\n\n==History==\nThe four Ordinary People MPs were Igor Matovi\u010d, Erika Jurinov\u00e1, Martin Fecko, Jozef Viskupi\u010d.<ref name=\"SaS chairman speaks about\"/> O\u013daNO sat in the National Council with the SaS and signed an agreement with the SaS that its members could not [[Crossing the floor|cross the floor]] to another group.  In June and July 2010,<ref name=\"SaS chairman speaks about\">{{cite news |title=SaS chairman speaks about its new MPs from the Ordinary People civic association |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=15 June 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39247/10/sas_chairman_speaks_about_its_new_mps_from_the_ordinary_people_civic_association.html |accessdate=}}</ref> it was rumoured that O\u013daNO would refuse to back the programme of the new centre-right coalition,<ref>{{cite news |title='Ordinary Man' MP Matovi\u010d accuses Fico of lying |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=5 August 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39711/10/ordinary_man_mp_matovic_accuse_fico_of_lying.html |accessdate=}}</ref> which included Freedom and Solidarity, and whose majority depended on Ordinary People.<ref name=\"Ordinary People faction will give\">{{cite news |title=SaS: Ordinary People faction will give up their parliamentary seats if they leave SaS caucus |first=Zuzana |last=Vilikovsk\u00e1 |newspaper=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=3 August 2010 |url=http://spectator.sme.sk/articles/view/39698/10/sas_ordinary_people_faction_will_give_up_their_parliamentary_seats_if_they_leave_sas_caucus.html |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Matovi\u010d said that it was not the right time to become an independent party.<ref name=\"Ordinary People faction will give\"/> However, on 28 October 2011, Ordinary People filed a formal party registration, while Matovi\u010d announced that the party would compete in [[2012 Slovak parliamentary election|2012 parliamentary election]] as a separate electoral list, of independents and representatives of the [[Civic Conservative Party]] and the [[Conservative Democrats of Slovakia|Conservative Democrats]].<ref name=\"Visegrad\"/> In the 2012 election, the party came in third place overall, winning 8.55% of the vote and 16 seats.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2012/03/slovakias-election Slovakia turns left], [[The Economist]] (11 March 2012)</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2014 European elections]], O\u013daNO came in fourth place nationally, receiving 7.46% of the vote and electing 1 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ep2014.statistics.sk/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528053354/http://ep2014.statistics.sk/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |archivedate=2014-05-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 Slovak parliamentary elections|2016 Slovak parliamentary election]], Ordinary People ran in alliance with [[New Majority (Slovakia)|New Majority]]. They received 11.03% votes in Slovakia and consequently 19 MPs in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|Slovak Parliament]], 17 of whom came from Ordinary People.\n\nIn 2014\u20132019, the party was member of European Parliament group of [[European Conservatives and Reformists]] and in 2019 switched to the [[European People's Party group]].\n\nAt the [[2020 Slovak parliamentary election|February 2020 parliamentary election]], the Party received 34.6% of the vote, winning a 53 of 150 seats in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]]. Party leader [[Igor Matovi\u010d]] was appointed as the Prime Minister designate.\n\n==Political positions==\nIn 2019, Ordinary People suggested toughening restrictions on abortions. The proposal included a fee charge for abortion for women over 40 years of age. The proposal also featured written guidance to be given by the doctor to the woman before the procedure. This guidance included a detailed description of the medical procedure and the feelings that women can expect after the procedure.<ref>[https://www.zenyvmeste.sk/navrhu-olano-na-sprisnenie-potratov-chybal-jediny-hlas--podporil-ho-beblavy-ci-blahova--zdrzali-sa-petrik-i-poliacik N\u00e1vrhu O\u013dANO na spr\u00edsnenie potratov ch\u00fdbal jedin\u00fd hlas, podporil ho Beblav\u00fd \u010di Bl\u00e1hov\u00e1, zdr\u017eali sa Petr\u00edk i Polia\u010dik] {{in lang|sk}}, \u017deny v meste (26 September 2019)</ref>\n\nDuring the election campaign in 2019, the party's leader Igor Matovi\u010d promised that Ordinary People would not enter a government which would approve registered partnerships for same sex couples.<ref>[https://www.teraz.sk/slovensko/olano-nepojde-do-vlady-ktora-by-mal/418599-clanok.html O\u013daNO nep\u00f4jde do vl\u00e1dy, ktor\u00e1 by schv\u00e1lila registrovan\u00e9 partnerstv\u00e1] {{in lang|sk}}, teraz.sk (15 September 2019)</ref> O\u013daNO also rejects [[migrant]] relocation quotas, proposed by the [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Slovensk\u00e9 volby vyhr\u00e1lo opozi\u010dn\u00ed hnut\u00ed, dominance Sm\u011bru skon\u010dila |url=https://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/slovenske-volby-vyhralo-opozicni-hnuti-dominance-smeru-skoncila/1860403 |website=\u010cesk\u00e9Noviny.cz |accessdate=1 March 2020 |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n=== National Council ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Vote\n! %\n! MPs\n! \u00b1\n! Place\n! Govt.\n|-\n![[2012 Slovak parliamentary election|2012]]\n| 218,537\n| 8.55\n|{{Composition bar|16|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 16\n| 3rd\n|{{no2|No}}\n|-\n![[2016 Slovak parliamentary election|2016]] \n| 287,611\n| 11.03\n|{{Composition bar|19|150|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 3\n| 3rd\n|{{no2|No}}\n|-\n![[2020 Slovak parliamentary election|2020]]\n|721,166\n|25,03\n|{{Composition bar|53|150|hex= {{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 34\n|1st\n|{{yes2|Yes}}\n|}\n\n=== European Parliament ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Vote\n! Vote %\n! Seats\n! Change\n! Place\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2014]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://volby.statistics.sk/ep/ep2014/EP-dv/Tabulka3_en.html |title=Elections to the European Parliament 2014| website=Vo\u013eby SR| publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic |access-date=7 March 2016}}</ref> \n| 41,829\n| 7.46\n| {{Composition bar|1|13|hex={{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 1\n| 4th\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2019]]\n| 51,834\t\