{{prose|section|date=December 2015}}\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 865\n|1930= 791\n|1940= 837\n|1950= 1114\n|1960= 1833\n|1970= 1971\n|1980= 5717\n|1990= 29188\n|2000= 109697\n|2010= 208453\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=248279\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Gilbert Civic Center.jpg|thumb|right|Town Hall building at the Civic Center]]\n[[File:Picture of lake front in Val Vista Lakes in Gilbert, Arizona, USA.jpg|thumb|right|A waterfront in the Val Vista Lakes community in Gilbert]]\n[[File:Downtown Gilbert - SWC Gilbert & Page - 2009-03-23.JPG|thumb|right|The Liberty Market with the Gilbert water tower (in background), pictured in March 2009]]\n[[File:SanTan Village - North - 2009-09-20.JPG|thumb|right|[[SanTan Village]] in September 2009]]\n<!--(I'm commenting this out because it's half a sentence, doesn't go with the following sentence, and the source is a dead link. If you can make sense of this, please do. Thanks!) As of July 1, 2009, [[Maricopa Association of Governments]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mag.maricopa.gov/pdf/cms.resource/MAG_2009-07-01_Municipality-Updates_99200.pdf|title=Maricopa Association of Governments Population & Housing Numbers for Greater Phoenix|publisher=Mag.maricopa.gov|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>-->\n\nAs of the census of 2010, there were 208,453 people, 74,147 housing units, and 3.01 persons per household.\n\n*Fastest growing municipality in the United States from 1990 to 2003 ([[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]])\n*4th fastest growing municipality in the United States ([[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau \u2013 2009]])\n*Ranked by CNN's ''Money'' magazine in 2008 as one of the best places to live in the United States<ref name=\"CNN Money Magazine 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com |title=CNN Money Magazine 2008 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>\n*One of the top 25 safest cities in the United States<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/ucr/ucr.htm#cius |title=FBI Crime Statistics |publisher=Fbi.gov |date=March 17, 2010 |accessdate=September 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120917122839/http://www2.fbi.gov/ucr/ucr.htm#cius |archivedate=September 17, 2012  }}</ref>\n*34.5% of Gilbert residents hold a bachelor's degree or higher.<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\">[http://en-us.nielsen.com/tab/product_families/nielsen_claritas Nielsen Claritas] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618213444/http://en-us.nielsen.com/tab/product_families/nielsen_claritas |date=June 18, 2010 }}</ref>\n*Highest household median income in the Phoenix Metropolitan Area with population 50,000+ ([[U.S. Census Bureau 2005]])\n\nAccording to Nielsen's Claritas demographics,<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\"/> in 2009 the racial makeup of the town was:\n*81.51% [[White American|White]]\n*15.39% [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanics or Latinos]]\n*3.08% [[African American|Black or African American]]\n*0.79% Native American\n*4.70% [[Asian American|Asian]]\n*0.23% [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander]]\n*5.97% from [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|other races]]\n*3.73% from two or more races\n\n'''2009 estimated population data by gender/age''':<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\"/>\n*31.37 average age male/female. By 2019, the average age was reported as 33.6.<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n*50.22% male\n**30.03 est. average age\n*49.78% female\n**31.82 est. average age\n*37.14% population under 21\n*33.25% population under 18\n*70.01% population over 16\n*66.76% population over 18\n*62.86% population over 21\n*5.30% population over 65\n\n'''2009 estimated population age 15+ by marital status''':<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\"/>\n*20.87% never married\n*66.71% married, spouse present\n*2.23% married, spouse absent\n*2.11% widowed\n*8.07% divorced\n\n'''2009 estimated population age 25+ educational attainment''':<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\"/>\n*92.33% high school/GED or higher\n*37.5% bachelor's degree or higher.  A 2019 report put the rate at close to 50% for residents over the age of 25.<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n*10.46% master's degree or higher\n\n'''2009 estimated household by household income''':<ref name=\"Nielsen Claritas\"/>\n*$109,213 average household income\n*$89,077 median household income.  Median income noted as >$87,000 in a report of 2013-2017 US Census data, as compared to a state-wide median of $53,000.<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n*$35,559 per capita Income\n*2.28% of families are below the poverty level\n\n===Religion===\nVarious religious denominations are represented in Gilbert. The town has been known for its high population of members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, a fact evidenced by the building of [[Gilbert Arizona Temple]] dedicated March 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sltrib.com/lds/ci_9071215?source=rss |title=LDS Church announces two new temples in Arizona |work=The Salt Lake Tribune |date=April 27, 2008 |accessdate=September 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930014058/http://www.sltrib.com/lds/ci_9071215?source=rss |archive-date=September 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[https://churchofjesuschristtemples.org/gilbert-arizona-temple/ Gilbert Arizona Temple], ldschurchtemples.com. Retrieved April 27, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Largest employers===\nAccording to the town's 2013 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gilbertaz.gov/home/showdocument?id=2854|title=City of Gilbert 2013 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]|page=141|accessdate=June 18, 2014|date=June 18, 2014}}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Gilbert Public Schools]]\n|3,642\n|-\n|2\n|[[Banner Health]]\n|2,268 (~1,000 by 2019)<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n|-\n|3\n|[[Mercy Gilbert Medical Center]]\n|1,233\n|-\n|4\n|Town of Gilbert\n|1,191\n|-\n|5\n|[[Fry's Food and Drug]]\n|966\n|-\n|6\n|[[Go Daddy]]\n|950 (1,300 by 2019)<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n|-\n|7\n|[[Walmart]]\n|791\n|-\n|8\n|[[Chandler Unified School District]]\n|518\n|-\n|9\n|B H Drywall\n|500\n|-\n|10\n|[[Dillard's]] Retail and Distribution\n|490\n|}\nAdditional employers noted in a 2019 report were [[Dignity Health]], employing about 1,000; and [[Isagenix International]], a marketing company employing >700.<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Music and dance===\nThese performers have been associated with Gilbert:\n* [[Lydia (band)|Lydia]], band<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com|title=Gilbert's Lydia to Perform with Full String Section at Mesa Arts Center|last=Burnsilver|first=Glenn|date=November 9, 2016|work=Phoenix New Times|access-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lindsey Stirling]], violinist, dancer, and performer; Mesquite High School graduate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2014/05/07/lindsey-stirling-billboard-album-chart-gilbert/8818225/ |title=Gilbert's Lindsey Stirling No. 2 on Billboard chart |work=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=May 8, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===9-11 Memorial===\n\nGilbert is home to a 9-11 Memorial, located at Town Hall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gilbertaz.gov/departments/town-hall|title=Town Hall {{!}} Town of Gilbert, Arizona|website=www.gilbertaz.gov|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> that features an eight-foot steel girder beam<ref>{{Citation|last=Atridim|first=Captain Rick|title=9-11 Memorial in Gilbert Arizona|date=2011-09-25|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/atridim/8209572942/|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> which held up the North Tower of the World Trader Center.<ref>{{Citation|title=World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|date=2020-02-21|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=World_Trade_Center_(1973%E2%80%932001)&oldid=941970161|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> Former Gilbert Fire Chief Collin DeWitt fundraised extensively for three years to create the memorial, and to bring the beam from New York City to Arizona. He drove to collect it himself along with his then Assistant Fire Chief Jim Jobusch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gilbertaz.gov/Home/Components/News/News/296/|title=Gilbert Digital Newsroom {{!}} Town of Gilbert, Arizona|website=www.gilbertaz.gov|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nThe design of the memorial angles the beam, which puts it in reach of everyone. Four granite walls bear the names of those lost to the attacks.<ref>{{Citation|title=Casualties of the September 11 attacks|date=2020-02-28|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Casualties_of_the_September_11_attacks&oldid=942995817|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>  Concrete was poured in the shape of a pentagon for the foundation of the memorial,<ref>{{Citation|title=9/11 Memorial - Gilbert, Arizona|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NiCVN4YTuJY|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> and it is surrounded by bricks which carry names of some of those who helped to donate to bring the memorial to life. There was an unveiling ceremony of the memorial on the 10th anniversary of the attack on September, 11, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/community/gilbert/articles/2011/08/09/20110809gilbert-911-memorial-construction-work-begins.html|title=Gilbert 9/11 memorial: Work begins on site|last=Aug. 9|last2=azcentral.com|first2=2011 11:01 AM The Republic {{!}}|website=azcentral.com|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\nGilbert was recognized in 2010 as the \"36th Best Place to Live in the nation\",<ref name=\"CNN Money Magazine 2010\">{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2010/snapshots/PL0427400.html |publisher=CNN |title=Best Places to Live 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813220449/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2010/snapshots/PL0427400.html |archivedate=August 13, 2010  }}</ref> as well as among the nation's \"top places to live and learn\",<ref name=\"CNN Money Magazine 2010\"/> by GreatSchools.org. Washington, DC-based [[CQ Press]] rated Gilbert the \"safest municipality in Arizona, and 25th safest in the nation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://os.cqpress.com/citycrime/2012/CityCrime2013_CityCrimeRateRankings.pdf|title=CQ Press: City Crime Rankings 2012|publisher=Os.cqpress.com|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince Gilbert remains incorporated as a town, it lacks the additional powers possessed by nearby [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]] and [[Chandler, Arizona|Chandler]], which are incorporated as cities. For instance, Arizona towns do not have as much power to regulate utilities and construction within their borders as cities possess.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azleg.gov/ars/9/00276.htm|title=Arizona Revised Statutes \u00a79-276. Additional powers of cities|publisher=Arizona State Legislature|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> Unlike most of its neighboring communities, Gilbert is theoretically vulnerable to annexation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azleg.gov/ars/9/00122.htm|title=Arizona Revised Statutes \u00a79\u2013122. Unification of a city and a town|publisher=Arizona State Legislature|accessdate=July 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe town is part of {{ushr|AZ|5}}, which is represented by Republican and Gilbert resident [[Andy Biggs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biggs.house.gov/biography |title=Official biography, Congressman Andy Biggs |publisher=Congressman Andy Biggs |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> The mayor of Gilbert is Jenn Daniels.\n\n===Crime===\n{{Infobox UCR\n|city_name= Gilbert\n|year= 2014\n|homicide= 0\n|rape= 11\n|robbery= 17\n|aggravated_assault= 60\n|violent_crime= 89\n|burglary= 246\n|larceny_theft= 1,175\n|motor_vehicle_theft= 54\n|arson= 10\n|property_crime= 1,475\n|source_url= https://www.fbi.gov/about-us/cjis/ucr/crime-in-the-u.s/2014/crime-in-the-u.s.-2014/tables/table-8/table-8-by-state/Table_8_Offenses_Known_to_Law_Enforcement_by_Arizona_by_City_2014.xls\n|source_name= 2014 FBI UCR Data\n|notes= 2014 population: 235,430\n}}\n\nGilbert is rated as a town of relatively low crime. According to [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] records, Gilbert was the largest town in the United States with zero murders in 2005, 2007, and 2014.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Education==\nMost of Gilbert is zoned to schools in the [[Gilbert Public Schools]], while other portions are zoned to districts including the [[Chandler Unified School District]], [[Mesa Public Schools]], and the [[Higley Unified School District]]. Also in Gilbert are charter schools such as Eduprize (the first charter school in Arizona), American Leadership Academy, and Legacy Traditional School.  The town is also home to [[Gilbert Christian Schools]], a chain of private schools. In 2018, the [[Park University]] opened a the [[Park University Gilbert|Gilbert Campus Center]] after leasing {{convert|18000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} at the University Building in the city's Heritage District.<ref name=\"ParkGilbert2019\">{{cite news |last1=Staff |title=Park University to expand campus in downtown Gilbert |url=https://ktar.com/story/2680894/park-university-to-expand-campus-in-downtown-gilbert/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=KTAR News |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n{{Main|Metropolitan Phoenix Freeways}}\nGilbert is primarily served by one [[Metropolitan Phoenix Freeways|area freeway]]\u2014the Santan Freeway portion of [[Arizona State Route 202|Loop 202]].  A small section of the [[U.S. Route 60 in Arizona|US 60]] Superstition Freeway also skirts the northern boundary of the town at the Higley Road interchange (Exit 186). Several regional arterials also serve the area, including Williams Field Road, [[Chandler, Arizona|Chandler]] Boulevard, and Gilbert Road. The town enjoys relative closeness to [[Phoenix Mesa Gateway Airport]], which is located in east [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]], and is a 25 minute drive from [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport]].\n\nRecently, a [[park-and-ride]] facility was constructed in downtown Gilbert for bus service and future [[commuter rail]] service. Although the facility borders the [[Union Pacific]] (formerly Southern Pacific) tracks and has provisions for commuter rail service, there is currently no such service. Bus service is limited in Gilbert, with some north-south routes in Mesa dead-ending at Baseline Road before entering Gilbert.  Routes that serve portions of Gilbert include the 108-Elliot Road, 112-Country Club/Arizona Avenue, 136-Gilbert Road, 140-Ray Road, 156-Chandler Boulevard/Williams Field Road, 184-Power Road, and 531-Mesa/Gilbert Express, with most of these routes operating at 30-minute frequency on weekdays.  Sunday service is only available on Routes 108, 112, 156, and 184.  Most people get around by cars or bikes. The city of Gilbert has a low percentage of households without a car. In 2015, 1.9 percent of Gilbert households lacked a car, and the figure was virtually unchanged in 2016 (1.7 percent). The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016. Gilbert averaged 2.08 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Car Ownership in U.S. Cities Data and Map|journal=Governing|url=http://www.governing.com/gov-data/car-ownership-numbers-of-vehicles-by-city-map.html|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 [[Waymo]] started testing in a small portion of the northwest portion of the town of Gilbert.<ref>{{cite web|title=Waymo Expanding Chandler Operations Ahead of Launch of Arizona Public Ride Service|journal=The Arizona Republic|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/money/business/tech/2018/08/21/waymo-expands-arizona-footprint-chandler-before-ride-service-start/1046805002/|accessdate=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recreation ===\nThe parks Gilbert Regional Park and Desert Sky Park were established in 2019 with multi-million dollar investments.<ref name=\"Steinbach2019\" />\n\n==Historic structures==\n{{Lists of historic properties}}\nThe following is a brief description of the historic structures which are pitcured. Some of these structures are listed in the National Register of Historic Places while others are listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.<ref>[https://nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/az/maricopa/state.html National Register of Historic Places Maricopa County, Arizona]</ref><ref>[https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/gilbert/2016/07/03/historic-gilbert-properties-you-need-see/86533124/ Historic Gilbert properties you need to see]</ref>\n\n*'''Gilbert Elementary School''' was built in 1913.  It is located at 10 S. Gilbert Rd. and now houses the Gilbert Historical Museum. It is listed in the National Register of Historic Places.\n*'''Gilbert High School''' was built in 1920.  It now houses the Gilbert Public School District Office.  The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''Gilbert Water Tower''' was built in 1925.  The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*'''Gilbert's First Jail House''' was built in 1918 and later used as a pump house. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''Tone Building''' was built in 1929 and now houses Joe's Real BBQ Restaurant. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*'''Liberty Market''' was built in 1936. Liberty Market was established by the Dong family. The neon sign which is still on display was designed by Mae Ong, the wife of Ben Ong, who purchased the market in 1943. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''Creed building''' was built in 1918. It now houses the Farmhouse Restaurant. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''Attaway Phelps-Blakely Building''' was built in 1910. It now houses the Norwood Furniture store.  The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''Bank of Gilbert''' was built in 1917. It now houses an insurance company. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*'''Clare's Metal Shop''' was built in 1918. It now houses Bergies Coffee. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*'''Clement's Garage''' was built in 1934. The structure is listed as historical by the Gilbert Heritage District.\n*The '''American Legion Post 39''' was built in 1934.\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Historic Gilbert\n|width=180px\n|height=200px\n|align=center\n|lines=4\n\n|File: Gilbert-Gilbert_Elementary_School-1913.jpg|'''Gilbert Elementary School'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Gilbert_High_School_1920.jpg |'''Gilbert High School'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Gilbert_Water_Tower-1925.jpg |The '''Gilbert Water Tower'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Gilberts_first_Jail_House-1918.jpg |'''Gilbert's first jail house'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Tone_Building-1929.jpg|The '''Tone Building'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Liberty_Market-1936.jpg |'''Liberty Market'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Creed_building-1918.jpg |The '''Creed building'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Attaway_Phelps-Blakely_Building-1910.jpg|The '''Attaway Phelps-Blakely Building'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Bank_of_Gilbert-1917-1.jpg|The '''Bank of Gilbert'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Clare's_Metal_Shop-1918.jpg|'''Clare's Metal Shop'''.\n|File: Gilbert-Clemen's_Gargage-1934.jpg|'''Clement's Garage'''.\n|File:Gilbert-American_Legion_Post_39-1950.jpg|The '''American Legion Post 39'''.\n}}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Jim Bechtel]], professional [[poker]] player; World Champion of Poker in 1993; lives in Gilbert<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2013/jul/07/1993-main-event-champ-jim-bechtel-poker/|title=For 1993 champ Jim Bechtel, Main Event always stirs up memories of competing at Binion's|date=July 7, 2013|work=LasVegasSun.com|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Burba]], lives in Gilbert; pitcher for late 1990s [[Cleveland Indians]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/colleges/osu/story/_/id/8154261/dave-burba-back-minors|title=OSU Time And Change: Dave Burba|publisher=ESPN|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Marquis Cooper]], professional [[linebacker]]; played for [[Highland High School (Gilbert, Arizona)|Highland High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/playerpage/492913 |title=NFL Players |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Ken Delo]], singer best known for'' [[The Lawrence Welk Show]]''; lives in Gilbert{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n* [[The Honky Tonk Man]], pro wrestler (real name Roy Wayne Farris); lives in Gilbert{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n* [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]], [[NFL]] [[quarterback]]; played for [[Highland High School (Gilbert, Arizona)|Highland High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/playerpage/547043 |title=NFL Players |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://la.galaxy.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=t106&player=gordon_a&playerId=gor137067&statType=current |title=Los Angeles Galaxy: Roster: Player Bio |publisher=La.galaxy.mlsnet.com |accessdate=September 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090709233130/http://la.galaxy.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=t106&player=gordon_a&playerId=gor137067&statType=current |archivedate=July 9, 2009  }}</ref>\n* [[Jineane Ford]], Miss Arizona USA 1980, [[Miss USA]] 1980<ref>{{cite news|author=Midey, Connie|date=July 3, 2011|title=Former Miss USA and TV news anchor is still a farm girl at heart|newspaper=The Arizona Republic|url=http://archive.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/arizonaliving/articles/20110703comeback0703jineane.html|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Alan Gordon (soccer)|Alan Gordon]], professional soccer player; born in Gilbert in 1981{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n* [[Dan Hausel]], Hall of Fame martial artist; resident of Gilbert since 2006\n* [[Shea Hillenbrand]], All-Star professional baseball player{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n* [[Darrin Jackson]], professional baseball player, 1985\u20131999; TV broadcaster; lives in Gilbert{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n* [[Kimberly Joiner]], [[Miss Arizona USA]] 2008; raised in and still lives in Gilbert<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/community/gilbert/articles/2008/04/11/20080411gr-missusa11-ON.html |title=Gilbert woman vies for Miss USA |work=The Arizona Republic |date=April 11, 2008 |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Naomi Lang]], five-time US ice dance champion, 2002 Olympian{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n* [[Spencer Larsen]], former professional football player; raised in Gilbert; played for [[Highland High School (Gilbert, Arizona)|Highland High School]]\n* [[Justin Lassen]], artist; lives in Gilbert; graduated from Gilbert High School in 2000{{dubious|date=December 2010}}\n* [[Ryan Leslie]], television personality on [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Real World: New Orleans (2010)|The Real World: New Orleans]]''{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n* [[Bengie Molina]], former [[Major League Baseball]] [[catcher]]; has lived in Gilbert since 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/business/realestate/articles/20110201arizona-priciest-home-sales-done-deals.html |title=The Valley's priciest home sales |work=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=February 11, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Alex Naddour]], bronze medalist at 2011 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships and in pommel horse at [[2016 Summer Olympics]]; graduate from [[Highland High School (Gilbert, Arizona)|Highland High School]]\n* [[Carlos I. Noriega]], [[NASA]] [[astronaut]]; retired [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]]; lives in Gilbert<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/noriega.html |title=Astronaut Bio: Carlos I. Noriega (1/2008) |publisher=Jsc.nasa.gov |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Phil Ortega]], [[MLB]] [[pitcher]], 1960\u20131969; born in Gilbert in 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/o/ortegph01.shtml |title=Phil Ortega Statistics |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Mykayla Skinner]], gold medalist at [[2014 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships]]; bronze medalist on vault\n* [[Lindsey Stirling]], violinist; dancer; performer; grew up in Gilbert\n* [[Eric Swann]], NFL player for [[Arizona Cardinals]]; lives in Gilbert{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n* [[Rick Woolstenhulme]], drummer for band [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{SisterCities|Gilbert|two}}\n* {{flagdeco|UK}} [[Newtownabbey]], County Antrim, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom\n* {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Leshan]], Sichuan, China\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|United States|Arizona}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links|voy=Gilbert}}\n*[http://www.gilbertaz.gov Official government website]\n{{Commons category-inline|Gilbert, Arizona}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles relating to Gilbert and [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]]\n| list =\n{{Maricopa County, Arizona}}\n{{Phoenix Metropolitan Area}}\n{{Arizona}}\n{{USLargestMetros}}\n{{Arizona cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Gilbert, Arizona| ]]\n[[Category:Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Sonoran Desert]]\n[[Category:Towns in Maricopa County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Towns in Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stray word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilbert,_Arizona"}
{"title_page": "Melktert", "text_new": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Melktert\n| image            = Melktert.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A freshly baked melktert\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[South Africa]]\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]]\n| type             = [[Tart]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Pastry crust, [[milk]], [[flour]], [[sugar]], [[egg (food)|eggs]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Melktert''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025b|l|k|t|\u025b|r|t}}, [[Afrikaans]] for '''milk tart''') is a South African dessert consisting of a [[shortcrust pastry|sweet pastry crust]] containing a [[custard tart|custard filling]] made from [[milk]], [[flour]], [[sugar]] and [[egg (food)|eggs]]. The ratio of milk to eggs is higher than in a traditional [[Pastel de nata|Portuguese custard tart]] or Chinese [[egg tart]], resulting in a lighter texture and a stronger milk flavour.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/weekend-argus-saturday-edition/20180224/281870118924700 | title =It's the simplicity of taste that makes milk tart great | publisher =Weekend Argus (Saturday Edition) | access-date =30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> \n\nThe dessert originated among [[Dutch Empire|settlers]] at the [[Dutch Cape Colony]] in the 17th century, and is believed to have developed from the Dutch ''mattentaart'', a [[cheesecake]]-like dessert<ref name=\"roads and kingdoms\">{{cite web  | url =https://roadsandkingdoms.com/travel-guide/johannesburg/johannesburg-in-10-dishes/ | title =A HISTORY OF JOHANNESBURG IN 10 DISHES| last =Mungwani| first =Uwive| date =13 September 2018 | website =Roads & Kingdoms | publisher =  | access-date = 30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> which was included in the cookbook ''Een Notabel Boexcken Van Cokeryen'' (''A Notable Book of Cookery'') published by [[Thomas van der Noot]] around 1514.<ref name=\"sweet and short\" /> Some recipes require that the custard be baked in the crust, while others call for the custard to be prepared in advance, and then placed in the crust before serving.<ref name=\"sweet and short\">{{cite web  | url =https://www.iol.co.za/lifestyle/food-drink/the-sweet-and-short-history-of-good-ol-milk-tart-19542653 | title =The sweet and short history of good ol' milk tart | last =Mosia | first =Lebohang | date =27 February 2019 | website = | publisher = IOL News | access-date = 30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> [[Cinnamon]] is often sprinkled over its surface, and the milk used for the custard may also be infused with a cinnamon stick before preparation. A staple at church [[fete]]s and home industries, and commonplace in South African supermarkets,<ref name=\"sweet and short\" /> melktert may either be served chilled or at room temperature.<ref name=\"sweet and short\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|South Africa|Food}}\n* ''[[Cook and Enjoy It]]'' \u2013 authentic South African recipes\n* [[List of African dishes]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.netwerk24.com/Sarie/Kos/Resepte/die-wen-melktert-hiers-die-resep-20170914 |title=Die wen-melktert - hier's die resep! |date=28 May 2009 |website=[[Sarie]]}}\n\n{{South African cuisine}}\n\n[[Category:South African cuisine]]\n[[Category:Tarts]]\n[[Category:Custard desserts]]\n[[Category:Milk dishes]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-stub}}\n{{pie-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Melktert\n| image            = Melktert.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A freshly baked melktert\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[South Africa]]\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]]\n| type             = [[Tart]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Pastry crust, [[milk]], [[flour]], [[sugar]], [[egg (food)|eggs]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Melktert''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025b|l|k|t|\u025b|t}}, [[Afrikaans]] for '''milk tart''') is a South African dessert consisting of a [[shortcrust pastry|sweet pastry crust]] containing a [[custard tart|custard filling]] made from [[milk]], [[flour]], [[sugar]] and [[egg (food)|eggs]]. The ratio of milk to eggs is higher than in a traditional [[Pastel de nata|Portuguese custard tart]] or Chinese [[egg tart]], resulting in a lighter texture and a stronger milk flavour.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/weekend-argus-saturday-edition/20180224/281870118924700 | title =It's the simplicity of taste that makes milk tart great | publisher =Weekend Argus (Saturday Edition) | access-date =30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> \n\nThe dessert originated among [[Dutch Empire|settlers]] at the [[Dutch Cape Colony]] in the 17th century, and is believed to have developed from the Dutch ''mattentaart'', a [[cheesecake]]-like dessert<ref name=\"roads and kingdoms\">{{cite web  | url =https://roadsandkingdoms.com/travel-guide/johannesburg/johannesburg-in-10-dishes/ | title =A HISTORY OF JOHANNESBURG IN 10 DISHES| last =Mungwani| first =Uwive| date =13 September 2018 | website =Roads & Kingdoms | publisher =  | access-date = 30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> which was included in the cookbook ''Een Notabel Boexcken Van Cokeryen'' (''A Notable Book of Cookery'') published by [[Thomas van der Noot]] around 1514.<ref name=\"sweet and short\" /> Some recipes require that the custard be baked in the crust, while others call for the custard to be prepared in advance, and then placed in the crust before serving.<ref name=\"sweet and short\">{{cite web  | url =https://www.iol.co.za/lifestyle/food-drink/the-sweet-and-short-history-of-good-ol-milk-tart-19542653 | title =The sweet and short history of good ol' milk tart | last =Mosia | first =Lebohang | date =27 February 2019 | website = | publisher = IOL News | access-date = 30 September 2019 | quote = }}</ref> [[Cinnamon]] is often sprinkled over its surface, and the milk used for the custard may also be infused with a cinnamon stick before preparation. A staple at church [[fete]]s and home industries, and commonplace in South African supermarkets,<ref name=\"sweet and short\" /> melktert may either be served chilled or at room temperature.<ref name=\"sweet and short\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|South Africa|Food}}\n* ''[[Cook and Enjoy It]]'' \u2013 authentic South African recipes\n* [[List of African dishes]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.netwerk24.com/Sarie/Kos/Resepte/die-wen-melktert-hiers-die-resep-20170914 |title=Die wen-melktert - hier's die resep! |date=28 May 2009 |website=[[Sarie]]}}\n\n{{South African cuisine}}\n\n[[Category:South African cuisine]]\n[[Category:Tarts]]\n[[Category:Custard desserts]]\n[[Category:Milk dishes]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-stub}}\n{{pie-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Klipfontein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected a typo.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melktert"}
{"title_page": "Bones (season 4)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number = 4\n |image = [[File:Bones-s4-dvd.jpg]]\n |caption = Season 4 DVD cover art\n |bgcolour = #26466D\n |country = United States\n |network = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n |first_aired = {{Start date|2008|9|3}}\n |last_aired = {{End date|2009|5|14}}\n |num_episodes = 26\n |episode_list = List of Bones episodes\n}}\nThe fourth season of the American television series ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' premiered on September 3, 2008, with a two-hour episode and concluded on May 14, 2009, on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. The show changed time slots again, airing on Wednesdays at 8:00 pm ET before moving to Thursdays at 8:00 pm ET in 2009. The season consisted of 26 episodes and averaged 10.8 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052709_07 |title=Season Rankings (Through 5/24)|work=ABC Medianet |date=May 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{See also|List of Bones characters}}\n\n=== Main cast ===\n*[[Emily Deschanel]] as [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan|Dr. Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]], a [[forensic anthropologist]]\n*[[David Boreanaz]] as FBI Special Agent [[Seeley Booth]], the official FBI liaison with the Jeffersonian\n*[[Michaela Conlin]] as [[Angela Montenegro]], a [[forensic artist]]\n*[[T. J. Thyne]] as [[Jack Hodgins (Bones)|Dr. Jack Hodgins]], an [[entomologist]]\n*[[Tamara Taylor]] as [[Camille Saroyan|Dr. Camille Saroyan]], a [[forensic pathologist]] and the head of the forensic division\n*[[John Francis Daley]] as [[Lance Sweets|Dr. Lance Sweets]], an FBI [[psychologist]] who studies the relationship between Dr. Brennan and Agent Booth\n\n=== Recurring cast ===\n*[[David Greenman]] as [[List of Bones characters#Marcus Geier|Marcus Geier]], a forensic technician\n*[[Patricia Belcher]] as [[List of Bones characters#Caroline Julian|Caroline Julian]], a prosecutor\n*[[Brendan Fehr]] as [[List of Bones characters#Jared Booth|Jared Booth]], Booth's brother\n*[[Marisa Coughlan]] as FBI Agent [[List of Bones characters#Payton Perotta|Payton Perotta]]\n*[[Nichole Hiltz]] as Roxie Lyon, Angela\u2019s girlfriend\n*[[Tuppence Middleton]] as Vera Waterhouse\n*[[Eric Millegan]] as Dr. [[Zack Addy]]\n*[[Ryan O'Neal]] as [[List of Bones characters#Matthew Brennan / Max Keenan|Max Keenan]], Brennan's father\n*[[Ty Panitz]] as [[List of Bones characters#Parker Booth|Parker Booth]], Booth's son\n*[[Stephen Fry]] as Dr. [[List of Bones characters#Gordon Wyatt|Gordon Wyatt]], Booth's former psychiatrist\n*[[Billy Gibbons]] as Angela's father\n*[[Deirdre Lovejoy]] as [[List of Bones characters#The Grave Digger|Heather Taffet]]\n\n;Interns\n*[[Eugene Byrd]] as Dr. [[List of Bones characters#Clark Edison|Clark Edison]]\n*[[Ryan Cartwright]] as [[List of Bones characters#Vincent Nigel-Murray|Vincent Nigel-Murray]]\n*[[Michael Grant Terry]] as [[List of Bones characters#Wendell Bray|Wendell Bray]]\n*[[Carla Gallo]] as [[List of Bones characters#Daisy Wick|Daisy Wick]]\n*[[Joel David Moore]] as [[List of Bones characters#Colin Fisher|Colin Fisher]]\n*[[Pej Vahdat]] as [[List of Bones characters#Arastoo Vaziri|Arastoo Vaziri]]\n*[[Michael Badalucco]] as Scott Starret\n\n== Episodes ==\nThe season premieres with its first two-part episode, \"Yanks in the U.K.\" which was filmed on-location in the [[United Kingdom]]. Due to the season's extended episode count of 26 and multiple pre-emptions, Fox aired seven episodes throughout the month of April 2009, with new episodes airing on Monday and Wednesday, along with its regular timeslot of Thursday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2009/04/02/bones-to-visit-monday-wednesday-nights-in-april-30918/8024/ |title=Bones to Visit Monday, Wednesday Nights in April |work=The Futon Critic |date=April 2, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2012}}</ref> This season sees the return of [[The Grave Digger (Bones)|The Grave Digger]], who was last seen in the second season. This time, The Grave Digger captures Booth. After Booth is rescued, the team discovers the true identity of The Grave Digger.\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table\n|background  = #26466D\n|overall     = 6\n|season      = 6\n|title       = 23\n|director    = 14\n|writer      = 19\n|airdate     = 16\n|prodcode    = 6\n|viewers     = 10\n|country     = US\n|episodes    = \n{{Episode list/sublist|Bones (season 4)\n |MainList=List of Bones episodes\n |EpisodeNumber=59<hr />60\n |EpisodeNumber2=1<hr />2\n |Title=Yanks in the U.K.\n |ShortSummary=This two-hour season premiere, begins when Booth and Brennan are at [[Oxford University]] in [[Oxford]], [[England]] for a conference. They are then called to [[London]] to help solve a case in collaboration with a pair of British investigators from [[Scotland Yard]]. Meanwhile, Angela's estranged husband, Grayson Barasa, is finally found, but he refuses to sign the divorce papers, much to the dismay of Hodgins and Angela.<hr />When one of the British investigators is murdered, Booth and Brennan become more determined to help solve the murder. Meanwhile, Angela and Hodgins continue to have relationship problems regarding their marriage.\n |WrittenBy=[[Hart Hanson]] & Karine Rosenthal<hr />Stephen Nathan & [[Scott A. Williams|Scott Williams]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Ian Toynton]]\n |Viewers=9.17<ref name=\"s4 premiere ratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2008/09/04/ratings-wednesday-september-3-bones-opens-strong-top-model-weak/4917/ |title=Ratings Wednesday, September 3: Bones Opens Strong, Top Model Weak |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Bill |last=Gorman |date=September 4, 2008 |accessdate=November 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108093155/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2008/09/04/ratings-wednesday-september-3-bones-opens-strong-top-model-weak/4917/ |archivedate=January 8, 2013 }}</ref><hr />10.2