tatus    = dead\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6253&type=2&interval=50&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12.pdf\n| archive-url =   https://web.archive.org/web/20040331010101/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020%2D119.01%2De.php?%26file_num%3Dnlc008388.6253%26type%3D2%26interval%3D50%26PHPSESSID%3Dccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12.pdf\n| title       = Adult Contemporary \u2013 Volume 38, No.&nbsp;23, August 06 1983\n| author      = [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]\n| publisher   = [[Library and Archives Canada]]\n| format      = PDF\n| archive-date = 31 March 2004\n| access-date  = 19 February 2011\n| url-status    = dead\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2011-02-20T05%3A27%3A10Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=15384775&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus\n| title       = AMICUS No.&nbsp;17118375\n| author      = [[Library and Archives Canada]]\n| language    = French\n| accessdate  = 19 February 2011\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"collectionscanada.gc.ca1\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2011-02-20T06%3A01%3A25Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=8146164&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus\n| title       = AMICUS No.&nbsp;8146164\n| author      = [[Library and Archives Canada]]\n| accessdate  = 19 February 2011\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"collectionscanada.gc.ca2\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2011-02-20T06%3A06%3A24Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=7406743&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus\n| title       = AMICUS No.&nbsp;7406743\n| author      = [[Library and Archives Canada]]\n| accessdate  = 19 February 2011\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"jam.canoe.ca\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Pop_Encyclopedia/S/Strange_Advance.html\n| title       = Artist: Strange Advance Biography\n| date        = 7 December 2004\n| work        = [[Jam!]]\n| archive-url  = https://archive.is/20130101002017/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Pop_Encyclopedia/S/Strange_Advance.html\n| archive-date = 2013-01-01\n| access-date  = 19 February 2011\n| url-status    = dead\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Strange+Advance\n| title       = Juno Awards Database\n| publisher   = [[Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706184410/http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Strange+Advance\n| archive-date = 2011-07-06\n| access-date  = 19 February 2011\n| url-status    = dead\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.strangeadvance.com/}}\n* {{AllMusic|class=artist|id=mn0000631439|label=Strange Advance}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Strange Advance}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/groups/2400609862/ Strange Advance] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strange Advance}}\n[[Category:1982 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1995 disestablishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian new wave musical groups]]\n[[Category:Canadian synthpop groups]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Strange Advance\n| image            = Strange Advance.png\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Drew Arnott and Darryl Kromm circa 1988\n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| genre            = [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| years_active     = {{hlist|1982\u20131995|2019\u2013present}}\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|strangeadvance.com}}\n| current_members  = Drew Arnott<br/>Sean Dillon<br/>Rob Bailey<br/>Alexander Boynton<br/>Ian Cameron<br/>Ross Friesen\n| past_members     = Darryl Kromm<br/>Ric deGroot<br/>Joey Alvero<br/>David Quinton<br/>Paul Iverson<br/>\n}}\n\n'''Strange Advance''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[New wave music|new wave]] band formed in 1982 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]].  They were nominated for a [[Juno Awards of 1983|1983 Juno Award]] as [[Juno Award for New Group of the Year|Most Promising Group of the Year]] and again in [[Juno Awards of 1985|1985]] as [[Juno Award for Group of the Year|Group of the Year]].<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\"/>  Their first two albums, 1982's [[Worlds Away (Strange Advance album)|''Worlds Away'']]''<ref name=\"collectionscanada.gc.ca2\"/>'' and 1985's ''[[2WO]]'', were Canadian gold selling records.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gold/Platinum |url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?_gp_search=strange%20advance |website=musicCanada |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1982\u20131995: Formation and Canadian popularity===\nStrange Advance was initially made up of Drew Arnott (keyboards, percussion, vocals), Darryl Kromm (lead vocals, guitars), and Paul Iverson (bass).  The three met in [[Vancouver]] and founded the group in 1980. Initially called '''Metropolis''', they were forced to change their name after discovering a band in Germany using \"Metropolis.\"\n\nThe group's first album, ''[[Worlds Away (Strange Advance album)|Worlds Away]]'' featured the title track, \"Worlds Away,\" which saw modest airplay in North American markets in 1983.  The album was produced by [[Bruce Fairbairn]], known for his work with [[Loverboy]] and [[Prism (band)|Prism]], but featured a very different sound from those groups.<ref name=\"jam.canoe.ca\" /> Rather than commercial [[hard rock]], Strange Advance's music was a fusion of [[progressive rock]] and [[New wave music|new wave]], with a heavy reliance on synthesizers and keyboards.\n\nIverson left the group after the first album and was not replaced.  The group's 1985 album ''[[2WO]]'' also went gold in Canada and was produced by Arnott, using an extensive array of session players, and brought the band their first big Canadian hit with \"We Run.\"  Strange Advance had never played a live gig prior to 1985, so Arnott and Kromm added musicians Ric deGroot (keyboards), Ian Cameron (guitar, violin), Joey Alvero (bass) and David Quinton (drums) to the line-up as session players, and supported the first two albums with a tour of Eastern Canada.\n\nStrange Advance's third album, 1988's ''[[The Distance Between]]''<ref name=\"collectionscanada.gc.ca1\"/> also used well-known session musicians (including [[Randy Bachman]] and [[Allan Holdsworth]]), and produced the top 20 single \"Love Becomes Electric.\" Following this album's release, the group became essentially inactive.\n\nIn 1995, the Strange Advance compilation album ''Worlds Away & Back'' featured a mix of previously released material, outtakes, remixes, demos, and three newly recorded tracks\u2014one from 1991, and two from 1995.\n\n===2016\u2013present: Remastering and reunion===\nOn June 24, 2016, ''[[The Distance Between]]'' was remastered and re-released on CD with two bonus tracks, an extended club mix of \"Love Becomes Electric\" and the previously unreleased song, \"Flow My Tears\".\n\nIn December 2018, ''[[Worlds Away (Strange Advance album)|Worlds Away]]'' was remastered and re-released on CD with two bonus tracks, the UK Dance Mix of \"Love Games\" (transferred from vinyl) and the b-side to \"She Controls Me\" - \"Lost In Your Eyes.\" This marks the first time their debut has seen a CD release of any kind, despite the albums' popularity. This release is only available in the Philippines, on the Sound Philosophy label, which is a new boutique label for titles not released on CD. This version appears to be sourced from the master tapes.\n\nOn September 17, 2018, Drew Arnott announced a crowdfunding campaign on Facebook to finance a summer 2019 Strange Advance reunion tour.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Drain |first1=Heather |title=Who Can Touch Us When We Run?: The Pain & Beauty of Strange Advance |url=https://diaboliquemagazine.com/who-can-touch-us-when-we-run-the-pain-beauty-of-strange-advance/ |website=Diabolique magazine |accessdate=3 July 2019 |date=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/strangeadvance1/status/1042583635361128448 |title= Strange Advance |publisher=Strange Advance |accessdate=3 July 2019 |date=19 September 2018}}</ref> The fundraising was successful, and the band (minus Kromm) planned to perform in 2019 for the Radical Orbits Tour. Unfortunately, due to cancellations and delays, the tour has not begun as of 2020.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[Worlds Away (Strange Advance album)|Worlds Away]]'' (1982)\n*''[[2WO]]'' (1985)\n*''[[The Distance Between]]'' (1988)\n\n===Compilation albums===\n*''Over 60 Minutes with... Strange Advance'' (1987)\n*''Worlds Away & Back'' (1995)\n\n===Music video compilations===\n*''Strange Advance'' (1985)\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:22em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Release\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.8em;font-size:90%;\"| [[RPM (magazine)|CAN Pop]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.8em;font-size:90%;\"| [[RPM (magazine)|CAN AC]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"She Controls Me\"\n| 1982\n| \u2014 || \u2014 \n|rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Worlds Away (Strange Advance album)|Worlds Away]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Kiss in the Dark\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1983\n| \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Love Games\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Worlds Away\"\n| 46 || 29 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"We Run\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1985\n| 28 || \u2014 \n|rowspan=\"3\"|''[[2WO]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Running Away\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Second That I Saw You\"\n| \u2014 || 20\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Love Becomes Electric\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1988\n| 20 || \u2014 \n|rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[The Distance Between]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Till the Stars Fall\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hold You\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Music|Canada}}\n*[[List of bands from Canada]]\n*[[List of bands from British Columbia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6259&type=2&interval=50&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12.pdf\n| archive-url =   https://web.archive.org/web/20040331010101/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020%2D119.01%2De.php?%26file_num%3Dnlc008388.6259%26type%3D2%26interval%3D50%26PHPSESSID%3Dccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12.pdf\n| title       = Top Singles - Volume 38, No.&nbsp;23, August 06 1983\n| author      = [[RPM (magazine)]]\n| date        = \n| month       = \n| year        = \n| work        = \n| publisher   = [[Library and Archives Canada]]\n| language    = \n| format      = PDF\n| archive-date = 31 March 2004\n| access-date  = 19 February 2011\n| quote       = \n| url-status    = dead\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.collectionscana