{"title_page": "Solomon Antwi Kwaku Bonsu", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Samuel Antwi Kwaku Bonsu\n|image = \n|image_size = \n|caption = \n|office1 = Minister of Pensions and National Insurance\n|term_start1 = July 1965\n|term_end1 = February 1966\n|president1 = Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n|predecessor1 = A. K. Onwona-Agyemang\n|successor1 = ''Ministry abolished''\n|office2 = Minister of Co-operatives\n|term_start2 = January 1965\n|term_end2 = July 1965\n|president2 = Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n|predecessor2 = ''New''\n|successor2 = Baffour Kwabena Senkyire<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Baffour+co-operative |page=ii |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref>\n|office4 = Member of Parliament<br>for Adotobri\n|term_start4 = June 1965\n|term_end4 = February 1966\n|predecessor4 = ''New''\n|successor4 = ''Consituency abolished''\n|majority4 = \n|office5 = Member of Parliament<br>for Sekyere West\n|term_start5 = 12 June 1959\n|term_end5 = June 1965\n|predecessor5 = [[R. R. Amponsah]]\n|successor5 = ''Consituency abolished''\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1921|11|1}}\n| birth_name = Solomon Antwi Kwaku Bonsu\n|birth_place = \n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|residence = \n|citizenship = Ghanaian\n|nationality = \n|fields = \n|workplaces = \n|alma_mater = [[Presbyterian College of Education,\u00a0Akropong]]\n|doctoral_advisor = \n|academic_advisors = \n|doctoral_students = \n|notable_students = \n|known_for = \n|influences = \n|influenced = \n|awards = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Samuel Antwi Kwaku Bonsu''' also known by the name '''Solomon Antwi Kwaku Bonsu''' was a [[Ghanaian]] [[politician]] in the [[Nkrumah government|first republic]]. He was the Minister of Co-operatives and later Minister of Pensions and National Insurance. He was also the member of parliament for the Sekyere West constituency from 1959 to 1965 and the member of parliament for the Adotobri constituency from 1965 to 1966.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBonsu was born on 21 November 1921 at Asante Mampong in the [[Ashanti Region]].<ref name=\"BONSU\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1966 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3hMOAQAAMAAJ&q=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&dq=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ8_T4isXoAhWFTRUIHWCBAYsQ6AEIOjAF |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=12 |date=1966 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref> After completing his Standard Seven, he entered the [[Presbyterian College of Education,\u00a0Akropong]] (then the Presbyterian Training Colloge, Akropong) where he obtained his Teachers' Certificate 'A'.<ref name=\"BONSU\"/> He later continued at the Theological Seminary at [[Akropong]] graduating in 1941.<ref name=\"BONSU\"/> In 1954 he studied to obtain his GCE\u00a0Advanced Level certificate prior to proceeding to the [[United Kingdom]] to study law at the [[Middle Temple]], [[London]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1966 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3hMOAQAAMAAJ&dq=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Legal+1959+deputy+protocol |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=12 |date=1966 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref> He was called to the bar as a barrister-at-law in 1957.<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/>\n\n==Career and politics==\nBonsu begun as a teacher at the [[Kumasi]] Presbyterian Middle School before joining the Kumasi branch of U. T. C. as a Departmental Store Manager.<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/>\n\nBonsu became a private legal pracitioner in 1959, and on 12 June that same year, he was sworn into office as the member parliament for the Sekyere West constituency.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=M_9HAQAAIAAJ&q=solomon+antwi+kwaku+bonsu+sekyere&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrsYz8pcfoAhVpVRUIHVwIAIcQ6AEIGTAA |page=94 |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1958 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> This was as a result of the seat being vacant due to a law in parliament at the time that deprived members of parliament of their seat if they were unable to be present in parliament for ten (10) consecutive days.<ref name=\"SOLOMON BONSU\">{{cite book |last=Asamoah |first=Obed |authorlink=Obed Asamoah |date=2014 |title=The Political History of Ghana (1950-2013): The Experience of a Non-Conformist |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=O28ZBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=r+r+amponsah+detained+1959&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAs4OerMfoAhUQUhUIHYNMBuQQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=r+r+amponsah+detained+1959&f=false |page=50}}</ref> The former occupant of the seat; [[R. R. Amponsah]] fell victim to this fate as he was detained while being trialled at the time for allegedly plotting with M. K. Apaloo to overthrow Nkrumah.<ref name=\"SOLOMON BONSU\"/> He was appointed deputy minister for Justice in 1960<ref>{{cite journal |title=Departments of State, Justice, and Commerce, the Judiciary, and Related Agencies Appropriations for Fiscal Year 1968:\u00a0Hearings Before the Subcommittee ... Ninetieth Congress, First Session on H.R. 10345 | author=United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on Appropriations |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fBs3AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA194&dq=bonsu+deputy+justice&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN0Z_nhsfoAhXyt3EKHeiyAEYQ6AEIGTAA#v=onepage&q=bonsu+deputy+justice&f=false |page=194 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |date=1967 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Parliamentarian, Volumes 41-42 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=LEeNAAAAMAAJ&q=s+a+k+bonsu&dq=s+a+k+bonsu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-8_m2icfoAhXEo4sKHRFFBy4Q6AEIQDAG |page=343 |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1960 |journal=The Parliamentarian; Journal of the parliaments of the Commonwealth.}}</ref> and a year later, he was appointed Chief of State Protocol for the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]] when she visited [[Ghana]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/> Bonsu served as the deputy minister for Justice from 1960 to January 1965 when he was appointed Minister of Co-operatives by the then president Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/><ref>{{cite report |title=Daily Report, Foreign Radio Broadcasts, Issues 15-16|url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=14SS45Qw3vEC&pg=RA1-PA1&dq=bonsu+minister+of+cooperatives&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi3msq6hcfoAhUKRhUIHeOsCVwQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=bonsu+minister+of+cooperatives&f=false |publisher=United States. Central Intelligence Agency |page=I 1 |date=1965}}</ref> In June that same year, he was moved to head the Ministry of Pensions and National Insurance.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&dq=&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Antwi+bonsu |page=ii |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> A month later, he was made member of parliament for the Adotobri constituency.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&dq=&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Antwi+bonsu+adotobri |page=iv |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> He served in these capacities in the [[Nkrumah government]] until Nkrumah was overthrown in February 1966.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nkrumah government]]\n* [[List of MLAs elected in the 1956 Gold Coast legislative election]]\n* [[List of MPs elected in the 1965 Ghanaian parliamentary election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonsu, SolomonAntwi Kwaku}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 1956\u20131965]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 1965\u20131966]]\n[[Category:Convention People's Party (Ghana) politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ghanaian politicians]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian men]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Samuel Antwi Kwaku Bonsu\n|image = \n|image_size = \n|caption = \n|office1 = Minister of Pensions and National Insurance\n|term_start1 = July 1965\n|term_end1 = February 1966\n|president1 = Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n|predecessor1 = A. K. Onwona-Agyemang\n|successor1 = ''Ministry abolished''\n|office2 = Minister of Co-operatives\n|term_start2 = January 1965\n|term_end2 = July 1965\n|president2 = Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n|predecessor2 = ''New''\n|successor2 = Baffour Kwabena Senkyire<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Baffour+co-operative |page=ii |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref>\n|office4 = Member of Parliament<br>for Adotobri\n|term_start4 = June 1965\n|term_end4 = February 1966\n|predecessor4 = ''New''\n|successor4 = ''Consituency abolished''\n|majority4 = \n|office5 = Member of Parliament<br>for Sekyere West\n|term_start5 = 12 June 1959\n|term_end5 = June 1965\n|predecessor5 = [[R. R. Amponsah]]\n|successor5 = ''Consituency abolished''\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1921|11|1}}\n| birth_name = Solomon Antwi Kwaku Bonsu\n|birth_place = \n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|residence = \n|citizenship = Ghanaian\n|nationality = \n|fields = \n|workplaces = \n|alma_mater = [[Presbyterian College of Education,\u00a0Akropong]]\n|doctoral_advisor = \n|academic_advisors = \n|doctoral_students = \n|notable_students = \n|known_for = \n|influences = \n|influenced = \n|awards = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Samuel Antwi Kwaku Bonsu''' also known by the name '''Solomon Antwi Kwaku Bonsu''' was a [[Ghanaian]] [[politician]] in the [[Nkrumah government|first republic]]. He was the Minister of Co-operatives and later Minister of Pensions and National Insurance. He was also the member of parliament for the Sekyere West constituency from 1959 to 1965 and the member of parliament for the Adotobri constituency from 1965 to 1966.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBonsu was born on 21 November 1921 at Asante Mampong in the [[Ashanti Region]].<ref name=\"BONSU\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1966 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3hMOAQAAMAAJ&q=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&dq=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ8_T4isXoAhWFTRUIHWCBAYsQ6AEIOjAF |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=12 |date=1966 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref> After completing his Standard Seven, he entered the [[Presbyterian College of Education,\u00a0Akropong]] (then the Presbyterian Training Colloge, Akropong) where he obtained his Teachers' Certificate 'A'.<ref name=\"BONSU\"/> He later continued at the Theological Seminary at [[Akropong]] graduating in 1941.<ref name=\"BONSU\"/> In 1954 he studied to obtain his GCE\u00a0Advanced Level certificate prior to proceeding to the [[United Kingdom]] to study law at the [[Middle Temple]], [[London]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1966 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3hMOAQAAMAAJ&dq=Solomon+Antwi+Kwaku+Bonsu&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Legal+1959+deputy+protocol |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=12 |date=1966 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref> He was called to the bar as a barrister-at-law in 1957.<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/>\n\n==Career and politics==\nBonsu begun as a teacher at the [[Kumasi]] Presbyterian Middle School before joining the Kumasi branch of U. T. C. as a Departmental Store Manager.<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/>\n\nBonsu became a private legal pracitioner in 1959, and on 12 June that same year, he was sworn into office as the member parliament for the Sekyere West constituency.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=M_9HAQAAIAAJ&q=solomon+antwi+kwaku+bonsu+sekyere&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrsYz8pcfoAhVpVRUIHVwIAIcQ6AEIGTAA |page=94 |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1958 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> This was as a result of the seat being vacant due to a law in parliament at the time that deprived members of parliament of their seat if they were unable to be present in parliament for ten (10) consecutive days.<ref name=\"SOLOMON BONSU\">{{cite book |last=Asamoah |first=Obed |authorlink=Obed Asamoah |date=2014 |title=The Political History of Ghana (1950-2013): The Experience of a Non-Conformist |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=O28ZBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=r+r+amponsah+detained+1959&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAs4OerMfoAhUQUhUIHYNMBuQQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=r+r+amponsah+detained+1959&f=false |page=50}}</ref> The former occupant of the seat; [[R. R. Amponsah]] fell victim to this fate as he was detained while being trialled at the time for allegedly plotting with M. K. Apaloo to overthrow Nkrumah.<ref name=\"SOLOMON BONSU\"/> He was appointed deputy minister for Justice in 1960<ref>{{cite journal |title=Departments of State, Justice, and Commerce, the Judiciary, and Related Agencies Appropriations for Fiscal Year 1968:\u00a0Hearings Before the Subcommittee ... Ninetieth Congress, First Session on H.R. 10345 | author=United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on Appropriations |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fBs3AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA194&dq=bonsu+deputy+justice&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN0Z_nhsfoAhXyt3EKHeiyAEYQ6AEIGTAA#v=onepage&q=bonsu+deputy+justice&f=false |page=194 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |date=1967 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Parliamentarian, Volumes 41-42 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=LEeNAAAAMAAJ&q=s+a+k+bonsu&dq=s+a+k+bonsu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-8_m2icfoAhXEo4sKHRFFBy4Q6AEIQDAG |page=343 |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1960 |journal=The Parliamentarian; Journal of the parliaments of the Commonwealth.}}</ref> and a year later, he was appointed Chief of State Protocol for the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]] when she visited [[Ghana]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/> Bonsu served as a the deputy minister for Justice from 1960 to January 1965 when he was appointed Minister of Co-operatives by the then president Dr. [[Kwame Nkrumah]].<ref name=\"S. A. K. BONSU\"/><ref>{{cite report |title=Daily Report, Foreign Radio Broadcasts, Issues 15-16|url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=14SS45Qw3vEC&pg=RA1-PA1&dq=bonsu+minister+of+cooperatives&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi3msq6hcfoAhUKRhUIHeOsCVwQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=bonsu+minister+of+cooperatives&f=false |publisher=United States. Central Intelligence Agency |page=I 1 |date=1965}}</ref> In June that same year, he was moved to head the Ministry of Pensions and National Insurance.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&dq=&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Antwi+bonsu |page=ii |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> A month later, he was made member of parliament for the Adotobri constituency.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates; Official Report, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=fwpIAQAAIAAJ&dq=&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Antwi+bonsu+adotobri |page=iv |publisher=Ghana National Assembly |date=1965 |journal=Parliamentary Debates}}</ref> He served in these capacities in the [[Nkrumah government]] until Nkrumah was overthrown in February 1966.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nkrumah government]]\n* [[List of MLAs elected in the 1956 Gold Coast legislative election]]\n* [[List of MPs elected in the 1965 Ghanaian parliamentary election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonsu, SolomonAntwi Kwaku}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 1956\u20131965]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 1965\u20131966]]\n[[Category:Convention People's Party (Ghana) politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ghanaian politicians]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian men]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stray word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_Antwi_Kwaku_Bonsu"}
